<FIRST>d e BC-Ballet     07-03 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ballet,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kirov Ballet Opens with `Corsaire'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kirov Ballet from Leningrad, not seen here in
25 years, opened at the Metropolitan Opera with ``Le Corsaire,'' a
three-act spectacle with a story that doesn't make much sense but
with exciting virtuoso dancing.
   The Kirov, from Leningrad, is known as a company of great
dancers, floating with grace, in contrast to the more sturdy
athleticism of the Bolshoi Ballet of Moscow. That impression was
confirmed Monday night.
   ``Le Corsaire'' is known to most balletomanes only for the second
act's spectacular trio which Rudolf Nureyev, who defected from the
Kirov, translated into an exhilarating duet for himself and Dame
Margot Fonteyn.
   The full-length ballet dates from 1856 in Paris. It begins with a
shipwreck, with dramatic effects of a sailboat rocking wildly on a
stormy sea.
   Three shipwrecked pirates (corsaires) are found by two Greek
maidens. A slave trader, danced with brio by Konstantin Zakinsky,
captures the maids and one of them, danced by Yelena Pankova, is
sold to a doddering pasha for his harem. The other maiden, the star
of the ballet, danced by Altynai Asylmuratova, is rescued by one of
the pirates, danced by Yevgeni Neff.
   Miss Asylmuratova and Neff are costumed like princess and prince,
and on Monday they danced as regally as they were garbed.
   As much applause as they received, the dazzling Farukh Ruzimatov
received more. He dances the part Nureyev took with Dame Margot.
   The slave trader, captured by the pirates, escapes from them and
recaptures Miss Asylmuratova. Before the pirates finally free both
maidens, most of the third act is taken up with a trio of ballerinas
and the corps de ballet, fluffy in pink and led by Miss Pankova, as
fast and light as a sugarplum fairy. In an effect which no American
company would use, fountains play behind a silver-pink backdrop.
   The ballet's score, more prettified than distinguished, is put
together from music by five composers. The version the Kirov dances
has choreography by Marius Petipa as staged in 1955 by Pyotr Gusev.
   Miss Asylmuratova and Ruzimatov were guest artists of American
Ballet Theater here this past season.
   The Kirov performed in the United States in 1986, a tour which
did not include New York. The present tour has the company at the
Met July 3 through 22, Kennedy Center in Washington July 25 through
Aug. 6, the War Memorial Opera House in San Francisco Aug. 9 through
16 and Orange County Performing Arts Center in Costa Mesa, Calif.,
Aug. 18 through 27.
</TEXT>
