<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 2328EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CoalStrike     07-03 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coal Strike,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Sets July Fourth Rally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Tensions escalated Monday between striking coal miners and
company security forces in West Virginia and Kentucky.
   In West Virginia, miner Donald Hampton, 44, of Pemberton was
struck by a car driven by a security guard as the guard left an
Appalachian Mining site, said state police Sgt. J.L. Miller.
   Hampton was treated at Montgomery General Hospital and released.
   In Kentucky, Pike County officials agreed Monday to investigate
allegations that a private security firm is illegally patrolling
Pittston Coal Co. mines.
   More than 120 striking United Mine Workers and their supporters
packed into a Pike County Fiscal Court hearing to protest Vance
International Inc. security guards who first arrived at Eastern Coal
Corp. property on June 20.
   About 1,900 UMW members have been on strike at Pittston holdings
in West Virginia, Virginia and Kentucky since April 5. Sympathy
strikes by miners at other operations began June 12, and an
estimated 37,000 miners are off the job in eight states.
   About 12,000 to 15,000 miners were expected to attend a rally
Tuesday in Norton, Va., a UMW official said.
   The UMW also announced another rally would be held Saturday in
West Virginia, with 3,000 to 5,000 striking miners expected.
   Sen. Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va., said he's concerned about the
impact of the strike on foreign coal exports.
   Rockefeller, UMW President Richard Trumka and a coal operator yet
to be named will meet with Japanese steel officials in New York next
Monday to discuss the strike.
   ``We're going to go there and tell them we are still reliable
suppliers of coal,'' Rockefeller said.
   In other action Monday, U.S. District Judge Dennis Knapp
postponed until next week a hearing on what he will do if miners
don't obey a national order he issued last week prohibiting sympathy
strikers from engaging in strike-related activities. A majority of
the nation's miners are scheduled to end a two-week vacation period
next week.
</TEXT>
