<FIRST>u w AM-HUD-Probe     07-03 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD-Probe,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Program for Elderly Under Scrutiny</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A program which provides nursing homes and
other housing for the elderly is under scrutiny by federal
investigators, a senior Department of Housing and Urban Development
official said Monday.
   The department is reviewing an inspector general's audit of the
Retirement Service program and Secretary Jack Kemp could make
decisions about the program as early as next week, the official said.
   ``Nursing homes will probably be next,'' said the official,
citing Kemp actions to suspend or overhaul other department programs
in the wake of highly critical investigative audits by the inspector
general.
   The New York Times said in Tuesda editions the department is
considering proposals to overhaul or terminate the program which has
left the government liable for hundreds of millions of dollars in
mortgages on troubled housing projects for the elderly.
   The newspaper said half of the 24 projects in the Midwest that
were audited were in default or financial difficulty.
   ``I think it's premature what will be proposed,'' said the
official. ``That's Secretary Kemp's decision and he hasn't made it.''
   The official, who asked not to be identified, did not give an
estimate of possible government losses. However, ``anytime a
significant percentage of those projects are in default you begin to
wonder about the program,'' he said.
   Last week Kemp cancelled a mortgage insurance program after an
audit found 25 of 58 projects financed throught the program had
defaulted. The department estimated the outstanding debts would cost
the government $90 million.
   Other federal housing programs, including subsidies for
rehabilitation of housing for those with moderate incomes, a
coinsurance program and a program in which at least one private
escrow agent who handled sales of foreclosed property has admitted
stealing more than $5 million, are under investigation by Congress
and the Justice Department for mismanagement, political
influence-peddling and other abuse.
</TEXT>
