<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 2339EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-ArmedLawmaker     07-03 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Armed Lawmaker,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legislator Threatened By Extremists Carries A Pistol</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dovish Israeli legislator says he has started
to carry a pistol after being threatened by right-wing extremists
who oppose his views on the Israeli-Palestinian conflict.
   ``There are very specific threats, telephone calls, letters,
saying: `We shall kill you, we shall harm your family,''' Abraham
Burg of the Labor Party said in an interview on Monday.
   ``I live in a secluded place and I also travel a lot,'' Burg
said. ``Politically, I'm at the forefront of the struggle against
the radicals. That's why I'm carrying a pistol at all times.''
   The legislator would not reveal what type of pistol he carries or
when he purchased it.
   Burg, the son of a former interior and police minister, Yosef
Burg, belongs to the dovish wing of the center-left party and is
known as a supporter of a far-reaching territorial compromise as a
way of solving the Israeli-Palestinian conflict.
   He said that threats from right-wing extremists seem to be linked
to his frequent radio and television interviews, and that ``they
follow immediately.''
   Some of the callers, he said, have identified themselves as
belonging to the Sicarites, an extremist underground group named
after biblical Jewish assassins who killed collaborators with Rome
in the first century.
   The group has claimed responsibility for the submachine-gun
attack in April that left one Palestinian dead and three wounded
near Jerusalem's Old City, and for at least eight arson attacks on
apartments and cars belonging to left-wing Israelis.
   The daily Davar reported Monday that parliament's security
officer had decided to equip other left-wing legislators with guns
after they, too, have been threatened by extremists.
   It said some liberal legislators already carry weapons.
   Parliament spokeswoman Sara Yitzhaki refused comment on the
report.
   Burg confirmed that left-wing lawmakers have been threatened but
said he was not aware whether any of his 119 colleagues in the
Israeli parliament, or Knesset, carried a weapon.
</TEXT>
