<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 2348EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Abortion-States-2ndAdd     07-03 0903</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion-States - 2nd Add,0932</SECOND>
<HEAD>NORTH CAROLINA: is uncertain.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   NORTH DAKOTA: Laws require parental consent before unmarried
minors can receive abortions and bar state funding except when the
woman's life is endangered. A bill banning abortion was defeated in
the 1989 Legislature. Its sponsor, Rep. Kelly Shockman, D-LaMoure,
plans legislation in the 1991 session based on the Missouri decision.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   OHIO: Probibits the use of public funds for abortions unless the
abortion is necessary to protect a woman's physical or mental
health. Ohio's parental consent law was declared unconstitutional
and is awaiting review by the U.S. Supreme Court. Most polls
indicate a majority of legislators favor some restrictions on
abortions.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   OKLAHOMA: Still has a pre-1973 law on the books prohibiting
abortions. Lawmakers favor further restrictions on abortion.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   OREGON: Considered a pro-choice state, has no laws on the books
restricting availability or public funding of abortions. Legislative
leaders say changes in the law are unlikely, but abortion opponents
predicted after the Missouri ruling that abortion will be a major
and contentious issue in the 1991 Legislature.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   PENNSYLVANIA: Public funds are available only in cases of rape or
incest. Last year the Legislature approved a provision that would
require parental consent for a woman under 18 to have an abortion,
but that has been blocked by a court challenge. Gov. Robert P. Casey
has said he backs whatever restrictions on abortion the court will
allow; Republican anti-abortion Rep. Stephen Freind predicts
legislation based on the Missouri ruling.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   RHODE ISLAND: Requires doctor to receive a woman's written
consent before abortion. Courts have struck down provisions
requiring a waiting period, fetal description and criminal
sanctions. Minors must get parental consent or a court order before
undergoing an abortion. A 1975 law making it manslaughter to perform
an abortion on a fetus that is viable remains on the books but is
not enforced. A legislative fight over applying the restrictions of
the Missouri ruling is likely, but prospects are uncertain.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   SOUTH CAROLINA: Law requires unmarried minors under age 16 to get
parental consent. A third-trimester abortion requires the consent of
the woman, her husband, the attending physician and an independent
second physician. The legislative outlook for any cange is uncertain.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   SOUTH DAKOTA: A pre-1973 anti-abortion law remains on the books
but was tailored to allow the practice under federal guidelines
after Roe vs. Wade. A 1977 state law would forbid abortions if
allowed by federal law, imposing penalties of up to two years in
prison and a $2,000 fine. Gov. George Mickelson said the Missouri
decision could become an issue in the 1990 Legislature.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   TENNESSEE: Has a parental consent law requiring approval of a
court or both parents before a minor can get an abortion. She can
seek court permission if the parents refuse. Lawmakers favor some
restrictions; Gov. Ned McWherter opposes abortion. Abortion foes say
they will push abortion legislation in line with the Missouri
decision.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   TEXAS: Prohibits abortions after the point of viability of the
fetus, except in cases in which the woman's physical or mental
health would be in jeopardy or in cases of severe fetal abnormality.
The legislative outlook for change is uncertain.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   UTAH: Law requires that women be counseled on fetal development
and the possibility of adoption. The law also requires consent of
parents for minors and husbands for married women. Utah restricts
Medicaid funds for abortions unless a woman's life is threatened.
Legislators are overwhelmingly opposed to abortion. Gov. Norm
Bangerter agrees, except in cases of rape, incest or danger to the
mother's health. Legislation limiting abortion under the Missouri
ruling is expected.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   VERMONT: Has no laws restricting abortions. Gov. Madeleine Kunin
says she opposes abortion restrictions.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   VIRGINIA: No restrictions on abortions. Legislative efforts to
require parental notification have been defeated. Lawmakers predict
no changes in Virginia's abortion laws as a result of the Missouri
case.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WASHINGTON: A pre-1973 law permits abortions through the 16th
week of pregnancy, requires spousal consent if the two are living
together and requires women to have lived in the state 90 days in
order to get an abortion. The state provides money for poor women to
get abortions. Prospects for tougher laws are uncertain _ voters
defeated a 1984 initiative to ban state money for abortion and a
similar 1986 proposal lacked enough signatures to get on the ballot.
Gov. Booth Gardner is pro-choice.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WEST VIRGINIA: Law on the books makes all abortions felonies
except those performed in the case of medical emergencies. An
unmarried minor must notify her parents before having an abortion.
The Legislature is sharply divided on the issue of abortion and has
killed bills to halt state financing of abortions. Legislation based
on Supreme Court ruling is likely to be proposed.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WISCONSIN: Pre-1973 law still on the books prohibits abortions
except to save a woman's life. A 1985 law makes it a felony to abort
a viable fetus. Wisconsin prohibits public financing of abortions
unless a woman's life is threatened. The legislative outlook for
further restrictions is uncertain.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WYOMING: Requires minors to get parental consent or court
approval before getting abortions. An abortion performed after the
fetus is viable is unlawful except in cases in which a woman's life
is threatened. While Wyoming is traditionally a conservative state,
the Legislature appears split on the issue. Some lawmakers do expect
new restrictions based on the Missouri ruling.
</TEXT>
