<FIRST>r i PM-Ireland     07-03 0133</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ireland,0136</SECOND>
<HEAD>Haughey Given Three Days To Form a New Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament has given Charles Haughey three
days to form a new government. If he fails, political observers say
another general election seems certain.
   Haughey's Fianna Fail party failed by six seats to gain a
majority in the June 15 election. His minority government, elected
28 months ago, called the sudden election hoping to gain a majority
in the 166-seat Dail, or parliament.
   Haughey told the Dail on Monday that a new election was a
``Doomsday solution'' and asked for extra time to gather enough
backing for a fifth term as prime minister.
   Fianna Fail has governed Ireland for 44 of its 67 years as an
independent state but has not formed a single-party majority
government since 1977-81.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890703-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 0017EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-China 1stLd-Writethru a0682 07-03 0812</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0682,0836</SECOND>
<HEAD>United States Charges China Targeted Apartments In Shooting</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 20 grafs to UPDATE with U.S. charging diplomats'
apartments were deliberately targeted in shooting. Picks up 7th pvs, `Party
membership ...' EDITS therafter to trim. ^LaserPhotos BEJ1,3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Embassy charged Monday that Chinese
soliders targeted American diplomats' apartments when they opened
fire June 6 on a foreigners' housing complex, and said it was filing
a protest.
   The move was likely to worsen relations between the two
countries, already made tense by U.S. criticism of China's military
crackdown on the student-led pro-democracy movement.
   The shooting, in which hundreds of rounds of bullets were fired
into the Jianguomenwai apartment compound, came a day after the
State Department announced the embassy had given refuge to two
Chinese dissidents, Fang Lizhi and his wife, Li Shuxian.
   A U.S. Embassy report on the shooting, which charged
pre-meditation, did not link it with China's anger over U.S.
protection of Fang and Li.
   The United States filed one protest shortly after the shooting.
The new protest, in the form of a diplomatic note, challenges for
the first time the Chinese account that the soldiers were responding
to sniper fire from within the apartment compound.
   Radio Beijing said at the time that one soldier was killed and
three injured, and plainclothes officers who went into the compound
brought out a Chinese man they claimed was the sniper.
   No witnesses reported seeing Chinese soldiers hit.
   The U.S. Embassy report said the arrest appeared to be staged. It
also said the soldiers fired not only from the ground but from a
building across the street, where they had taken up positions the
day before.
   A diplomat from another Western country confirmed that some
bullets were fired from the opposite building and whizzed over the
heads of children who were playing on the floor in the foreigners'
apartments. He said the shooting appeared intended to intimidate
foreigners.
   No one was hurt, but most foreigners evacuated the compound later
that day.
   ``There is no doubt, in this embassy's opinion, that certain
apartments were deliberately targeted by the (army),'' the U.S.
Embassy report said.
   It said one U.S. defense attache's apartment was hit by 18
bullets. Ten other U.S. diplomats' apartments also were hit.
   Chinese guards stationed outside the U.S. Embassy, who normally
carry only revolvers, were armed Monday with long-barreled automatic
pistols and wore military helmets for the third straight day.
   The guards appeared in the new gear Saturday, when the embassy
held an Independence Day party for American residents in Beijing.
   One guard said they would maintain their tighter security through
Tuesday, which is America's Independence Day, but refused to explain
why.'
   On Sunday, the first tourists were allowed to enter central
Beijing's Tiananmen Square since the army seized it June 3-4 and
drove out pro-democracy protesters, killing hundreds of unarmed
civilians.
   A bus was driven onto the square early Sunday and about a dozen
foreigners climbed out. Authorities said groups with advance army
permission would be allowed to visit the vast square, but it
remained closed to the general public.
   The assault on Tiananmen began the crackdown on the student-led
movement for a freer society. Authorities have since arrested more
than 1,800 people and announced 27 executions.
   One student said Sunday that he and many others still were
stunned by the violence. The government says up to 300 people died
in the crackdown. Chinese witnesses and Western intelligence sources
say up to 3,000 were killed.
   The student, who did not want his name used, gazed at the square
from behind a gate and said that despite their horror at the
crackdown, many of his peers still want to join ruling Communist
Party to further their careers and were quietly accepting the
government line that troops were needed to quell the protests.
   Party membership ``means the person was good in school, is in
good health, has the right thoughts and is likely to move ahead in
the world,'' the student said.
   But the highly publicized party pledges to clean up its act
indicated the party is aware of deep popular discontent.
   Television news reported that three party members from a Beijing
suburb were sentenced to prison terms of one to 10 years for
accepting bribes in their capacity as factory managers. A Shanghai
legislator was sentenced to eight years for taking bribes, according
to the report.
   It did not say if they were expelled from the party.
   Widespread corruption has destroyed public trust in leaders, and
the students gained broad popular support for demanding an end to
corruption during the seven weeks of protests.
   Over the past few years, the party announced several
anti-corruption campaigns followed by arrests. But no top-level
leaders were prosecuted, and many Chinese said the campaigns only
highlighted the extent of corruption.
</TEXT>
