<FIRST>r a PM-Names     07-03 0879</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Names,0913</SECOND>
<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American pianist Van Cliburn drew bravos and even
screams when he repeated the spectacular performance of
Tchaikovsky's Piano Concerto No. 1, which launched his career three
decades ago.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and his wife, Raisa, joined in the
standing ovation Sunday night in Tchaikovsky Hall and later
expressed their enjoyment privately in a 35-minute meeting backstage
with Cliburn.
   Before playing, Cliburn told the 1,500 people packed into the
hall, ``For 31 years, I have felt like I had two homes. I will soon
be asking permission from your distinguished President Gorbachev to
buy an apartment in Moscow. I will be coming for much-needed visits
for my music, for my soul, to Russia and to Moscow.''
   Cliburn, 54, of Fort Worth, Texas, said the Soviet leader told
him he would help arrange the apartment.
   Sunday was Cliburn's third public performance in 11 years. He
came out of retirement to play for the Gorbachevs at the White House
in 1987. He was to play tonight at the Tchaikovsky Conservatory, on
the same stage where he won the Tchaikovsky Competition for young
pianists in 1958.
   In addition to the Tchaikovsky, Cliburn performed Liszt's Piano
Concerto No. 1, a Debussy prelude and the Schumann-Liszt Widmung.
   ``He played like a god,'' said Dallas Morning News critic John
Ardoin, who flew to Moscow to review the performance. ``I don't see
how anyone under this pressure and much emotion could play like he
did.''
