<FIRST>r a AM-PlaneCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0777 07-03 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plane Crash, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0777,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fiery Plane Crash Engulfs 2 Mobile Homes; One Dies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf with 1 graf to UPDATE with spokeswoman saying
no one was in the trailers; SUBS next-to-last graf to CORRECT spelling
of victim to Burrow, sted Borrow and provide his hometown</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANGEL FIRE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small plane crashed into two mobile
homes and exploded in flames shortly after takeoff from this resort
town Sunday. All four people aboard were burned, one fatally.
   No one was in the trailers, Colfax County sheriff's dispatcher
Pat Osterman said.
   The plane failed to gain altitude after takeoff from Angel Fire
Airport at 3:30 p.m., Mrs. Osterman said. Eyewitnesses reported the
plane was 35 to 40 feet off the ground as it passed over the golf
course.
   ``It went into the trees, hit two mobile homes and was engulfed
in flames,'' Mrs. Osterman said. ``The aircraft and mobile homes
were destroyed.''
   She said all four people were able to get out of the plane, but
one woman fell into some burning fuel and was killed.
   The dead woman's identity was not immediately known, she said.
   The pilot, Paul Fitch, 45, of Phoenix suffered third-degree burns
over 65 percent of his body and was in critical condition at
University of New Mexico Hospital burn center in Albuquerque, said
emergency room nurse Lisa Paddock.
   The other passengers, Fitch's wife, Cathy, and John Burrow, 24,
of Tolleson, Ariz., had similar burns over 40 percent of their
bodies, Mrs. Osterman said. Their conditions were not immediately
known.
   The ski resort of Angel Fire is 20 miles east of Taos and 40
miles south of the Colorado state line.
