<FIRST>r i PM-Mexico-TwoMayors     07-03 0667</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Two Mayors,0689</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fed Up With Governing Party, This Town Installed A Mayor Of Its Own</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Mexico-Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHERAN, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This Indian town in the mountains of
western Mexico has one working public telephone, four polling places
and two mayors.
   One chief executive represents the Institutional Revolutionary
Party, or PRI, which has run Mexico for 60 years. The other
represents the deep gulf between the PRI and much of the state of
Michoacan.
   Together, the two men show why Sunday's state assembly election
is seen as a key test for the PRI, whose authority has seriously
eroded.
   People in this town of 30,000, 175 miles west of Mexico City,
take their franchise seriously and believe it has been long been
systematically violated by the PRI.
   Emboldened by the opposition sweep of Michoacan in national
elections last year, they occupied city hall in December, demanding
that then-Mayor Octavio Rios be replaced.
   Most Cheran residents are Purepeche Indians, but Rios is not a
Purepeche and is not from Cheran and many said he had been imposed
from outside.
   In February, they held a town assembly and chose Dr. Alberto
Munoz, a Purepeche local, as their mayor.
   The quiet rebellion got the attention of the PRI-dominated state
government. Within weeks, the state assembly named a new mayor, also
a Purepeche from Cheran.
   ``That made people even madder,'' said poll watcher Jose
Velazquez, as a cluster of women in the region's distinctive black
and indigo shawls lined up at a ballot box Sunday under a steady
drizzle.
   The new PRI mayor, Manuel Santa Clara, came out to vote Sunday as
well. Volunteer poll watchers said it was a rare public appearance
for a man the citizens refuse to acknowledge.
   ``I don't go sometimes,'' Santa Clara admitted in an interview at
his home, where a rickety table on the patio serves as his office.
``It's not because I'm afraid. It's because I don't want to provoke
people.''
   Santa Clara said Munoz's government is collecting proper state
and federal taxes and sending them to the state capital in Morelia.
Constituents say the Munoz-run public services have been operating.
   Munoz, assisted by the town's tradition of communal labor, has
even launched some small water projects with funds donated by
constituents.
   But Santa Clara said he has custody of the mayoral stationery,
the city treasury and budget and the official rubber stamps and
seals. He dismisses Munoz's role.
   ``All he has is city hall. And city hall is just a building,''
Santa Clara said.
   For many Michoacanos, city hall has became an important symbol of
their discontent and their support for the opposition Democratic
Revolutionary Party.
   In December, 50 of the state's 113 city halls were occupied.
Several are still padlocked and at least three other towns have
parallel governments like that of Cheran.
   Munoz was out of town Sunday, but fellow citizens were eager to
talk about Cheran's exercise in improvised democracy.
   Santa Clara ``has the money, the backing of the government, but
he doesn't have the support of the people,'' said Velazquez.
   The PRI admits the 1988 elections showed the government it has
run for three generations had alientated the people of Michoacan,
where leftist candidate Cuauhtemoc Cardenas soundly beat the PRI's
Carlos Salinas de Gortari.
   A massive public works program was launched and for the first
time local party congresses were held to nominate candidates for the
state assembly race.
   ``They have ignored us for years,'' one of Velazquez' fellow poll
watchers said. His weathered face creased into a smile. ``Now,
suddenly we're important.''
   ``They want to recoup the government,'' Velazquez. ``But the
people don't want the PRI.''
   The new PRI mayor brought in a shipment of pipe for a water
project to be built with communal labor, but Cheran's people scorned
it. Huge piles of pipe lie under the arches at city hall.
   Michoacan holds mayoral elections in December. The people of
Cheran will have another chance to go to the polls.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
