<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 0117EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Budget     07-03 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Going Slow: Congress Inches Toward Implementing 1990 Budget</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly a month and a half after Congress
whisked through a $1.17 trillion budget for fiscal 1990, the pace of
implementing the plan is slackening and its weakest links show signs
of unraveling.
   Pivotal lawmakers voice optimism that by the Oct. 1 start of the
new fiscal year, the package of spending and deficit-cutting bills
needed to implement the budget will be in place.
   The goal is a projected shortfall below the $100 billion target
mandated in the Gramm-Rudman deficit reduction law.
   But questions remain about where $5.3 billion in new tax receipts
sought in the fiscal blueprint will come from.
   Also unclear is how, and even whether, some of the rest of $28
billion in savings claimed in the budget will be achieved at all.
   Rep. Bill Frenzel of Minnesota, ranking Republican on the House
Budget Committee, complained last week to a reporter that some
committees view cuts ``with a jaundiced eye and a cavalier manner. I
think we'll have difficulty with some of them.''
   The overall budget resolution for fiscal 1990 was approved May
18, the earliest date in a decade.
   But lawmakers now must approve other bills to carry out the
budget. Thirteen measures disperse money among federal agencies, and
another contains new taxes and spending cuts.
   The work on those 14 bills has gone slowly. And though Oct. 1
seems far off, Congress' generous summer recesses leave it with only
about eight weeks of work left until then.
   The House last week approved one of the 13 spending bills, an
$18.5 billion measure for science and water programs. House leaders
hope to complete the other 12 by the end of the first week in
August. The Senate has not begun to consider any of the spending
bills.
   Last year the House had completed all 13 spending measures by
June 30 and the Senate had disposed of four.
   Problems are arising, however, as lawmakers put together a plan
for cutbacks in Medicare, farm initiatives and other benefit
programs.
   Some of the savings are easy. Congress will save $1.7 billion by
simply declaring that the money-losing Postal Service is considered
``off-budget.''
   Other choices are tougher, such as the need to find $5.3 billion
in new tax collections.
   House Ways and Means Chairman Dan Rostenkowski considered
agreeing to a cut in the capital gains tax sought by President Bush,
who contends it would increase government collections by stimulating
the economy.
   But the Illinois Democrat abandoned that idea last week and said
he will instead tinker with a number of narrow tax provisions, such
as halting a tax break that encourages banks to lend money to
developing countries.
   It is unclear how such a tax package would be treated by Bush,
who has promised to reject any new taxes this year.
   Rostenkowski's panel also last week approved nearly $3 billion
worth of reductions in the growth of the Medicare program for the
elderly.
   But decisions by a host of other House committees remain to be
made. Among them are requirements for the Post Office and Civil
Service Committee and the Agriculture Committee to each save $1.1
billion, the Veterans Affairs panel to slash $666 million, and the
Merchant Marine Committee to find $200 million in cuts.
   ``We've been doing this for eight years and we've cut all the
easy stuff,'' said one committee aide, asking to not be identified.
``We're down to muscle and bones.''
   A crucial hurdle looms July 15, when the White House's Office of
Management and Budget collects data on the economy. A slow economy
boosts the deficit by cutting tax collections and increasing the
government's tab for unemployment and other support programs. This
could require Congress to find even more budget savings than
anticipated to reach the $100 billion deficit target.
</TEXT>
