<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 0154EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-RiverFreeway Bjt   07-03 0641</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-River Freeway, Bjt,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>California Aqueducts Viewed as `Safety Valve' For Heavy Traffic</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUE MANNING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Traffic here has gotten so bad that officials
are discussing using the 500 miles of flood control channels as
part-time freeways.
   Promoters think Los Angeles County's concrete waterways are a
congestion reliever. Detractors say if you see aqua, duck.
   It's an idea that has surfaced from time to time during the past
20 years, always to be scuttled because of better options, says Jim
Sims, director of transportation programs for the county
transportation department.
   ``Now, we're at the point that we may be running out of
attractive alternatives. And we may be at the point where we could
live with something we can't use all the time,'' Sims said.
   ``In the past it hasn't been shown to be feasible,'' said Kathy
Delegal, spokeswoman for the county's Department of Public Works,
which maintains the channels. But traffic congestion has worsened,
so ``it should be looked at again,'' she said. ``We're open-minded.''
   All agree that traffic in Los Angeles County is on the brink of
busting through its barriers. Of the 10 busiest freeway interchanges
in the United States, six are in the county and two are in
neighboring Orange County, according to the state Department of
Transportation.
   The nation's busiest interchange is the West Los Angeles junction
of the Santa Monica and San Diego freeways, used by about 513,000
vehicles daily.
   The Los Angeles County Transportation Commission's newly approved
budget includes $100,000 for a feasibility study on channel
conversions. The study is to be completed early next year and will
focus only on engineering and hydrology.
   Environmental concerns, safety and other barriers would be
considered if the engineering feasibility is positive, Sims said.
For example, the impact of an oil or diesel fuel spill on the harbor
most be reviewed.
   One of the channels targeted for possible conversion is the Los
Angeles River, largely paved over in the 1950s. It starts where the
Calabasas and Bell creeks come together in the San Fernando Valley,
passes east of downtown and heads to the harbor, Ms. Delegal said.
In sections, it ranges from 45 feet to 160 feet across and is
between 30 and 40 feet deep, she said.
   The channel often is used by police and the Rapid Transit
District for driver training. Movie studios use it for location
shooting.
   ``They like it for car chases,'' said Jean Granucci of the
Department of Public Works.
   Sims said the channels would be used by specialized
transportation, trucks, car pools or van pools. ``Obviously, it
wouldn't be usable 365 days a year,'' he said.
   Deputy Mayor Mike Gage called the concept ``ludicrous'' and said
Mayor Tom Bradley would prefer to see the channels used for rafting
and swimming.
   State Assemblyman Richard Katz criticized Bradley for rejecting
the idea so quickly.
   ``Unlike people at City Hall, I don't profess to know the answers
until I get the facts,'' he said. ``The whole point of the study is
to find out what will work.''
   Sims said ramps with gates would have to be built for the
part-time freeways, and plans devised ``to clear people out when it
rains.''
   KNX-AM traffic reporter Bill Keene likes the idea. ``It's great
if the weather stays decent,'' he said. He suggested the waterways
be turned over to trucks since they ``are responsible for 33 percent
of our accidents and 66 percent of our major tieups.''
   But the flood control channel conversion is not the ultimate
answer, Sims cautioned: ``We are trying to look at every idea we can
to reduce congestion _ including ideas that haven't been thought of
before.''
   Among the other options authorities have studied are double-deck
freeways; commuter and Metro rails; and in-vehicle television
screens that show congestion and suggest alternate routes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
