<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 0214EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Eastern     07-03 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Increases Flights, Continental Offers Special Fare</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines has nearly tripled its flights in a
move that was met with outrage from union workers who have been on
strike against the carrier for four months.
   ``Fly Cheap. Die Cheap,'' about 100 striking pilots yelled Sunday
at the first Eastern passengers to fly out of Fort Lauderdale since
the strike began.
   ``Our purpose is to get the public aware of our problems and to
let them know we are still on strike,'' said Robert Fay, a pilot for
32 years. ``We're not here for greed. We're here on principle.''
   In San Francisco, one of the cities where service resumed, 300
striking machinists and pilots formed a line passengers had to push
through.
   At Hartsfield Atlanta International Airport, passengers crowded
Eastern's gates.
   ``It gives you an uneasy feeling to walk across a picket line,''
said Jeff Handler, who passed through Hartsfield on his way from
Sarasota to Greenville, S.C. He noted his tickets cost $79 each way,
much less than fares of competing airlines.
   ``Such is life,'' he said, smiling as he made his way through the
crowded concourse.
   In all, Eastern increased its scheduled daily flights to 225 from
80, serving 49 cities instead of 27. The move was in line with a
rebuilding plan the carrier has submitted to U.S. bankruptcy court.
Eastern filed for bankruptcy reorganization March 9, five days after
the strike began.
   Also Sunday, Continental Airlines, which like Eastern is also
owned by Texas Air Corp., announced $76 one-way fares on U.S.
flights for three days following the Fourth of July holiday. United
Airlines plans to match the offer, said United spokesman Joseph
Hopkins.
   Before the Machinists union strike, Miami-based Eastern operated
1,040 daily flights to 102 cities and had 30,000 employees.
   Currently, Eastern is operating with about 8,000 employees,
including 300 pilots who did not honor the strike and 150 new pilots
recruited and trained since the strike began. About 550 other pilots
are in training, and a recruiting drive continues, said Eastern
spokesman Robin Matell said.
   By December, Eastern plans to reach its goal of 800 flights a day
serving 77 cities, Matell said.
   ``Everything is going as planned _ we're right on target to come
back strong,'' he said.
   ``The only thing you might notice is some gray hair in the
cockpit,'' Matell said, noting the average age of its new hires is
about 40. ``These guys are older and they have more experience.''
   Air Line Pilots Association spokesman L.D. Williams said
Eastern's decision to increase its flights is unsafe because of the
shortage of qualified pilots.
   ``They're not able to get enough qualified people to replace us
and they're not going to be around for the amount of time it takes
to do that,'' Williams said. ``They have lowered their standards.
They are desperate for pilots.''
   Matell said passenger traffic on the new flights has been strong.
   ``We've been offering comeback fares, real bargains, and the
public has been gobbling them up,'' the spokesman said.
   Houston-based Continental is offering the $76 one-way fare on all
of the carrier's flights in the U.S. mainland where seats are
available for trips beginning Thursday, Friday or Saturday.
   Continental's sale fare requires no advance purchase, but it must
be bought within 24 hours of the time the reservation is made.
Travelers may return as early as Sunday, or can stay as long as they
like.
</TEXT>
