<DOCNO> AP890703-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 0309EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     07-03 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ambassadorial Nomination of Frederick Bush In `Deep Trouble'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's nomination of his chief
political fund-raiser to be U.S. ambassador to Luxembourg is in
``deep trouble'' because of the man's involvement in the Housing and
Urban Development scandal, says Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole.
   ``I would guess it may be a while before he goes to Luxembourg,''
Dole said Sunday, referring to Frederick M. Bush, who is no relation
to the president but was finance director for both his 1980 and 1988
presidential campaigns.
   ``And if he goes, it may just be as a visitor,'' Dole quipped,
speaking on CBS' ``Face the Nation'' program,
   Frederick Bush was questioned extensively last Thursday and in
May by the House Government Operations Committee about hundreds of
thousands of dollars in consultant fees which his lobbying firm,
Bush &amp; Co., reaped in 1986 and 1987 for HUD projects in Puerto Rico.
   Frederick Bush acknowledged in his testimony that he had
contacted political appointees at HUD. But he said he did not feel
his campaign efforts on behalf of George Bush or his job as deputy
director of the vice president's staff from 1982 to 1984 gave him
``political influence'' with HUD officials.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Thornburgh Requests List of Convicted Flag Burners</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh says he has
directed the Justice Department to compile a list of federal
prisoners convicted of burning the U.S. flag in anticipation that a
recent Supreme Court decision will lead to their freedom.
   ``If someone is entitled to relief, then all are entitled to
relief,'' Thornburgh said. The court's 5-4 decision in a Texas case
said flag burning is a constitutionally protected form of political
protest.
   Thornburgh said, however, that he doubted that more than ``a
handful'' of federal prisoners are involved.
   Thornburgh made the comments on ABC-TV's ``This Week With David
Brinkley'' in response to a question about Carlos Mendoza-Lugo, a
Puerto Rican nationalist now at the U.S. penitentiary in Atlanta.
   Mendoza-Lugo, who was given a one-year prison sentence after
pleading guilty to a federal charge of flag desecration, last week
filed a petition in U.S. District Court for his release.
   ``My expectation is that he probably will be entitled to that
relief,'' Thornburgh said of Mendoza-Lugo, who burned a U.S. flag
two years ago in front of a U.S. Post Office as a protest for Puerto
Rican independence.
</TEXT>
