<DOCNO> AP890703-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 0402EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a ImeldaMarcos:Ferdinand'sLifeIsBestBirthdayPresent     07-03
0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>Imelda Marcos: Ferdinand's Life Is Best Birthday Present</SECOND>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto HU1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ousted Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos
granted his wife's wish that he live to see her 60th birthday but
remained in critical condition with massive organ failure.
   ``I thank Ferdinand for this beautiful gift, his great strength
of spirit, that strength will help me carry this burden,'' Imelda
Marcos said on her birthday Sunday, after a Roman Catholic Mass at
the couple's home-in-exile.
   Marcos, 71, was battling widespread infection and was being kept
alive by machines at St. Francis Medical Center, where he has been
hospitalized since January.
   The hospital said his condition essentially was unchanged since a
failed transplanted kidney was removed Thursday. Aides said Marcos'
fever had subsided and that while lapsing in and out of
consciousness he seemed to recognize his wife.
   About 75 people attended the Mass, held under a white canopy in
the backyard of the hillside home overlooking downtown Honolulu and
the Pacific.
   Mrs. Marcos, wearing a red dress with a blue and white scarf and
black sunglasses, was greeted with traditional Hawaiian leis and
several dozen red roses, balloons and a large arrangement of
Hawaiian flowers.
   She was joined by her children, Irene Araneta, who lives near San
Francisco, and Ferdinand Jr., commonly known as ``Bong Bong.''
   Mrs. Marcos said she remained optimistic that Marcos would
recover. She promised she would never remove him from the
life-support equipment.
   She was less hopeful that Philippine President Corazon Aquino
would relent in her refusal to permit Marcos to come home to die.
   Mrs. Aquino accuses the Marcoses of stealing billions of dollars
during his 20-year rule.
   ``As long as there is life, there is hope,'' Mrs. Marcos said.
``I am no longer optimistic in Mrs. Aquino, but I'm so blessed that
Ferdinand is still around.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
