<SECOND>PM-BRF--Beach Brawl,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fraternity Party Ends in Violence on N.Y. Beach</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WANTAGH, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A huge beach party involving a college
fraternity ended in violence that left three men shot, one stabbed
and 11 people under arrest, police said.
   The most seriously wounded from Saturday's violence at Jones
Beach State Park was a 22-year-old New York City man listed in
critical condition, authorities said.
   Saturday's party drew at least 12,000 people, many members of the
Omega Psi Phi fraternity, said state police Lt. Stephen Kowal.
   The group has gathered without permits at the beach during recent
Independence Day weekends, said Kowal.
   ``There's a lot of drinking, and we suspect probably a lot of
drugs. ... It usually ends up in fights breaking out between the
groups,'' said Kowal, who was hospitalized after a 1986 brawl
involving the fraternity.
   Saturday night's violence was sparked by two separate
confrontations, Kowal said.
   The first was an argument that left two men shot; the second
started when a car was blocking traffic, police said.
