<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--FlagCuts     07-03 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Flag Cuts,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Use Hair to Protest Supreme Court Decision</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PN1 of July 2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MESA, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four teen-agers are using their heads as a
visual protest against the U.S. Supreme Court's decision to allow
flag burning as a form of political protest.
   The four, all military-bound, had a barber sculpt Old Glory,
stars and letters into their flattop haircuts.
   ``I've been in the ROTC for three years, and with the flag
burning they've been doing, it goes against many things I've
learned,'' said 17-year-old Bob Arens, who will join the Army next
month.
   ``If you're going to burn your flag, you're going to burn your
freedoms, too.''
   Joining Arens were fellow ROTC members Michael Revel, 18, Brian
``Biff'' Mitchell, 16, and Bill Hancotte, 18. They all said that
flag burning should not have First Amendment protection.
   ``The flag is our national symbol and should be treated with
respect,'' said Mitchell, who went home with a large star on the
left side of his head.
   ``Getting the haircut was kind of a patriotic thing to do.''
</TEXT>
