<DOCNO> AP890703-0050 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 0522EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     07-03 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls, Stocks Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against the Japanese yen and the
Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index rose sharply today despite a big
setback for Japan's governing Liberal Democratic Party in Tokyo
elections.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which fell 7.62
points last Friday, rose 287.73 points, or 0.87 percent, closing at
33,236.42.
   The dollar closed at 142.50 yen, down 1.45 yen from Friday's
close of 143.95 yen. It opened at 144.75 yen and fluctuated between
142.50 yen and 144.90 yen.
   The dollar rose in the morning on news that the opposition
parties were pulling ahead in vote counting from Sunday's Tokyo
metropolitan election.
   But it fell sharply in the afternoon, confounding expectations
that a defeat for the pro-business LDP would hurt the yen.
   ``To a certain extent, markets predicted last week that the LDP
would be defeated _ from the LDP defeat in Niigata (parliamentary
by-election) _ and people bought dollars and sold yen,'' said
Sumitomo Bank's Toshiaki Kakimoto.
   ``People say that the market is unstable before you know the
result, but it quiets down once the result comes in,'' he added in
explanation of today's turnabout for the dollar.
   Kakimoto also said the Bank of Japan had intervened heavily,
selling an estimated $500 million to 600 million in the morning and
another $200 million to $300 million in the afternoon.
   ``The Bank of Japan forced the dollar down. They seem to feel
that the 140-yen range is not favorable for the United States,'' he
said.
   ``They also probably wanted to prevent the yen from going too
low, which might happen in overseas markets if the Bank of Japan
decided not to intervene,'' Kakimoto added.
   On the stock market, an analyst at Nomura Securities, who spoke
on condition of anonymity, said the markets may have been reacting
positively to the LDP's defeat.
   ``The political issues didn't revolve around whether the LDP was
bad or whether Japanese democracy was no good; rather, they focused
on common sense and morality issues,'' he said.
   With a humbler LDP government, ``it may be possible to have
discussions on whether, for instance, the consumption tax is
favorable,'' he added.
   But the analyst said the fundamental problems of the United
States' economic slowdown and lower interest rates still were
affecting the stock market.
   Steel issues were the only stocks to receive particular attention
today, he added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
