<FIRST>r i PM-Gromyko-Callaghan     07-03 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gromyko-Callaghan,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Prime Minister Recalls Gromyko as Tough Negotiator</HEAD>
<UNK>With PM-Obit-Gromyko</UNK>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lord Callaghan, the former British prime minister
and foreign secretary, today remembered Andrei A. Gromyko as a tough
negotiator who softened toward the end of his tenure in the Soviet
leadership.
   ``He was a good executor of a bad foreign policy that has now
changed,'' said Callaghan, who, as James Callaghan was foreign
secretary in a Labor government from 1974-76 and prime minister from
1976-79.
   Callaghan said Gromyko, the longtime Soviet diplomat, foreign
minister and president, was ``a very hard man to negotiate with.''
   ``He represented Soviet foreign policy at a time when it was
expansionist and dogmatic,'' he said. ``Toward the end of his
period, especially as president, he softened and I was astonished
when he described me as a good friend.''
   Callaghan said that in private, Gromyko ``could relax and unbend.
He and his wife had a love of art and they particularly wanted to
see the Tate Gallery when he came to London to study the works being
displayed there.''
   Gromyko died Sunday at age 79.
</TEXT>
