<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Torrential Rains, Tornadoes in Louisiana and Texas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms raked Louisiana and Texas today, and a front
drenched parts of South Dakota, Minnesota and Wisconsin.
   Showers and thunderstorms associated with the low pressure center
which once was Tropical Storm Allison were scattered from Alabama
and Georgia to Indiana and Ohio.
   Thunderstorms in Louisiana spawned tornadoes that damaged a home
in Alexandria and destroyed a business at Deville. Strong winds
downed trees and power lines around the state and knocked mobile
homes off their moorings.
   Thunderstorms moving southward across the eastern half of Texas
spattered golf ball-size hail in Wise and Tarrant counties, with
winds blowing down trees, tearing the roof off a building at Coleman
and raring up to 90 mph in the Dallas area.
   Hail the size of baseballs thumped Dorset, Minn., on Sunday
night, generated by storms that developed ahead of a cold front in
the north-central region. Twisters were reported near Nevis, Pine
River and Motley, and high winds downed trees at Grand Rapids, Minn.
   Today's forecast was for scattered showers and thunderstorms in
Texas, with heavier showers and thunderstorms in Louisiana and
Mississippi.
   A flash flood watch was in effect today for northwestern Georgia,
much of Alabama, and southeastern Mississippi.
   Heavy rainfall totals for the six hours ending at 2 a.m. EDT
included 2.6 inches at Dallas, 1.32 inches at Fort Polk, La., and an
inch at Evansville, Ind.
   For Monday, showers and thunderstorms were forecast from
southeastern Illinois across the Ohio Valley, in the western
Carolinas, and from Georgia to Louisiana and Florida.
   High temperatures were expected to be in the upper 60s and 70s
over the Pacific Northwest; near 90 degrees from southern New York
along the Atlantic Coast to Florida and the Mississippi Valley,
North Dakota and Montana; the 90s and above over the rest of the
Plains and the Rockies; from 100 to near 110 degrees over Texas' Rio
Grande Valley, and as high as 115 degrees or more through the desert
Southwest. Highs over the remainder of the nation were expected to
be in the 80s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 47
degrees at Yellowstone Park, Wyo., to to 93 degrees at Phoenix.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 71 cloudy; Boston 70 fair; Buffalo 61 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 75 cloudy; Cincinnati 66 foggy; Cleveland 73 foggy;
Detroit 72 hazy; Miami 77 fair; New York 73 fair; Philadelphia 72
fair; Pittsburgh 70 hazy; Portland, Me. 65 fair; Washington 73
cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 65 fair; Chicago 72 hazy; Dallas-Fort Worth 73
cloudy; Denver 80 windy; Des Moines 72 hazy; Indianapolis 65 rain;
Kansas City 72 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 79 partly cloudy;
Nashville 77 partly cloudy; New Orleans 78 partly cloudy; St. Louis
69 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 82 windy; Anchorage 71 partly cloudy; Las
Vegas 84 fair; Los Angeles 64 fair; Phoenix 95 fair; Salt Lake City
74 fair; San Diego 65 fair; San Francisco 60 windy; Seattle 59 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 68 fair; Toronto 64 fair.
</TEXT>
