<FIRST>r i PM-NorthernIreland     07-03 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northern Ireland,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Bombs Explode at Airport, Attack Claimed for IRA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three bombs exploded at
Belfast's Harbor Airport early today, damaging two commuter aircraft
but causing no injuries, police said.
   An anonymous caller to a Belfast radio station said the Irish
Republican Army planted the bombs. He used a codeword to
authenticate the claim and said a fuller statement would be made
later.
   One blast damaged the undercarriages of two aircraft parked on
the tarmac, while two others exploded near the air traffic control
tower and on the airfield, said police Sgt. Freddie Handley.
   The airport received a telephone warning eight minutes before the
first bomb went off, police said.
   The aircraft, a Shorts 360-300 and a Shorts 330, are both
twin-turboprop passenger planes built by Short Brothers Ltd., an
aircraft and missile maker. It is being sold to Canada's Bombardier
Inc., an aerospace company.
   The state-owned Short Brothers, Northern Ireland's biggest
employer, owns Harbor Airport, the second largest in the British
province. Located on the capital's north side, it operates domestic
flights to mainland Britain and the Irish Republic.
