<FIRST>r a PM-OilSpill     07-03 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Spill,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tanker Journeys to Drydock Nine Days After Spill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Greek tanker that ran aground and spilled
420,000 gallons of heating oil off Rhode Island limped into New York
waters today for repairs.
   The World Prodigy, escorted by a tugboat with pollution gear
aboard, awaited high tide outside New York Harbor to enter a
drydock, said Coast Guard Petty Officer Wayne Wertz.
   Coast Guardsmen watching the ship from the air reported no oil
leaking, said Wertz. The vessel was carrying nearly 8 million
gallons of oil at the time of the accident, but most of it was
pumped out immediately afterward.
   The tanker, which hit a reef June 23 at the mouth of Narragansett
Bay, left Sunday under Coast Guard escort, moving under its own
power at a slow 7{ knots because of holes in the hull. The Coast
Guard vessels eventually dropped back.
   The captain, Iakovos Georgudis, was at the helm. He faces federal
pollution charges after admitting he entered the bay without a
harbor pilot on board.
   A Coast Guard marine safety officer also rode on the bridge.
   ``I'm glad to see it's gone,'' said Joseph Sweetland, a Sunday
beach visitor. ``There's a lot better view out here and with that
thing sitting out there, anything could happen, I guess.''
