<FIRST>r a PM-AIDSDayCare     07-03 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS Day Care,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Day Care Center for AIDS Victims to Open</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A day-care center for adults with AIDS opens
this fall, offering medical attention as well as classes and other
activities for people who might otherwise be stuck at home or put in
the hospital.
   ``I'm looking forward to it as a place to get out of the house,''
said Keith Permenter, 32, who quit as an assistant administrator at
a law firm because of AIDS-releated illness. ``I want to take art
classes. You can only watch so much daytime television, and you get
tired of talking to the dog.''
   The Continuum HIV Day Services, set to open in September near
City Hall, will offer at least 75 people an alternative to more
expensive institutions such as nursing homes and hospitals.
   Adult day-care centers have been springing up across the country
in the past decade, but most focus on the elderly. Medical advances
are allowing people with AIDS to live longer, turning the disease
into a long-term, chronic illness similar to ailments effecting the
elderly.
   Both groups often require constant supervision because of
dementia, which may cause victims to become forgetful and combative.
   The center, which will be open to people who have recently tested
positive for the AIDS virus as well as those with AIDS or
AIDS-related illness, received a $200,000 state grant and a $150,000
city contract financed with federal tax dollars.
   Private donations, fees from clients and medical insurance also
will help pay bills.
</TEXT>
