<FIRST>r i PM-Greece     07-03 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Greece,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Greek Parliament Sworn in Without Papandreou</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deputies in a new Parliament controlled by
a coalition of leftists and conservatives were sworn in today and
were expected to plan an investigation of financial scandals in
former Premier Andreas Papandreou's government.
   Papandreou, whose Panhellenic Socialist Movement finished second
in the June 18 parliamentary elections, did not attend the ceremony.
   His successor, Tzannis Tzannetakis, and the new 22-member Cabinet
attended.
   The government, formed Sunday after a pact between the
conservatives and a Communist-led alliance, ended a political
impasse after no party won a majority in Parliament in elections
June 18.
   The leftists and conservatives say they will govern together for
three months to begin investigations of a series of financial
scandals under Papandreou.
   He did not attend the ceremony, despite an announcement last week
that he would be well enough to go. As a party leader, he
automatically won back his seat in the Parliament and will lead the
opposition.
   Papandreou, 70, is recovering from pneumonia and kidney failure
at the Athens General State Hospital.
   In the new one-chamber Parliament, the conservative New Democracy
has 145 seats and the Coalition of the Left and Progress holds 28
seats.
   Papandreou's Panhellenic Socialist Movement, with 125 seats, did
not participate in the government.
   The other two seats are held by a minor party and an independent.
   The Parliament's leadership will be elected Tuesday. The chamber
is then expected to begin procedures for prosecuting Socialist
members accused of involvement in financial scandals.
</TEXT>
