<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 0847EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-GromykoProfile     07-03 0757</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gromyko Profile,0777</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gromyko: A Symbol of Soviet Stoicness for Decades</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Obit-Gromyko</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Andrei A. Gromyko's unsmiling countenance and
staunch, party line positions personified the Soviet Union for
nearly three decades.
   The 79-year-old former foreign minister, whose death was
announced today, lived only nine months after being retired from the
largely ceremonial presidency to make way for Mikhail S. Gorbachev,
the Communist Party chief who wanted to turn the job into a powerful
post.
   But the man known to Western diplomats as ``Old Stoneface,''
``Mr. Nyet'' and ``Grim Grom'' paved the way for Soviet leaders to
make a graceful exit. Until Gromyko left the ruling Politburo with
official praise on Sept. 30 and was retired the next day from the
presidency, most senior Soviet officials either died in office or
fell from power into obscurity.
   Gromyko's stature was confirmed today when Gorbachev announced
his death to the legislature, the Supreme Soviet, and deputies stood
in unison for a moment of silence.
   Gromyko died 16 days shy of his 80th birthday.
   One of the best-remembered pictures of him was one of the last.
He sat amid members of the ruling Communist Party Politburo, the
only person not casting an affirmative vote for his removal from the
presidency. He abstained.
   Gromyko appeared again in public in January to attend a
conference of Americans, Soviets and Cubans who were involved in the
1962 Cuban missile crisis.
   Two days before the crisis erupted, Gromyko calmly told President
John F. Kennedy the Soviets had no missiles in Cuba. At the
conference in January, other Soviet officials disclosed that
one-third of the Kremlin's nuclear arsenal was deployed in Cuba at
the time, with another third aboard ships bound for the island 90
miles off Florida.
   Although he served nearly four years as president, providing a
visible symbol of continuity as Gorbachev overhauled the Soviet
leadership and bureaucracy, Gromyko was best known outside the
Soviet Union as his government's career foreign policy chief.
   Born July 18, 1909, into a Byelorussian peasant family, Andrei
Andreyevich Gromyko joined the Communist Party as a young man and
rose quickly through government ranks.
   He served every leader from Josef Stalin to Gorbachev. He dealt
with hundreds of foreign officials whose faces changed with the
world order after World War II, and he was regarded as a skillful
spokesman for his country's interests.
   Gromyko was respected by those who faced him across the
bargaining table for his ability to enunciate his government's
policy and for his voluminous knowledge of historical detail. But
his stubborn refusal to bend on key issues frustrated adversaries,
who sometimes blamed him for blocking arms control by walking away
from the table.
   After joining the Foreign Ministry and being posted to Washington
after the outbreak of World War II, Gromyko rose quickly to the rank
of ambassador to the United States and was named his country's first
permanent representative to the United Nations in 1946.
   During the world body's formative years, he earned the nickname
``Mr. Nyet'' for the 26 vetoes he cast in the Security Council.
   Nikita Khrushchev, who elevated Gromyko to foreign minister, told
the United Nations the man was so loyal he would drop his pants and
sit on a block of ice if ordered him to do so. Gromyko sat
impassively as Khrushchev spoke, as he did again several years later
when Khrushchev startled the U.N. General Assembly by pounding a
shoe on his desk. There have been reports the infamous shoe was not
Khrushchev's but Gromyko's.
   Gromyko was a player in every superpower confrontation for more
than a quarter-century but rarely shared his private side. His
memoirs, published after he left the Foreign Ministry, were most
notable for their lack of spicy detail.
   Although he was generally regarded as a Communist Party
hard-liner, Gromyko nominated the relatively youthful reformer,
Gorbachev, to take over the Soviet leadership in March 1985.
   And although Gorbachev then removed Gromyko from the foreign
minister's post he had held 26 years, Gromyko continued to serve in
a visible role as chairman of the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet,
which made him head of state, the equivalent of president.
   Gromyko's advancing age and Gorbachev's announcement in June 1988
that he planned to create a strong presidency as part of an overhaul
of the Soviet political structure made Gromyko's replacement
inevitable.
   He said he was sad to leave.
   ``Age is a stubborn thing,'' the veteran Communist said in a
televised statement on the night his retirement was announced.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
