<FIRST>r w PM-Baker-Asia 1stLd-Writethru a0450 07-03 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baker-Asia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0450,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Heads for Tokyo Meeting on Philippines Aid</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Top 2 grafs new with Baker leaving; picks up 3rd graf pvs, The
program.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III left for
Japan today and talks with officials from other nations on a
proposed $2 billion-a-year aid and investment package for the
Philippines.
   Baker was to discuss in Tokyo the five-year aid program, which is
designed to help the Philippines' young democracy overcome economic
backwardness and a determined leftist guerrilla movement.
   The program envisions $1 billion a year in economic aid from a
variety of donors over the next five years, plus a similar amount in
private investment.
   The United States is seeking $200 million from Congress as its
contribution to the program. Combined with other programs, the
administration is asking a total of $658.6 million for the
Philippines for the next fiscal year.
   Representatives from the European Economic Community, Canada,
Australia and other nations also are attending the meeting, which is
being convened by the World Bank.
   The three-day meeting opened today, and Baker will spend 22 hours
in Tokyo before heading for a meeting in Brunei.
   Brunei is the site of the annual meeting of foreign ministers of
Southeast Asian Nations, informally known as ASEAN. As is customary,
the U.S. secretary of state and other interested parties from
outside the six-member ASEAN group hold consultations at the
conclusion of the ministerial meeting.
   Former Secretary of State George P. Shultz attended six of the
so-called post-ministerial ASEAN conferences.
   Baker will spend two days in Brunei, focussing on the prospects
for peace in Cambodia. The meeting could help determine whether a
negotiated settlement among rival factions in Cambodia is possible
after the expected completion of the withdrawal of Vietnamese forces
in September.
   Another topic on the agenda in Brunei is the evolving situation
in China and the political and economic fallout of last month's
crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators.
   ASEAN's members are the Philippines, Indonesia, Thailand,
Singapore, Malaysia and Brunei.
   Baker then heads for Poland, where he will link up with President
Bush at the start of his four-nation visit to Europe, highlighted by
the economic summit meeting next week in Paris.
   En route to Poland, Baker will spend a day and a half in the
Arabian Peninsula country of Oman. There he will confer with
officials of the Oman government, with which the United States has
had close ties, and rest up for his visit to Europe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
