<FIRST>u i PM-China 1stLd-Writethru a0492 07-03 0818</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0492,0844</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Embassy Protests Over Attack at Diplomatic Quarters</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads throughout to UPDATE with five arrests, Taiwan calling
for reporter's release. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEJ1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Embassy filed a protest today over what
it called a premeditated army attack on apartments of American
diplomats and other foreigners last month.
   The protest is likely to further worsen relations already made
tense by U.S. criticism of China's crackdown on unarmed
pro-democracy protesters.
   Also today, two Taiwanese reporters said a colleague was taken
away by security forces after he reportedly met with fugitive
student leader Wang Dan. The reporters said they feared Wang also
was arrested.
   The evening television news reported five people have been
arrested, including three students, allegedly for stealing a
submachine gun from an army vehicle during the first days of the
crackdown. Four other people turned themselves in for stealing army
guns and were released, the report said.
   U.S. Embassy spokesman Sheridan Bell said Charge d'Affaires
Raymond Burghardt delivered the protest note to the Foreign
Ministry, which did not respond immediately.
   Chinese soldiers fired into Jianguomenwai apartment compound on
June 6, a day after the State Department said the U.S. Embassy had
given refuge to two Chinese dissidents, Fang Lizhi and his wife, Li
Shuxian.
   A U.S. Embassy report charged the shooting was premeditated but
did not link it to China's anger over U.S. protection of Fang and Li.
   The United States filed one protest shortly after the shooting.
The new protest challenges for the first time the Chinese account
that soldiers were responding to sniper fire from within the
apartment compound.
   At the time, Radio Beijing said one soldier was killed and three
were injured, and plainclothes officers who went into the compound
brought out a Chinese man they claimed was the sniper.
   No witnesses reported seeing Chinese soldiers hit, however.
   The U.S. report said the arrest appeared to have been staged. It
also said the soldiers fired not only from the ground but from a
building across the street, where they had taken up positions the
day before.
   A diplomat from another Western country, speaking on condition of
anonymity, confirmed that some bullets were fired from the opposite
building and whizzed over the heads of children playing in the
foreigners' apartments. No one was hurt, but most foreigners
evacuated the compound later that day.
   ``There is no doubt, in this embassy's opinion, that certain
apartments were deliberately targeted,'' the U.S. report said.
   It said one U.S. defense attache's apartment was hit by 18
bullets. Ten other U.S. diplomats' apartments also were hit, as were
apartments of other nationals such as Spaniards.
   Shortly after the shooting, the European Economic Community asked
the Chinese government for an explanation, but received no response.
   China has agreed to pay for damage caused by the shooting.
   The Bush administration, in other responses to the Chinese
crackdown, has criticized it and cut off military aid.
   Wang, a history student at Beijing University, was a leader of
seven weeks of student-led protests in Beijing for a freer society.
He went underground after the army crushed the protests on June 3-4,
killing hundreds of unarmed civilians.
   Wang's name appeared on a list of 21 students wanted by police.
   Antonio Jiang, a reporter for Taiwan's Journalist Weekly, said
security officials searched Taiwan Independence Morning Post
reporter Huang Teh-Pei's hotel room at 3 a.m. today.
   Police grabbed him as he left his hotel just before noon and
pushed him into an unmarked car.
   Huang reported that he met with Wang on Sunday and was driving in
the Post's car when they realized they were being followed,
according to Jiang. Huang got out, and the driver left with Wang.
The driver has not returned, Jiang said.
   Beijing police and the city government Foreign Affairs Office
said they did not know if Wang was arrested. Jiang said police
denied any knowledge about Huang.
   Taiwan government spokesman Shaw Yu-ming urged Beijing to expel
Huang, as it has Western reporters who interviewed pro-democracy
students.
   Chinese guards stationed outside the U.S. and Australian
embassies, who normally carry only revolvers, were armed today with
long-barreled automatic pistols and wore military helmets for a
third straight day. Extra uniformed and plainclothers guards also
were posted.
   The guards refused to explain their new gear, which may be linked
to the presence of Fang and Li at the U.S. Embassy and unconfirmed
reports the Australians also were sheltering fugitives.
   In other developments, China's official newspapers gave over most
of their front pages today to pictures and biographies of 10 young
officers and soldiers killed during the June 3-4 attack.
   Senior leader Deng Xiaoping gave them the title ``guardian of the
People's Republic of China,'' which Western diplomats said they
believed was a newly created honor.
   The government said the 10 were beaten or burned to death by
protesters.
</TEXT>
