<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 0933EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Italy-Kidnapping     07-03 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Italy-Kidnapping,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kidnappers Send Hostage's Ear to Press for Ransom</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kidnappers holding a wealthy landowner sent one of
the victim's ears to a Rome newspaper with a message purportedly
from the captive saying, ``Please pay, they're not joking.''
   The macabre package received Sunday night also included a
photograph showing 64-year-old Marzio Perrini with one of his ears
mutilated, police said.
   The Italian news agency ANSA said the ear was sent to scientists
for examination but that investigators had no doubts it came from
the kidnapping victim.
   The kidnappers who snatched Perrini on Dec. 28 from his estate
near Brindisi have reportedly demanded $7 million for his freedom.
   The cutting off of an ear is a technique used in the past by
Calabrian kidnapping gangs to show they mean business.
   In 1973, the kidnappers of J. Paul Getty III, grandson of the
late U.S. oil billionaire, cut off one of his ears and sent it to a
Rome newspaper. He was freed after a reported payment of $2.7
million.
   The newspaper Giornale D`Italia said an unidentified man called
the paper Sunday and told it to pick up a package containing a
letter from Perrini at a post office box.
</TEXT>
