<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 1005EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Deaths SUB a0498 07-03 0161</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deaths, SUB, a0498,0162</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last item to CORRECT to Alva sted Alba in overline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Alva Sole</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alva Sole, a U.S. Airmail Service pioneer
who delivered mail to Franklin D. Roosevelt and was a friend of
World War I ace Eddie Rickenbacker, died Thursday at age 99.
   Sole was born in Wheeling, W.Va., and as a teen-ager went to work
shoveling coal on a train. He landed a job as a mail clerk on a
train and worked his way up to become head of the postal service's
Atlanta office in 1933.
   In air mail's infancy, Sole would swoop down, aim his
canvas-covered biplane at two posts on the ground, fly between them
and snatch a mail pouch from a wire stretched overhead before
climbing back into the air.
   Highlights of Sole's career included flying mail to Roosevelt at
Warm Springs, Ga., and taking Roosevelt's son Elliott on flights. He
flew planes with Will Rogers.
</TEXT>
