<DOCNO> AP890703-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 1018EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-VincennesAnniversary     07-03 0591</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vincennes Anniversary,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airport Renamed After Airbus Tragedy; Papers Attack U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranians today gathered at Bandar Abbas
Airport to remember 290 people killed one year ago when the U.S.
Navy shot down a civilian jet moments after it left the city, Tehran
Radio reported.
   The director of Civil Aviation announced that the airport, where
the ill-fated flight originated, had been renamed The International
Airport of the Tir 12 Martyrs, after the date of the incident.
   According to the lunar Persian calendar, Tir 12 last year
coincided with July 3, 1988, the day the USS Vincennes mistook Iran
Air Flight 655 for an Iranian fighter plane coming in for an attack
and shot it down.
   Newspaper editorials today called the incident ``a crime,'' or an
act of ``terrorism.''
   The jetliner was on a commercial flight from Bandar Abbas, where
a large air base is located, to Dubai in the United Arab Emirates.
   The majority of passengers aboard the A300 Airbus were Iranians.
All 290 people aboard died.
   Relatives of the victims, clergymen, and air force and civil
aviation officials attended the airport ceremony, Tehran Radio said.
It did not provide a crowd estimate.
   The broadcast, monitored in Nicosia, said the civil aviation
director, Mohammad Nabi Habibi, unveiled a painting depicting the
incident and displayed what he said were several parts of the
aircraft pulled from the Persian Gulf.
   ``The martyrs of this incident were another group of innocent
people who fell victims to American atrocities,'' he said.
   The daily Abrar, in an editorial carried by IRNA and monitored in
Nicosia, said: ``The Iranian nation will never forget U.S. crimes.''
   ``This has kindled a fire in the heart of the Iranian nation
which would not be extinguished without the elimination of U.S.
criminals,'' it said.
   The English-Language Kayhan International said the Iran Air
tragedy ``proved that Tehran's relations with Washington are
irreparable.''
   ``Those who feel the situation may change in the near future are
advised to go through the pictures of mutilated bodies of Iranians
on board the Airbus,'' it said in an editorial.
   More than 200 relatives of the Iran Air tragedy are suing
designers and manufacturers of the ship's radar system, a spokesman
for the group said Sunday in Abu Dhabi.
   Nagib Ghafoor, spokesman for the Flight 655 Litigation Group,
said the suit was filed June 28 in U.S. District Court in San
Francisco on behalf of relatives of 83 of the victims.
   Pentagon analysts have said that split-second decisions aboard
the Vincennes were affected by the inability of radar operators to
immediately match the plane's radar trace with digital direction,
altitude and speed information displayed on another screen.
   Ghafoor said the suit was filed against the General Electric Co.
``and other entities which designed and manufactured the radar
equipment on board the USS Vincennes.''
   Ghafoor said the complaint charged that the radar equipment
indicated the aircraft approaching the Vincennes was an F-14 diving
in an attack mode rather than the Iran Air flight, which was
climbing.
   He said claims against the United States on behalf of the
families ``are in the process of being filed as well.''
   GE is based in Fairfield, Conn. It refused comment Sunday, saying
it had not seen the suit.
   The Iranian government has been seeking a World Court verdict
against the United States and demanded financial compensation for
the dead. Washington has indicated it is willing to pay compensation
to victims' families but wants to be sure no money goes to the
Iranian government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
