<FIRST>u a PM-Obit-Schaffner 1stLd-Writethru a0475 07-03 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Schaffner, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0475,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>Academy-Award Winning Director Franklin J. Schaffner Dies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `Schaffner received..', to CORRECT that his films
received 28 Oscar nominations, sted Schaffner himself.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Director Franklin J. Schaffner, whose
1970 movie ``Patton'' won best picture and six other Oscars, has
died. He was 69.
   Schaffner, who during a four-decade career also directed such
popular films as ``Planet of the Apes'' and ``Papillon,'' died of
cancer Sunday at his Santa Monica home.
   He had just completed ``Welcome Home'' for Columbia Pictures,
said publicist Michael Roth.
   ``Patton'' star George C. Scott refused to accept the Oscar he
won for best actor for his portrayal of the World War II Gen. George
S. Patton, saying the awards demeaned the profession.
   But Schaffner, who won best director for the movie, said, ``I
will gladly accept any honors from the academy.''
   Films by Schaffner received 28 Academy Award nominations.
   He also was producer and past president of the Directors Guild of
America.
   His television career included more than 150 live CBS plays for
programs including ``Studio One'' and ``Ford Theatre.''
   He won Emmy awards for directing in 1954, 1955 and 1962, and
directed the first six episodes of ``The Defenders,'' a television
courtroom drama that began in 1961 and starred E.G. Marshall and
Robert Reed.
   Schaffner was born in Tokyo to Protestant missionaries. He was
raised in Lancaster, Pa., and graduated from Franklin &amp; Marshall
College in Pennsylvania.
   He had planned to study law, but joined the Navy during World War
II, serving four years as a lieutenant.
   As a news and public affairs director for CBS after the war, he
covered events that ranged from Brooklyn Dodgers baseball games in
1948 to the national election conventions of 1948 and 1952.
   He directed such TV series as ``Person To Person'' for Edward R.
Murrow and Jacqueline Kennedy's ``A Tour Of The White House.''
   Schaffner's first full-length film feature was ``The Stripper,''
released in 1962 and starring Gypsy Rose Lee and Joanne Woodward.
   His 1973 ``Papillon'' starred Steve McQueen and Dustin Hoffman;
the 1968 science fiction film ``Planet of the Apes,'' starred
Charlton Heston and Roddy McDowall. He also directed ``The Boys from
Brazil,'' 1978, with Gregory Peck.
   His other films included Gore Vidal's ``The Best Man,'' 1964,
starring Henry Fonda; ``The War Lord,'' 1965; ``The Double Man,''
1968; ``Nicholas And Alexandra,'' 1971; ``Islands In The Stream,''
1977; ``Sphinx,'' 1981; ``Yes, Giorgio,'' 1982; and ``Lionheart,''
in 1987.
   Schaffner is survived by his wife, Jean, two daughters and two
sisters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
