<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 1033EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Afghanistan     07-03 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moslem Rebels Reject Arafat's Peace Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan rebels today rejected a
Palestine Liberation Organization plan for ending the country's
civil war and blasted the plan's architect, Yasser Arafat.
   Qaribur Rehman Saeed, director of the rebel-controlled Afghan
News Agency, said the PLO chief ``is not the person to mediate. He
has been supporting the Kabul government for 10 years.''
   Saeed said none of the seven rebel parties, based in Pakistan,
supports Arafat's plan, which calls for a cease-fire and talks
between the U.S.-backed Moslem guerrillas and President Najib's
government. The talks would be followed by elections.
   ``The mujahedeen don't want to talk to Najib, and they don't like
Arafat,'' said Saeed. Afghan guerrillas call themselves mujahedeen
or Islamic holy warriors.
   Arafat is reportedly going to the Afghan capital on Thursday to
speak with Najib.
   The guerrillas have been fighting to oust Afghanistan's
pro-Soviet government for 11 years. The Soviet army fought alongside
Afghan troops for nine years but pulled the last of its soldiers out
of the country in February in accordance with a U.N.-mediated accord.
   The guerrillas have refused to deal with Najib.
   The Afghan government said Sunday that rebels are mobilizing
fighters around Kabul and may be planning an assault on the Afghan
capital. The military was placed on maximum alert in and around the
city.
   ``We are watching the situation very closely. We will wait until
the last moment. If they try to mount a military assault, we will
give them a befitting reply,'' said Lt. Gen. Abdul Haq Olumi, the
top military man in the ruling People's Democratic Party of
Afghanistan.
   Olumi refused to give details of the reported mobilization. ``We
will tell you after we win the battle,'' said the 49-year-old
general.
   ``We do not want bloodshed,'' Olumi said. ``We want to fight for
peace now.'' But he said soldiers would ``fight to their last blood
and sweat'' to defeat the guerrillas.
   Olumi also claimed that 15,000 guerrillas had been killed in
fighting since the Soviet Union withdrawal was completed. It was the
first time since February the government released rebel casualty
figures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
