<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 1050EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Israel     07-03 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jerusalem May Says Arabs of Jerusalem Should Vote in Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Teddy Kollek says the 140,000 Arabs in
Jerusalem should participate in any elections held to choose
Palestinians to negotiate the future of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   ``We must accept that the Arabs of east Jerusalem see themselves
as Palestinians,'' Kollek was quoted as saying over the weekend by
his spokeswoman, Bonnie Boxer.
   A showdown over the election issue is expected Wednesday in the
right-wing Likud bloc. Party rebels have said they will force Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir to amend his election plan to exclude Arabs
in east Jerusalem from voting.
   Under Shamir's plan, the vote would be followed by negotiations
between the Palestinians elected and Israeli officials on the future
of the occupied territories. However, the plan rules out creation of
an independent Palestinian state.
   ``I think the anger and hostility we would provoke by denying
Jerusalem Arabs the opportunity to participate in the proposed
elections is far more ominous than any supposed danger from their
joining a democratic process,'' Kollek, 78, a member of the
left-leaning Labor Party, was quoted as saying.
   But right-wingers say Israel would weaken its claim to
sovereignty over all of the city by allowing participation of
residents of the eastern sector of Jerusalem, which was captured
from Jordan in the 1967 war.
   Most residents of east Jerusalem have Jordanian citizenship but
are permanent residents of Israel and carry Israeli identity cards.
They are allowed to vote in city elections but not national
balloting in Israel.
   ``What the Israeli government is proposing now is elections to
choose Palestinian Arab leaders to negotiate with Israel on the
shaping of the Palestinian future,'' said Kollek.
   ``The Arabs of Jerusalem clearly deserve the opportunity to share
in the decison-making process. This is no way prejudices Israel
sovereignty in united Jerusalem,'' he said.
</TEXT>
