<FIRST>u w PM-Scotus-Abortion-Scene     07-03 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Abortion-Scene,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cries of Triumph, Groans of Anguish After Abortion Decision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On the steamy marble plaza facing the Supreme
Court today, there were cries of triumph, groans of anguish.
   But for once those favoring abortion and those fervently against
it appeared to agree.
   The Supreme Court had just given the pro-life movement a major
boost.
   ``I think it's a serious setback for us,'' said former
congresswoman Bella Abzug, a pro-abortion advocate.
   ``This is a creeping invasion, a creeping invasion of women's
rights, that's what it is,'' she said.
   ``It was a major victory for the pro-life movement,'' said Tom
Glessner, executive director of the Christian Action Council.
   The moment of decision, shortly after 10 a.m., brought a
momentary silence to the plaza, a momentary quieting of the
competitive chanting.
   Men and women in dark suits feverishly turned the pages of the
court's decision in ``William Webster, Attorney General of Missouri,
et al vs. Reproductive Health Services et al.''
   ``I'm not clear what happened, exactly,'' said a young woman in
purple shorts.
   ``I'm trying to figure this out,'' said a young man. ``I want to
read it in the paper tomorrow.''
   But then the approximate meaning of the decision, giving states
more power to limit abortion rights but stopping short of
overturning the landmark Roe vs. Wade pro-abortion decision, began
to take hold.
   The chanting began again.
   ``Not the courts, not the states, women will decide our fate,''
shouted the group of 50 or so pro-abortion demonstrators on the
broad sidewalk facing the court's Roman-temple facade.
   ``Ah, too bad,'' a teen-ager gloated. ``You guys lost.''
   ``What does this mean?'' someone asked Molly Yard, president of
the National Organization for Women.
   ``It means if you've got money you can get an abortion,'' she
said. ``If you're poor, too bad, you're down the drain.''
   ``What do you do now?''
   ``There are lots of things we can do,'' she said as she marched
through a forest of microphones and television cameras. ``We're
going to mobilize all over the country.''
   The Pro- and anti-abortion demonstrators _ they numbered about
200 _ tried unsuccessfully to drown each other out.
   ``Hey, hey, ho, ho, Roe vs. Wade has got to go.''
   ``One, two, three, four, abortion rights for rich and poor. Five,
six, seven, eight, separation church and state.''
   A bearded man, wearing the brown robe of a Catholic friar, knelt
on the sidewalk, fingering the beads of a long rosary. A sign held
above his head read, ``The baby had no choice.''
   To his left, a competing sign: ``Keep abortion legal.''
   Across the plaza, organizers of both groups _ pro-life and
pro-choice _ talked about next time.
   More abortion cases will be argued before the court this fall and
both sides said they saw opportunity and hope in that.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
