<FIRST>u i PM-Salvador     07-03 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leftist Guerrillas Attack Salvadoran Military Post</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas today opened
fire with automatic weapons and rocket-propelled grenades on a
military guard post. One attacker was killed in the fighting.
   Mauricio Gutierrez Castro, the new chief justice of the Supreme
Court, said he was also slightly injured in a rebel attack Sunday
evening as he was driving back from a nearby beach with his family.
   The body of a slain guerrilla was seen lying on the road near
where the 30-minute gun battle took place at dawn. The rebel
appeared to be the only casualty of the fighting.
   No government troops here hurt, the armed forces press office
said in a news release. The military post guards the entrance of a
San Salvador residential neighborhood where many army officers live.
   Appearing on a television news show early today, Gutierrez said
his car and a second vehicle with bodyguards were caught at a
roadblock the guerrillas had set about 10 miles south of San
Salvador.
   The bodyguards in the second vehicle opened fire when they saw
the road blocked by a parked bus, and the guerrillas waiting in
ambush fired back. One bodyguard was killed and another wounded,
Gutierrez said.
   Gutierrez said his driver made a quick U-turn and drove away from
the fighting. One bullet scraped the back of the justice's neck.
   ``I don't think it was an attack on me personally,'' Gutierrez
said, adding that the rebels ``had no way of knowing I would be
travelling on that road.''
   Gutierrez, a conservative, was named chief justice June 27,
shortly after the new administration of President Alfreo Cristiani
took office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
