<FIRST>r i PM-BoatPeople     07-03 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boat People,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S Ships Land 92 Vietnemese Boat People in Thailand</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 90 Vietnamese boat people
picked up by two U.S Navy warships were transferred to refugee camps
in Thailand today, a Thai official said.
   In another rescue, a U.S.-registered tanker picked up 133
Vietnamese refugees drifting Sunday in a wooden boat in the South
China Sea off Vietnam, Japan's coast guard said. The tanker Aries is
expected to drop off the refugees in Japan on Thursday, it said.
   A U.S. Embassy spokesman in Bangkok said the 92 Vietnamese
boarded the cruiser Reeves and the destroyer Fife about 370 miles
east of Vietnam on Thursday, when the warships were headed for a
routine stop in Thailand.
   The U.S. vessels decided to pick up the Vietnamese after judging
that the refugees' two vessels lacked sufficient food, water and
navigational equipment to continue their voyage, embassy spokesman
Neil Klopfenstein said.
   Praphakorn Smiti, head of the Operations Center for Displaced
Persons in Thailand, said the boat people were interviewed and
allowed ashore today.
   They were taken to Ban Thad, he said. It is a refugee camp 60
miles east of Bangkok run by the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees.
   At the camp, the Vietnamese will be screened to assess whether
are fleeing political persecution or seeking better living
conditions, Praphakorn said.
   Thailand and other Asian nations swamped by an unrelenting influx
of Vietnamese refugees want to repatriate those who are not
political refugees. But Vietnam has said it will not accept back
people who flee their impoverished country to seek better lifestyles.
   Between January and May, according to U.N. figures, 1,429
Vietnamese boat people arrived in Thailand. As of May 31, there were
13,470 Vietnamese in camps in Thailand, of whom 11,068 arrived by
boat. Many of the refugees want to settle in the United States.
 
</TEXT>
