<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Taxes     07-03 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Taxes,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Court Orders Reargument of State Taxing Powers Cases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today ordered reargument in
its next term of an important battle over state taxing powers.
   The justices will hear arguments over related cases from Arkansas
and Florida when they return to the bench in October for their
1989-90 term.
   Rulings in the two cases are likely sometime next year.
   At issue is whether a business that successfully challenges a
state tax as an undue burden on interstate commerce is entitled to
be refunded money it paid before the tax was invalidated.
   The court announced today that it will broaden its inquiry next
term. The court said it also will consider whether a state _ rather
than refund tax revenues to those hurt by discriminatory levies _
may retroactively raise taxes of those who benefited from the
discrimination.
   In the Arkansas case, trucking companies are seeking $160 million
in tax refunds after the state Supreme Court declared the state's
mileage-based tax on trucks unconstitutional.
   The state court based its ruling on a 1987 ruling by the nation's
highest court that struck down a similar tax in Pennsylvania.
   The Arkansas court ordered state officials to pay $4.9 million in
refunds from a special escrow account created in the summer of 1987.
But the state court said the trucking companies are not entitled to
additional refunds on taxes the state collected before the escrow
account was created.
   In the Florida case, a state tax that granted an exemption to
in-state liquor dealers was struck down. Out-of-state dealers then
sought refunds on the money they had paid under the tax.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890703-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 1141EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-Abortion-Weddington     07-03 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Weddington,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Roe Attorney Disappointed by Court Decision</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Ms. Weddington has scheduled a 1 p.m. EDT news conference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLEY SHANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The attorney who successfully argued the Roe vs.
Wade case said she was disappointed by the Supreme Court's ruling
today that gives states greater power to limit abortions.
   The new ruling ``could eventually lead to abortion being almost,
if not actually, illegal in at least some states and maybe many of
the states,'' said Sarah Weddington, reached by telephone shortly
after the court's decision was announced.
   ``I've invested 20 years of my life in this and now have been
handed a major defeat,'' she said.
   Ms. Weddington represented Norma McCorvey, a Dallas woman who
took the pseudonym Jane Roe, in the landmark 1973 abortion case
establishing women's constitutional right to abortions.
   The court today, in a series of mostly 5-4 votes, restored
several Missouri abortion regulations that a lower court had
invalidated for unduly interfering with women's constitutional right
to abortion.
   She predicted the decision will not immediately affect women
seeking abortions ``until state legislatures pass new laws.''
   But the Austin, Texas, attorney said the decision signals a
``major change in direction'' for the court.
   ``Roe vs. Wade basically said that there is a right of privacy in
the Constitution that allows women to make certain choices for
themselves and one of those was the choice of whether to continue or
terminate a pregnancy,'' she said.
   ``While the Supreme Court did not say there is no right of
privacy, they didn't say `we think there is' or `we think there
isn't.' What they said was, `We're going to allow the states to
regulate in major ways.'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890703-0092 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 1142EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Scotus-School     07-03 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-School,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Agrees To Review Law In Omaha Religion Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to review a 1984
federal law requiring that student religious groups be given the
same access as other extra-curricular clubs to public high school
facilities.
   The justices, setting the stage for an important ruling on
church-state relations, said they will decide whether a student
Bible study group must be allowed to meet at an Omaha, Neb., high
school after class hours.
   The court will hear an appeal by school officials who say giving
such access to the club violates the constitutionally required
separation of church and state.
   A decision is expected sometime in 1990.
   Students at Westside High School sought in 1985 to organize a
Christian Bible study club. Officials refused to approve the club,
suggesting the students meet instead at a church next door.
   A federal judge ruled in favor of the school officials. But the
8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals overturned the decision in
February, saying the club must be allowed to meet on school premises.
   The appeals court noted that the high school has let some 30
other extra-curricular groups, such as a chess club and a scuba
diving club, meet on school grounds after class hours under a
faculty member's supervision.
   Congress in 1984 passed the Equal Access Act barring public high
schools that accept federal aid from discriminating against groups
based on ``the religious, political, philosophical or other content
of the speech at such meetings.''
   The law is designed to force schools to give the same privileges
to religious clubs as other ``non-curriculum-related student
groups.''
   The Supreme Court ruled in 1981 that state-run universities
cannot ban student groups from using campus facilities for religious
worship and study.
   But the justices have not decided whether the same rule should
apply to high schools.
   They examined the issue in 1986 in a Pennsylvania case but,
because of a procedural flaw, did not answer the question.
   At that time, four court members said they would let high school
students conduct such meetings. Two of those _ former Chief Justice
Warren E. Burger and Justice Lewis F. Powell _ no longer sit on the
court. The two others were now-Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist
and Justice Byron R. White.
   Justice Department lawyers in the former Reagan administration,
which also protested the court's ban on organized prayer in public
schools, had pressed for permitting student Bible study and worship
meetings.
   The Bush administration has not stated its position on the
Nebraska case acted on today.
   The 8th Circuit court rejected the contention that high school
students are more impressionable than college students and therefore
should be given more protection from student religious groups that
may appear to be sanctioned by school authorities.
   ``We reject this notion because Congress considered the
difference in the maturity level of secondary students and
university students before passing the Equal Access Act,'' the
appeals court said. ``We accept Congress' fact-finding.''
   Besides Nebraska, the 8th Circuit court ruling set a binding
precedent in Arkansas, Iowa, Minnesota, Missouri, North and South
Dakota.
   The case is Westside Community Schools vs. Mergens, 88-1597.
  
</TEXT>
</DOC>
