<FIRST>u w PM-Scotus-Abortion-Blackmun     07-03 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Abortion-Blackmun,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blackmun Says Signs Evident Court Will Move to Overturn Roe Vs. Wade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Justice Harry A. Blackmun, author of the 1973
Supreme Court decision legalizing abortion, said in a strongly
worded dissent today that ``signs are evident and very ominous''
that the court will move to reverse a woman's right to abortion.
   Blackmun said that with its decision today, the court was
inviting further challenges to its landmark Roe vs. Wade decision.
   He criticized the court majority for not acknowledging this.
   ``The silence is callous. It is also profoundly disruptive of
this court as an institution,'' he said from the bench.
   He said that with its decision, the court was inviting ``charges
of cowardice and illegitimacy.''
   Blackmun said that overturning the Roe vs. Wade decision would
cast ``in darkness the hope of every woman in this country.''
   ``For today, at least, the law of abortion stands undisturbed,''
Blackmun said. ``For today, the women of this nation will retain the
liberty to control their destinies. But the signs are evident and
very ominous, and a chill wind blows.''
   He predicted that reversal of Roe vs. Wade would force hundreds
of thousands of women each year to ``defy the law and place their
health and safety in the unclean and unsympathetic hands of
back-alley abortionists. Or they would attempt to perform abortions
upon themselves with disastrous results.
   ``Every year, many women, especially poor and minority women,
would die or suffer debilitating trauma, all in the name of enforced
morality or religious dictates or lack of compassion as it may be.''
   As Blackmun read his remarks, Justice Thurgood Marshall watched
intently. But the five other justices did not look at him. Justices
Sandra Day O'Connor and Anthony Kennedy were not on the bench.
   Although his words were strong, Blackmun at no time raised his
voice or showed any signs of overflowing passion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
