<FIRST>r i PM-Algeria     07-03 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Algeria,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Algeria Legalizes Multiparty System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislators approved a new law allowing
opposition political parties, a move that will end the one-party
rule existing in this North African state since its independence in
1962.
   Today's newspapers reported 40 groups intend to form parties to
challenge the political dominance of President Chadli Bendjedid's
National Liberation Front, which has ruled Algeria since the country
won independence from France.
   The vote came Sunday after deputies considered 34 amendments to
the bill. It is the latest progression since widespread rioting in
October left 170 people dead and led to calls for reform.
   In a series of referendums since November, Algeria's 13 million
voters have backed sweeping political changes proposed by Bendjedid,
who was elected to a third five-year term in December.
   The first multicandidate balloting will be in municipal elections
in December.
   According to the bill, groups wanting to form political parties
now can apply to the Interior Ministry, which has two months to give
a reply.
   The state will contribute to each political party in proportion
to its membership in Parliament. Parties are not allowed to accept
financial or material support.
   The new law forbids members of the military, policemen,
magistrates or members of the Constitutional Council from belonging
to political movements.
   It also does not allow the formation of parties based on
regional, linguistic, racial or religious grounds. Some deputies
felt that article was aimed at Algeria's Berber minority or Islamic
fundamentalists in this country, one of the more liberal Arab states.
   As ruling party deputies debated the bill, several hundred
people, many of them women, demonstrated peacefully in front of
Parliament building, calling for respect for women's rights and
equality before the law.
   In February, Algerians approved a new constitution which made no
mention of the socialist policy underpinning the previous 1976
constitution drawn up by President Houari Boumedienne, who ruled
Algeria from 1965-78.
   This month, Parliament also is to consider reforms on laws
governing freedom of expression and the electoral code.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
