<FIRST>u a PM-Abortion-Laws     07-03 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Laws,0564</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abortion Debate Swings to Legislatures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers in several states today predicted fierce legislative
battles as anti-abortion activists seek laws based on the U.S.
Supreme Court's ruling legalizing new restrictions on abortion.
   In Alabama, Republican state Rep. Greg Beers promised prompt
legislation to impose limits on abortion. In coming months, he said,
``I believe you'll see every state in America introducing
legislation like this.''
   Pennsylvania's leading abortion foe, Rep. Stephen Freind, said
that while the 1973 Roe v. Wade decision legalizing abortion was
still partially in place, ``they've tremendously chipped away at it.
   ``We can go a hell of a lot further in restricting abortions as
long as there is a rational basis for doing so,'' Freind said.
   ``It does throw it back in our laps,'' said Rep. Richard M.
Dillinger, an Indiana Republican. But he said the outcome was
unclear: ``I don't know about the sentiment of this Legislature.
Nothing's been done on abortion recently.''
   Florida House Speaker Tom Gustafson said before the ruling that
he would call for a special session of the Legislature if the court
authorized new restrictions on abortion. Otherwise, he said, the
issue would overshadow other work of the regular session.
   ``The battle is now going to go to the state Legislature,''
declared Eric Johnke of Planned Parenthood of Pennsylvania, a
supporter of legal abortion. ``We are committed to fighting it out
there.''
   In Iowa, Gov. Terry Branstad, who said he has ``a consistent
pro-life position,'' hailed the ruling but took a middle position on
possible new laws. He said he first will ``consult with a wide range
of people,'' adding: ``I think we have to consider all points of
view.''
   Similarly, Sen. Lu Hardin, an Arkansas Democrat who has
introducted anti-abortion legislation in the past, said he would
study the ruling before acting on new laws for his state. ``Am I
just going to automatically sponsor them? The answer is no,'' he
said.
   The high court upheld several abortion restrictions in a Missouri
law, including provisions banning any public employee from
performing or assisting in abortions not neccessary to save the
mother's life, and banning the use of any public hospital or other
facility in such abortions.
   The ruling also said the states may ban the use of tax money for
``encouraging or counseling'' women to have abortions not necessary
to save their lives, and may require doctors to determine, when
possible, whether a fetus at least 20 weeks old can live outside the
womb.
   As a result of the ruling, ``What we are going to see is a
tremendous surge of legislative activity,'' said Sarah Weddington,
the Texas lawyer who argued the case, known as Roe v. Wade, that
legalized abortion in 1973.
   New state laws, she said, ``could eventually lead to abortion
being almost, if not actually, illegal in at least some states and
maybe many of the states.''
   While Roe v. Wade was not reversed, ``We are considering it a
victory,'' said Molly Kelly, of the Pro-Life Coalition of Southeast
Pennsylvania.
   ``We're obviously going to try to get our Legislature not only to
uphold the Missouri provisions, but also to challenge Roe so that
the next time this case comes up we think Roe will go down,'' she
said.
</TEXT>
