<FIRST>u a PM-Abortion-MissouriReax 2ndLd-Writethru a0578 07-03 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Missouri Reax, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0578,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abortion Clinic Officials Call Court Ruling an ``Outrage''</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Widdicombe in grafs 2,7,8 of pvs, and inserts
4 grafs reax from woman who underwent abortion after 6th pvs bgng ``State
Attorney''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LORI DODGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials at the clinic that figured in today's
Supreme Court abortion ruling called the decision ``the beginning of
a war'' that will be fought for years to come.
   ``This is a serious, serious setback for women and families in
this country,'' said Judith Widdicombe, founder of Reproductive
Health Services, the clinic that challenged a 1986 Missouri law
which imposed a variety of restrictions on a woman's right to obtain
an abortion. ``This is an outrage.
   ``There's a movement in this country that will not tolerate this.
It will become our Vietnam of the 1990s.''
   Missouri Gov. John Ashcroft hailed today's ruling, saying that
``By beginning the dismemberment of Roe vs. Wade, the Supreme Court
gives the American people greater ability to save innocent lives.
That's something Missourians take very seriously.''
   The high court stopped short of overturning its 1973 Roe vs. Wade
decision which barred the states from outlawing abortion.
   State Attorney General William Webster, who was the chief
defendant in a suit brought by Reproductive Health Services
challenging the law, called the decision ``a great victory,'' but
declined further comment until he had read the full text of the
opinion.
   Jane, 30, a St. Louis woman who had an abortion earlier this
year, was at the clinic for the announcement of the decision.
   ``This is going to go on and on,'' said Jane, who asked that her
real name not be used. ``And the quiet silent majority is going to
have to speak up. Every organization that's pro-choice is going to
have to fight a thousand times harder. It's like dominoes. If you
give up once, they keep falling down one by one.
   She said the restrictions are going to cause abortions to cost
more and become more difficult to get.
   ``It's clear that in Missouri a woman is not going to have the
option that I had a couple of months ago,'' said Jane.
   Widdicombe said she did not believe the anti-abortion movement
would be satisfied with the tighter restrictions on abortions.
   ``Their goal is no abortions,'' Widdicombe said. ``Next will come
birth control.''
   She said her main fear now was that the Legislature would
interpret the Supreme Court ruling as restrictively as possible.
   Mary Bryant of Planned Parenthood, who lobbied against Missouri's
1986 law, said she expected an ``avalanche'' of legislation
introduced in Missouri that would attempt to even further restrict
abortions in the state.
   In today's decision, the justices restored Missouri regulations
that:
   _ require doctors to determine, when possible, whether a fetus at
least 20 weeks old is capable of surviving outside the womb, by
testing lung capacity and conducting other tests.
   _ ban the use of tax money for ``encouraging or counseling''
women to have abortions not necessary to save life.
   _ ban any public employee _ doctor, nurse or other health care
provider _ to perform or assist an abortion not necessary to save a
woman's life.
   _ ban the use of any public hospital or other facility for
performing abortions not necessary to save life.
   The decision also upheld the constitutionality of a declaration
in Missouri law that ``the life of each human being begins at
conception.''
</TEXT>
