<HEAD>Ian Smith Challenges His Suspension From Legislature</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retired white opposition figure Ian D.
Smith launched a court appeal Monday of his suspension from the
Zimbabwe parliament in 1987 for criticizing the government.
   In a test case challenging the jurisdiction of parliament, Smith
filed for payment of his salary as a legislator during his
suspension in 1987.
   Attorneys for Smith _ the leader of the former breakaway British
colony of Rhodesia that became independent Zimbabwe in 1980 _ said
he was filing for his unpaid salary of about $2,250.
   Smith, 68, was suspended from the legislature after attacking the
government's calls for economic sanctions against neighboring South
Africa. He also charged that democracy had been undermined in
black-governed Zimbabwe.
   The appellate court's ruling is not expected for several months.
   Last year, a lower court ruled the 100-seat parliament was
empowered to suspend erring members and dismissed Smith's claim
against the legislature.
   Smith, who led white-ruled Rhodesia from 1965 to 1979, held a
parliamentary seat in indepedent Zimbabwe until 20 seats reserved
for white politicians were abolished in 1987.
