<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Agriculture     07-03 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Agriculture,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reforms Needed in Food Processing, Gorbachev Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Increasing production won't put more food into
Soviet stores unless processing and packaging also are improved,
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev told a conference on agriculture.
   Gorbachev and Yegor K. Ligachev, the Politburo member in charge
of agriculture, said poor food packaging and processing results in
losses of more than 20 percent of produce before the goods reach the
market.
   ``We have asked a number of ministries, including defense, to
help out,'' Gorbachev said. Several military plants are being
converted to civilian use to help ease food and consumer goods
shortages.
   Details of Friday's conference of the Communist Party's
policy-making Central Committee were published Monday in the party
newspaper, Pravda.
   ``Further increases of agriculture production is senseless unless
we deal with processing, since much of the produce is lost,'' he
said.
   Gorbachev said entrenched party bosses were hampering
agricultural reform, particularly lease farming approved by the
Central Committee in March.
   ``There are opponents to lease farming. When they cannot
intimidate those people who are not afraid of responsibility and
hard work, they offer such conditions of lease that there is no way
for anyone to agree to them,'' he said.
   Under the March reforms, farmers who till land owned by the state
were allowed to lease the property from the state for 50 years, with
the right to pass it on to descendants. Officials say the program
has started slowly, in part because of bureaucratic meddling.
   Gorbachev said party bosses who obstruct reform should be dealt
with at the regional level. ``Party bodies should not be afraid of
those Communist leaders who are doing harm to our cause because it
does harm both to the cause and party credibility.''
   Ligachev said diverting military resources to civilian use could
help get more food into the shops. ``Defense ministries are expected
to provide sophisticated up-to-date equipment for food industries.
Because of their general efficiency, they have been given that task.
   ``It is well known the country has shortages of many things.
Unfortunately, there is no shortage of rhetoric, labels and
sometimes libel,'' he said.
   Ligachev said government critics were demanding the land be
turned over to farmers.
   ``At the same time, it appears that in real life, the vast
majority of farmers do not want to take that land and leave
collective and state farms,'' he said.
   The deputy chairman of the Georgian republic's Council of
Ministers, Guram D. Mgeladze, said farmers were unwilling to risk
leaving secure jobs on state farms for leased land because ``they
have been deceived so many times.''
</TEXT>
