<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Language     07-03 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Language,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Court Rejects Hispanics' Challenge of English as Florida's Language</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today rejected appeals by
Hispanics challenging Florida's designation of English as the
state's official language.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that an election
giving official-language status to English did not violate the
federal Voting Rights Act.
   Florida voters last Nov. 8 approved the proposal by an 84-16
percent margin. The initiative amended the state Constitution and
left it up to the Florida Legislature to implement the change.
   Voters in Colorado and Arizona approved similar measures the same
day, bringing to at least 17 the number of states that have passed
laws or adopted constitutional amendments designating English as the
official language.
   The other states are Arkansas, California, Georgia, Hawaii,
Illinois, Indiana, Kentucky, Mississippi, Nebraska, North Carolina,
North Dakota, South Carolina, Tennessee and Virginia.
   Spearheading the drive for such measures is a group calling
itself U.S. English, which also has been urging Congress to make
English the nation's official language.
   The ballot proposal in Florida was challenged on grounds that
petitions seeking signatures to place the initiative on the ballot
were not translated into Spanish in six of the state's 67 counties
covered by the federal Voting Rights Act.
   The law requires a state that distributes ``materials or
information relating to the electoral process'' to provide a
bilingual translation for minority groups in covered areas.
   But the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled last year that
Florida officials did not violate the law.
   The appeals court said the law does not apply to initiative
petitions and, in Florida's case, the involvement by state officials
was marginal.
   The state officials had a ``ministerial'' role in placing the
initiative on the ballot but were not responsible for the drive that
collected signatures on the petitions, the appeals court said.
   ``Congress has never shown any intent ... to expand coverage of
the (Voting Rights Act) to materials distributed by private
citizens,'' the appeals court said. ``It is hard to imagine that in
passing the act Congress could have intended that private citizens
seeking to further their own political goals through the initiative
petition process be subject to specific language requirements.''
   The appeals court upheld a ruling by a federal judge who said the
initiative was legal.
   The 11th Circuit court also rejected arguments that the judge
lacked authority to rule in the case. Opponents of the initiative
said the Voting Rights Act requires that the dispute be decided
initially by a special three-judge federal court, not a lone judge.
   Leaders in South Florida's Latin community said approval of the
initiative touched off an increase in anti-Hispanic incidents.
   The cases are Delgado vs. Smith, 88-1327, and In Re Delgado,
88-1329.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
