<FIRST>u w PM-Scotus-Helmsley     07-03 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Helmsley,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Told to Restudy Lawsuit Against Helmsley</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today told a federal appeals
court to restudy a lawsuit accusing billionaire hotel owner Harry
Helmsley and his business partners of fraud in connection with a New
York city condominium conversion.
   The justices said the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals should
restudy Helmsley's case in light of their June 26 ruling in a
Minnesota telephone rates case.
   The appeals court ruled that Helmsley and the others may be sued
under a federal law, the Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt
Organizations Act or RICO.
   The appeals court last January ruled that the law permits five
tenants of the Parkchester condominium complex in the Bronx to sue
on grounds the business partners concealed structural defects in the
buildings, the presence of asbestos in insulation and the need to
replace electrical systems.
   The appeals court said the accusations constitute a pattern of
racketeering activity as defined by the RICO statute.
   The Supreme Court issued a similar ruling June 26. The justices
said a single fraudulent scheme that has the threat of continuing
illegal activities is covered by the 19-year-old law.
   The high court also said the law is aimed at more than the
traditional forms of organized crime, and may target fraudulent
business activities as well.
   The case acted on today is separate from a federal indictment
against Helmsley, his wife, Leona, and two of their former aides.
   Mrs. Helmsley is accused in that case of evading taxes by billing
personal luxuries as business expenses.
   Her husband, who is 80, has been found incompetent to stand trial
on the criminal charges because of memory loss and reasoning
problems caused by several slight strokes.
   Opening arguments in the criminal case were scheduled for
Wednesday in federal court in New York City.
   The case acted on today is Helmsley vs. Beauford, 88-1523.
</TEXT>
