<DOCNO> AP890703-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 1231EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Scotus-Religion6thLd-Writethru     07-03 1161</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Religion 6th Ld-Writethru,a0600,1100</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS grafs 10-12, bgng: ``_Rejected appeals,'' to give English
language, LaRouche and Helmsley actions.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court ruled today that some
government-sponsored religious displays are permissible as long as
they do not have ``the effect of promoting or endorsing religious
beliefs.''
   By a 5-4 vote, the court said displaying a Christmas nativity
scene inside the Allegheny County Courthouse in Pittsburgh violates
constitutionally required separation of church and state because it
appears to endorse Christian principles.
   But the court unanimously permitted a Hanukkah menorah on the
front steps of the City-County Building in Pittsburgh because that
display also included a Christmas tree and a sign saluting liberty,
which the court said produced an overall secular purpose.
   The ruling came on the final day of this court session along with
a long-awaiting decision on the controversial abortion issue.
   In the abortion case, the justices gave states far greater power
to limit abortions, but stopped short of reversing their 1973
decision legalizing abortion. They also agreed to hear three other
abortion cases _ from Minnesota, Illinois and Ohio _ when the
court's next term begins in October.
   In other actions, the court:
   _Accepting its first-ever ``right to die'' case, agreed to decide
whether a Missouri family may order removal of a life-support system
from a woman in an irreversible vegetative condition.
   _Agreed to review a 1984 federal law requiring that student
religious groups be given the same access as other extra-curricular
clubs to public high school facilities. The justices will decide
whether a Bible study group must be allowed to meet at an Omaha,
Neb., high school after class hours.
   _Ordered a battle over state taxing powers reargued on broader
issues next term. Related cases from Arkansas and Florida raise the
issue of whether a business that successfully challenges a state tax
as a burden on interstate commerce is entitled to a refund of
previously paid taxes.
   _Rejected appeals by Hispanics challenging Florida's designation
of English as the state's official language.
   _Without comment, rejected arguments that the government
unlawfully tried to silence political extremist Lyndon LaRouche, who
was convicted with six others in a scheme to defraud lenders of more
than $30 million.
   _Told the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals to restudy a a
lawsuit accusing billionaire hotel owner Harry Helmsley and his
business partners of fraud in connection with a New York city
condominium conversion.
   The court said the menorah, a nine-branched candelabra used
during the celebration of the Jewish holiday Hanukkah, does not
appear to endorse Judaism because of its ``particular physical
setting.''
   The inclusion of the Christmas tree and sign saluting liberty
give the overall display a secular purpose, the court said.
   While the justices were split sharply in declaring the Nativity
scene unconstitutional, the court substantially upheld its long-used
test for determining when the wall between church and state is
breached.
   Justice Harry A. Blackmun wrote for the court and was joined in
striking down the Nativity scene by Justices William J. Brennan,
Thurgood Marshall, John Paul Stevens and Sandra Day O'Connor.
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy, participating in his first
church-state case since joining the court in 1988, dissented in
voting to permit the Nativity scene.
   The other dissenters were Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and
Justices Byron R. White and Antonin Scalia.
   ``Thank God for the Supreme Court,'' said Charles Saul, a
Pittsburgh attorney representing a Jewish group which owned the
menorah. ``The court is saying that when you put a menorah and a
Christmas tree and these kinds of things together, that all faiths
are welcome. And that the government is not endorsing one particular
religion.''
   Blackmun said the Nativity scene, or creche, violates the
Constitution because ``nothing in the context of the display
detracts from the creche's religious message.''
   That message, Blackmun said, is spelled out unmistakably in the
display.
   ```Glory to God in the Highest!' says the angel in the creche _
glory to God because of the birth of Jesus,'' he said. ``This praise
to God in Christian terms is indisputably religious _ indeed
sectarian.''
   By contrast, he said display containing the menorah includes
symbols that support the nation's pluralist tradition.
   ``The city's overall display must be understood as conveying the
city's secular recognition of different traditions for celebrating
the winter holiday season,'' he said.
   Kennedy said the court, in barring goverment sponsorship of the
creche, showed ``an unjustified hostility toward religion, a
hostility inconsistent with our history and our precedents.''
   Today's ruling relied heavily on a 1984 decision in which the
court upheld the constitutionality of a creche in Pawtucket, R.I.
   The creche at issue there was surrounded by secular symbols such
as Santa Claus, reindeer and snowmen.
   The Pittsburgh creche was displayed by itself.
   Justice Department lawyers had urged the justices to allow the
Pittsburgh displays, contending, ``Since the use of the creche as a
symbol of the holiday does not constitute a government endorsement
of the religious content of that symbol, the government is not
required to surround it with candy canes, reindeer or other purely
secular symbols.''
   Lower courts across the nation have been confused about just
where the 1984 ruling drew the line between permissible governmental
acknowledgment of religious heritages and the unconstitutional
promotion or advancement of religion.
   Most lower courts have treated the 1984 decision as a narrow one,
and have disallowed various religious displays deemed too religious.
   Blackmun acknowledged today that the 1984 ruling is ``none too
clear.'' But he said today's ruling may help dispel the confusion.
   He said these are the guiding principles: ``The government's use
of religious symbolism is unconstitutional if it has the effect of
endorsing religious beliefs, and the effect of the government's use
of religious symoblism depends upon its context.''
   In Pittsburgh, from 1981 to 1987, a 9-foot-wide creche depicting
the birth of Jesus Christ was displayed inside the county courthouse
in the city for about six weeks during the Christmas season.
   A block away, an 18-foot menorah was displayed each year from
1982 to 1987 on the front steps f the building that houses city and
county offices. It stood next to a 45-foot Christmas tree.
   A federal judge refused to order the dismantling of the displays
in late 1987, but the 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled, by a
2-1 vote, that they were unlawful. That ruling prevented the
displays being shown last Christmas season.
   The creche is owned by the Holy Name Society, a Roman Catholic
men's group that arranges for its display. The menorah is owned by
Chabad, a small Jewish sect that loaned the symbol to the city free
of charge.
   The legal controversy began when the American Civil Liberties
Union asked for removal of the creche and menorah in 1986. The
request was denied.
   The ACLU, several lawyers who conduct business at the courthouse,
a Unitarian minister and a Moslem then sued, seeking to block the
displays.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
