<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Dumping     07-03 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Dumping,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Court allows anti-dumping regulations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today allowed the government
to enforce anti-dumping regulations in a way foreign companies and
importers of foreign goods say improperly impedes international
trade.
   The court, without comment, rejected a Canadian steel producer's
appeal, which was supported by an American export-import association
and an international consumers group.
   Algoma Steel Corp. Ltd. of Canada challenged a decision by the
International Trade Commission, a U.S. agency responsible for
enforcing some anti-dumping rules.
   The commission said that Canadian steel tubing was being dumped _
sold at below fair market value _ in the United States. The
commission said such sales were injuring or threatening injury to
U.S. industry.
   The finding permits imposition of anti-dumping duties to penalize
foreign companies and importers of the steel products.
   The Commerce Department, which shares responsibility for
enforcing anti-dumping rules, said some of Algoma Steel's exports to
the United States were sold above fair market value.
   Commerce officials said that over one six-month period more than
half of Algoma Steel's exports were sold above fair market value.
   Algoma Steel said that fact, in effect, was ignored when the
International Trade Commission determined dumped goods were causing
injury to U.S. industry.
   The Canadian company said any fairly traded products should be
excluded from the commission's assessment.
   But a federal appeals court here upheld the commission's finding
in January, ruling the commission did not act arbitrarily or
capriciously when it included the fairly trade goods in its
calculations.
   ``Many such (fairly traded) sales might be the best evidence
possible that the less-than-fair-value sales had served their
purpose and the United States competitor was in full retreat,'' the
appeals court said. ``It is therefore not at all obvious that the
more-than-fair-value sales are (automatically) legally irrelevant.''
   Algoma Steel's appeal was supported by the American Association
of Exporters and Importers representing 1,200 U.S. companies
involved in international trade.
   ``The inclusion of fairly traded imports to decide injury in a
dumping case blurs the distinction between fair trade and unfair
trade, thereby penalizing honest U.S. importers who follow
internationally acceptable practices,'' the association said.
   Also backing the appeal was Consumers for World Trade, which said
U.S. trade law was being misused to erect protectionist barriers.
   The Bush administration urged the justices to reject the appeal.
   The case is Algoma Steel vs. U.S., 88-1781.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890703-0113 </DOCNO>
