<FIRST>u i PM-SouthAfrica 1stLd-Writethru   07-03 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0579,0588</SECOND>
<HEAD>ANC Has Reportedly Ordered Halt to Civilian Attacks</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 5th graf, ``The ANC...' to correct that meeting began Thursday,
sted Tuesday. PIckup 6th pvs, `Ms. Neke...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The African National Congress
guerrilla group has ordered a halt to attacks that are likely to
harm innocent civilians, according to a group of whites who returned
today from talks with the rebels.
   The delegation also said the ANC said it will not oppose white
anti-apartheid candidates in national elections because it thinks
they could make a difference in Parliament.
   Several Western countries, including the United States and
Denmark, paid for the meeting between 115 white South Africans and
the 85 members of the ANC, the largest of the exiled guerrilla
organizations fighting to overthrow the white minority government in
South Africa. Most ANC members are black.
   It was the largest group of white South Africans to have talks
with the ANC.
   ``The ANC tends to be demonized in this country, which is a very
serious problem considering we are going to need to negotiate with
them in the future,'' said Gael Neke, an executive member of the
Five Freedoms Forum, which organized the conference in Lusaka,
Zambia. The meeting began Thursday and ended Sunday.
   Ms. Neke said a major topic at the conference was the ANC's use
of violence, particularly limpet mines and car bombs aimed at
targets in which civilians are more likely to be hurt than the
military or police.
   These include restaurants, sports stadiums, public toilets and
trash cans.
   Some delegates expressed dissaproval of this policy and were told
by ANC delegates that orders ``went out last year to end'' such
violence, she said, adding that ``in fact it has stopped.''
   There have been 28 bombings in South Africa this year, with 20
injuries. Most of the recent bombs have been placed under police
vehicles or at the homes of politicians.
   The most serious occurred June 11, when a bomb exploded under a
parked police van at a soccer stadium in a black township, injuring
three black teen-agers and a 20-year-old man.
   The white delegation chief, Mike Olivier, said the ANC members,
including President Oliver Tambo and South African Communist Party
leader Joe Slovo, said some white anti-apartheid members of
Parliament could make a difference, although the organization
believes Parliament as a whole is not representative of South
Africans.
   He said the ANC representatives would not call for a boycott of
the Sept. 6 parliamentary elections for the white House of Assembly,
but they would continue to condemn voting in elections for the
Indian and mixed-race houses, because the ANC contends most people
in those communities do not vote and the elected members are
therefore not representative.
   Under law, blacks have no vote in national affairs.
   Olivier said the ANC insisted that certain conditions must exist
in South Africa before it is willing to negotiate with the South
African government. Those conditions include the release of
political prisoners; legalization of the ANC and other
anti-apartheid political organizations; the lifting of the national
state of emergency, the return of exiles to South Africa; and
withdrawal of soldiers from black townships.
   Another Five Freedoms Forum member, Gavin Evans, said ANC
delegates indicated ``if those conditions were met, on entering into
a period of negotiations, they would be prepared to suspend
violence.''
   He said the delegates didn't discuss what ``suspend'' meant.
</TEXT>
