<FIRST>u w PM-Scotus-AbortionReax 2nd-LdWritethru a059whenthesecondvotewillbeheluling;Pro-AbortionPeopleSayItErodesRights
07-03 0919</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Abortion Reax, 2nd-Ld Writethru, a0590,900</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abortion Opponents Hail Ruling; Pro-Abortion People Say It Erodes
Rights</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New lead, picking up 2nd graf pvs, We are. Inserts one graf
after 8th pvs, This ruling, one graf after 11th pvs, Molly Yard, and ADDS
four grafs at end with more reax</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-abortion groups today hailed the Supreme
Court's abortion ruling as a major victory while pro-choice
advocates said greater restrictions on the right to end a pregnancy
will send women ``into back alleys.''
   ``We are smiling. We are thumbs up all the way,'' John Willke of
the National Right to Life Committee said shortly after the court's
divided ruling that expanded state authority to restrict abortions.
   ``Women's rights in every state are now in jeopardy,'' said
Judith L. Lichtman, president of the Women's Legal Defense Fund.
``Women across the country are outraged that this fundamental right
can be taken away.''
   In its ruling, the court stopped short of overturning a historic
1973 decision that granted women the right to abortions. But it
permitted the state of Missouri to enforce several provisions
designed to restrict abortions not necessary to save life, and
opened the way for other states to follow suit.
   The court also said it would hear two new abortion cases next
term.
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, a key abortion opponent in Congress,
called the decision ``a major victory for the pro-life cause.''
   Judith Widdecombe, founder of Reproductive Health Services, the
Missouri clinic involved in the court case, said: ``There's a
movement in this country that will not tolerate this. It will become
our Vietnam of the 1990s.''
   ``This ruling will sentence thousands of teen-agers each year to
bear children they are not ready emotionally, physically or
financially to raise,'' said the Center for Population Options.
   Lori Schroyer, spokeswoman for the California Abortion Rights
Action League, said ``access to abortion is going to be limited to
those of privilege. It will force people across state lines and into
back alleys.''
   Patricia Schroeder, D-Colo., said the decision ``made women wards
of the state. Their rights are all dependent on what states decide
to do, and I think that's a very sad day for America's families,
young people and everyone else who's concerned about rights and
choices.''
   Molly Yard, president of the National Organization for Women,
said the decision ``chips away'' at abortion rights. Noting the
cases still to be heard, she said the court will have more
opportunities to limit abortion rights until ``pretty soon nothing
much will be left for a woman in controlling her reproductive life.''
   Sen. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H., who calls abortion ``the greatest
human rights violation in history,'' said the ruling is ``the first
big step toward overturning Roe vs. Wade and another step toward the
end of the killing of prenatal infants.''
   Olivia Gans, a spokeswoman for the National Right to Life
Committee, said the decision ``recognized that the states have an
interest in protecting the life of'' the unborn child.
   ``This is a very important day for our group. We're talking about
allowing the people of America the decision whether or not they are
comfortable with allowing abortion on demand,'' she said.
   But Susan Liss, director of People for the American Way, said the
ruling ``paves the way for a state by state bloodletting that could
be among the most painful in our history.''
   Abortion-rights groups said the ruling shifts the battlefield on
the issue from the courts to the political arena, and promised to
make abortion an issue in elections throughout the country.
   ``Every person who stands for election in this country is going
to have to answer,'' Yard said.
   Lichtman said ``the handwriting is on the wall _ we can no longer
depend on the courts to protect this fundamental right of women to
make the most private and intimate decisions about their
reproductive lives.''
   Randall Terry, founder and national director of Operation Rescue,
said the decision opens the door to a reversal of Roe vs. Wade.
   ``It's a faltering step under which children will continue to be
murdered, but this decision indicates that Roe's days are
numbered,'' said Terry, whose organization is known for its protests
outside abortion clinics.
   But Sarah Weddington, a Dallas attorney who successfully argued
the Roe vs. Wade case in 1973, said that while the decision is
effective immediately, said ``it will have no practical implication
until state legislatures pass new laws.
   ``So in terms of is abortion legal or illegal in the various
states, tomorrow it's going to be the same as today. But what we are
going to see is a tremendous surge of legislative activity in all of
the state legislatures depending on which ones are in session and
which ones are not,'' she said.
   Despite that reassurance, many women appeared to be fearing the
worst.
   At Women's Health Services Inc., a Pittsburgh abortion clinic,
executive director Sue Roselle, said, ``The telephones are ringing
off the hook. Women are saying, `I want my abortion now before they
change the law.'''
   ``Women will mourn this day,'' said Janet Benshoof of the
American Civil Liberties Union. ``The right of privacy should be
secured by the Constitution. American women should not have their
rights up to a vote in every state legislature.'
   The National Abortion Federation said that ``whether a woman can
exercise her constitutional right to abortion will increasingly
depend on where she lives, how much money she has and how far she is
able to travel.''
</TEXT>
