<FIRST>r w AM-Democracy-Documentary     07-03 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Democracy-Documentary,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Producer Says Trade and Information Lead to Democratic Change</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The push for democratic change in such places
as eastern Europe and China comes about mainly from two major
changes around the globe, says a television documentary producer
whose study of democracy begins next week on the Public Broadcasting
System.
   ``The major factors are increasing international trade and the
increasingly widespread and electronic delivery of information,''
Patrick Watson, a veteran Canadian producer, said in a telephone
interview. ``As you increase the contact among people and increase
the flow of information, you get a push for democracy.''
   Watson turned his three-year, 30-nation project into a 10-hour,
10-part series, ``The Struggle for Democracy,'' which will begin
airing July 11 on PBS stations.
   Watson is particularly interested in China, where in 1964 he
produced and directed, ``The Seven Hundred Million,'' the first film
by a North American since the Communists took over the world's most
populous nation. Eight years ago, he hosted a Canadian Broadcasting
Corporation series, ``The Chinese.''
   As he sees it, the bloody repression last month of students in
Beijing resulted from the threats to the aging Chinese leadership
represented by the young intellectuals.
   ``Actually, the students are not particularly popular in China,''
he said. ``If there were an election, the students would be rejected
because the government has so tightly controlled the flow of
information over the years and has succeeded in painting outside
influences as subversive.''
   No reforms are likely in China until the current leadership dies
out or looses power, he said. ``When the old guard goes, you'll
likely see a push for change that will primarily take the form of
economic reforms because the economy has such trouble.
   ``That push, in turn, will open up trade and contact with
outsiders, and increase prosperity and that will begin the process
of change,'' Watson said. ``But it will be very slow. In the near
term, you'll see some softening up of the harsh process that you've
seen lately, but it will be a very long time and a very long road
before you see any real change.''
   Watson said his project taught him that ``democracy wears a
different face in whatever culture it exists.
   ``If the Soviets or the Chinese do some type of democracy, North
Americans will likely look at it and say that it doesn't look at all
like ours, but it may actually turn out to be a very functional
democracy for that culture,'' he said.
   The prime factors needed for democracy, according to the
producer, are ``a reasonable level of prosperity and economic
stability. It doesn't mean that democracy will occur if you have
those factors, but they are preconditions.''
   Another factor is some form of freedom of information.
   ``It is absolutely essential to have an informed constituency,''
Watson said. ``That's one of the things you saw in China, where
information was being faxed from the western nations back to
Beijing.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890703-0118 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 1239EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-FlagTown Bjt   07-03 0662</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flag Town, Bjt,0681</SECOND>
<HEAD>Flag Town Rallies 'Round the Colors</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER MATTIACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HERMITAGE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Where 444 American flags fly this Fourth of
July and all year 'round, Verna Wagner teaches her grandchildren to
count the 50 stars and 13 stripes and never burn the flag, no matter
what the Supreme Court ruled.
   ``We want them to learn about our country and about what the flag
stands for,'' Mrs. Wagner, 63, said this weekend. ``If they want to
burn the flag, we'd tell them to go to Cuba or Iran where it's okay
to do it.''
   Bill Stratter, 64, a former World War II Navy boatswain's mate
relaxing nearby at the Veterans of Foreign Wars Public Golf Course,
vowed never to let the colors burn for freedom of speech or anything
else.
   ``If you were desecrating the flag, I'd probably shoot you if I
had a gun in my hand,'' he said.
   Old Glory snaps row-on-row in the summer breeze at Hillcrest
Memorial Park cemetery, where a new flag was raised each of the 444
days American hostages were held in Iran from Nov. 4, 1979, to Jan.
20, 1981.
   Tom Flynn, owner of the 65-acre cemetery, later added a small
bronze marker and a perpetual flame for eight American servicemen
who died trying to rescue the hostages in 1980.
   One former hostage still returns occasionally, and daily a few
tourists or residents of this city of about 17,500 people near Ohio
stop by. Lately, newly hatched swans and mallards paddling in a
shallow pool among the flags keep visiting children happy.
   Mrs. Wagner's grandchildren, Jason Jackson, 3{, and Justin, 2,
were encouraged to look skyward.
   ``We're very patriotic,'' said their mother, Linda Jackson. ``I
want them to know about the United States.''
   ``The flags are beautiful and sometimes it's very inspiring
here,'' said cemetery Superintendent Jim Bigler, 40, who keeps each
banner flying atop 18-foot steel poles year round.
   ``I never think of myself as a big, giant patriot. I stand at
ballgames, but I don't always sing,'' Bigler said.
   ``The flag stands for 200 years of history, good times and bad
times, lives lost and lives born,'' he said. ``It's very
disrespectful to burn it. You're protesting all the things it stood
for in one shot and it stands for too much.''
   Don Wilson, 60, an Army veteran of Korea and manager of the VFW
golf course, said the Supreme Court went too far with last week's
5-4 ruling that flag burning is legal under the Constitution's First
Amendment protections of freedom of speech.
   ``I believe in the so-called civil rights, but where does it
stop?'' Wilson said. ``When you burn the flag, you're never going to
have a peaceful demonstration. People feel this deep down inside.''
   John Kukol, 66, incoming VFW commander and a Navy veteran of
World War II, said freedom of speech means it's okay to call
President Bush an obscenity, for example.
   ``But don't start monkeying around with the flag, buddy,'' Kukol
said. ``That's different.''
   ``I don't think our forefathers ever meant free speech to mean
having Commies burning the flag. It just shows how stupid the
Supreme Court is,'' said Robert Price, Democratic mayor of adjacent
Sharon.
   Several residents said they agreed with Bush in calling for a
constitutional amendment to protect the flag from desecration.
   ``If that's what it takes, we ought to do it,'' Mrs. Wagner said.
   ``Okay, the Supreme Court made the ruling,'' Wilson said. ``But
if enough people feel this way, let's change the Constitution. We
can overrule the Supreme Court.''
   But Bigler said it's easier to raise a flag than to amend the
Constitution to protect it.
   ``I think you should be very cautious when you're amending the
Constitution. You shouldn't rush into it willy-nilly,'' he said.
``But I guess if you just want to say `Wait a minute' on this issue,
you could come out looking very bad, very bad indeed.''
 
</TEXT>
