<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-LaRouche     07-03 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-LaRouche,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>LaRouche Loses Supreme Court Appeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Political extremist Lyndon LaRouche and six
others convicted in a scheme to defraud lenders of more than $30
million lost a Supreme Court appeal today.
   The court, without comment, rejected arguments that the
government unlawfully tried to silence LaRouche's political movement.
   LaRouche is serving a 15-year federal prison sentence for mail
fraud, conspiracy and scheming to defraud the Internal Revenue
Service. His co-defendants were given either three-year or five-year
sentences.
   U.S. District Judge Albert V. Bryan Jr. in Alexandria, Va.,
rejected LaRouche's claim that the government waged a politically
motivated vendetta against the four-time presidential candidate.
   In sentencing the defendants last January, Bryan said LaRouche's
vendetta claim is ``errant nonsense.''
   ``The idea that this organization is a sufficient threat to
anything that would warrant the government bringing a prosectuion to
silence them just defies human experience,'' the judge said.
   Prosecutors said LaRouche and the others conspired to default on
some $34 million in loans from political supporters.
   LaRouche has taken extreme views on a variety of issues. For
example, he has supported a quarrantine of AIDS victims and has
charged that Queen Elizabeth is involved in drug trafficking.
   His political organization, the National Caucus of Labor
Committees, has its headquarters in Leesburg, Va.
   Convicted along with him were William Wertz, Edward Spannaus,
Michael Billington, Dennis Small, Paul Greenberg and Joyce
Rubinstein. Wertz and Spannaus each were sentenced to five years in
prison; the others to three years.
   The case is In re LaRouche, 88-1990.
</TEXT>
