<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-AIDSTesting     07-03 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-AIDS Testing,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Court Asks Bush Administration About Nebraska AIDS tests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today asked the Bush
administration whether it thinks a Nebraska state agency should be
able to test its employees for AIDS.
   The court said it wants to hear what Justice Department lawyers
think about rulings that blocked the agency from imposing mandatory
blood testing of employees who come into direct contact with the
mentally retarded people the agency serves.
   The justices are not expected to say whether they will review the
Nebraska case until sometime in the court's 1989-90 term, which
begins in October.
   The Eastern Nebraska Human Services Agency in 1987 adopted a
policy requiring certain employees to submit to blood testing for
the virus associated with AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency
syndrome.
   AIDS is a contagious disease that attacks the body's immune
system, rendering it incapable of resisting other diseases and
infections. The virus most often is spread through close contact
with blood, blood products or semen from infected persons.
   The incurable condition is believed caused by an unusual virus,
now called human immunodeficiency virus or HIV, discovered in France
and the United States.
   The Nebraska agency's rationale for imposing AIDS testing is that
retarded clients who engage in violent or aggressive conduct, such
as biting or scratching, risk contracting the disease from an
infected employee.
   The policy also sought to test employees for hepatitis.
   After employees of a five-county subagency called the Eastern
Nebraska Community Office of Retardation sued, U.S. District Judge
Lyle Strom barred enforcement of the policy.
   The judge said the evidence showed that the risk of an agency
staffer transmitting AIDS to a client, assuming that any staffer is
infected with the disease, ``is extremely low, approaching zero.''
   The 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld Strom's ruling last
Feb. 6.
   ``Under the facts established in this case, the district court
properly enjoined (the) policy as an unreasonable search and seizure
under the (Constitution's) Fourth Amendment,'' the appeals court
said.
   In the appeal acted on today, the state agency urged the justices
to create ``a special needs exception'' to the Fourth Amendment's
general ban on government searches and seizures in the absence of
probable cause.
   The appeal said the 8th Circuit court ruling ``imposes an unduly
stringent standard'' on the agency ``to justify the mandatory blood
testing ... (for) ensuring a safe training and living environment
for mentally retarded citizens.''
   The chief victims of AIDS have been homosexual men and
intravenous drug users, although a small percentage of cases are
attributed to transfusions of contaminated blood, heterosexual
contact and spread from infected pregnant women to their offspring.
   As of May 31, 1989, AIDS had been diagnosed in 97,193 Americans,
of whom more than half, or 56,468, have died since June 1, 1981,
according to the CDC. No one is known to have recovered from AIDS.
   The case is Eastern Nebraska Community Office of Retardation vs.
Glover, 88-1805.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890703-0122 </DOCNO>
