<FIRST>u w PM-Scotus-LawyerAds     07-03 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Lawyer Ads,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Court Agrees to Look at States' Limits on Lawyers' Ads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to take a fresh
look at how far states may go to prohibit advertising by lawyers.
   The court said it will hear an appeal by an Illinois lawyer
censured for saying on his professional letterhead he is a civil
trial specialist certified by the National Board of Trial Advocacy,
a private organization.
   The court will hear arguments in the case during its next term
beginning in October, with a ruling likely in 1990.
   The Illinois Supreme Court, which disciplines that state's
lawyers, last February upheld the state rule against advertising
oneself as a certified civil trial specialist.
   The state court censured Gary E. Peel of Edwardsville, Ill., who
since 1983 included the specialist reference on his letterhead.
   The state court said Peel's use of the reference is misleading
because it makes it appear he is more qualified than other lawyers
who do the same type of work. The state court also rejected Peel's
arguments that the rule violates his constitutional free-speech
rights.
   The state court said Peel's claim that he ``is certified as a
civil trial specialist by the National Board of Trial Advocacy is
misleading because it tacitly attests to (his) qualifications as a
civil trial advocate. Because not all attorneys licensed to practice
law in Illinois are certified by the NBTA, the assertion is
tantamount to a claim of superiority by those attorneys who are
certified.''
   The state court noted that only lawyers who specialize in patent,
trademark and admiralty law in Illinois are allowed to advertise
their specialties.
   The reason for allowing those exceptions is to help the public
find attorneys who practice those unusual specialties, the state
court said.
   The NBTA, based in Boston, said it uses ``rigorous standards'' to
determine whether any civil or criminal trial advocate is entitled
to its certification.
   It said it has certified more than 1,000 lawyers nationwide.
   The Supreme Court in a key 1977 ruling struck down a ban on all
lawyer advertising, ruling that it violated free-speech rights.
Since then, the court has upheld some regulation of lawyer ads but
struck down other rules.
   The case is Peel vs. Attorney Registration and Disciplinary
Commission of Illinois, 88-1775.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
