<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 1356EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-US     07-03 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-US,0658</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets, Americans Prepare for Arms Control Experiment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A team of American scientists and congressmen
prepared Monday to fly to the Black Sea for experiments on whether
radiation devices can detect the presence of nuclear warheads aboard
ships.
   Rep. Bob Carr, D-Mich., described the experiment as a
``confidence-building measure'' to aid the superpowers as they
negotiate a Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty to slash nuclear
arsenals by 30 percent to 50 percent.
   Four Soviet navy ships will take part in the experiment
Wednesday, said Albert G. Makerov of the Soviet Academy of Sciences,
which is sponsoring the project, along with two liberal private
American organizations, the Natural Resource Defense Council and the
Federation of American Scientists.
   A spokeswoman for the U.S. Embassy said there would be no comment
on the experiment because it does not involve U.S. authorities. The
United States is aware of the project, and ``embassy officers have
met with the congressmen,'' said the spokeswoman, Margot Squire.
   U.S. Navy officers have balked at allowing Soviet inspectors
aboard U.S. warships and have objected to Soviet proposals to limit
nuclear-tipped cruise missiles under the proposed START agreement.
   The Reagan and Bush administrations have maintained that
virtually no verification regime could prevent either superpower
from disguising shipboard nuclear warheads as conventional weapons,
thus frustrating any attempt control nuclear weapons at sea.
   The Soviets have cited the impasse over sea-launched cruise
missiles as a major obstacle to completion of the strategic treaty.
   Makerov and physicist Tom Cochran, who leads the U.S. team, said
the experiment would begin Wednesday at the Black Sea port of Yalta.
   The scientists will use radiation detection devices to determine
their ability to spot nuclear weapons material aboard the Soviet
missile cruiser Slava, which will be carrying a nuclear-tipped
cruise missile. American scientists said they believed the weapon
would be either an SS-N-12 or the newer SS-N-22.
   Cochran said his group would use portable devices to detect the
emission of gamma rays, given off by some forms of uranium, and
neutrons, given off by plutonium.
   The American team, which includes physicists from Stanford
University and Princeton University, plans to use two types of
detectors to be carried aboard the Slava.
   It was unclear how close the Soviet navy would allow the American
scientists to approach the Slava's cruise missiles, which are stored
and launched from the deck.
   While the American devices are in use, Soviet scientists will
conduct similar tests using detectors in a helicopter and a vessel
near the Slava.
   Preliminary results are expected Thursday, although later
calculations would be made to compare the U.S. and Soviet findings,
Cochran said.
   ``We need to take this one step at a time,'' said Cochran,
acknowledging that radiation devices alone were unlikely to provide
adequate verification of the numbers of nuclear weapons aboard any
naval vessel.
   Cochran said the tests ``cannot guard against efforts to evade
any treaty by squirreling nuclear weapons in the bowels of a
warship.''
   The Slava will be a good test subject because ``there are no
below-decks magazines on this cruiser'' where other nuclear tipped
weapons might be concealed, he said.
   A sister ship to the Slava, the Marshal Ustinov, is due to visit
Norfolk, Va., home of the U.S. Atlantic fleet, on July 25. The port
call is part of growing military cooperation between the United
States and the Soviet Union that was reached new heights last month
with a visit to previously closed Soviet bases by the chairman of
the U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff, Adm. William Crowe.
   Despite growing military-to-military cooperation, the Pentagon
opposes the Yalta experiments because U.S. officials are ``trying to
get the best of both worlds, the benefits of the tests without the
responsibility,'' Carr said.
   Also observing the test are Reps. John Spratt, D-S.C., and James
Olin, D-Va.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
