<FIRST>r i AM-China-Book     07-03 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Book,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Book on `Rebellion' Goes on Sale</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A collection of essays portraying the official
version of how China's government crushed pro-democracy
demonstrators has gone on sale under the title ``Quelling
Counterrevolutionary Rebellion _ Study Material.''
   At the state-run Xinhua Book Store on Wangfujing, Beijing's main
shopping avenue, copies of the 149-page paperback are stacked
together with popular self-education manuals.
   Some readers scanned the book Monday, but few were buying it.
   ``It's usually ordered by groups who have to study it,'' a
saleswoman said.
   The book, part of a massive propaganda campaign, begins with
excerpts from a June 9 speech by senior leader Deng Xiaoping, in
which he accuses a small number of people of plotting to overthrow
the Communist Party and socialist system.
   Deng praises the soldiers who took part in the bloody June 3-4
suppression of the student-led movement in Beijing, and says China
will continue its open-door and reform policies under Communist
Party rule.
   The book, which sells for the equivalent of 48 cents, also
reprints an April 26 editorial from the People's Daily newspaper
that condemned the student demonstrations and alleged they
represented a ``conspiracy'' to overthrow the government. Students
had demanded the government retract the editorial.
   The book also contains extracts from talks between Premier Li
Peng and student leaders on May 18, five days after the students
began a hunger strike to press for democratic reforms. Students had
complained it was more of a speech by Li than an exchange of views.
   ``Quelling Counterrevolutionary Rebellion'' presents witnesses'
accounts of the ``rebellion,'' along with official reports of how
``rioters'' attacked soldiers and troops were ``forced'' to
retaliate.
   Other articles denounce dissident astrophysicist Fang Lizhi, who
took refuge in the U.S. Embassy with his wife shortly after the
crackdown in which hundreds, and possibly thousands, of unarmed
students were killed.
   China Youth Publishers have printed 120,000 copies of the book.
   A sign outside Xinhua Book Store says anyone interested can order
photographs of the suppression of the uprising, but few people took
notice of it.
   Nearby, an old man was busy dealing with readers eager for an
annual compilation of ``Family Doctor,'' a monthly magazine with
practical medical information, and ``America as a Riddle,''
featuring essays by dissident writer Liu Binyan.
   ``This is the best-seller,'' he said, pointing at Liu's book.
</TEXT>
