<FIRST>u a PM-TreatyOak     07-03 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Treaty Oak,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sunscreens Being Erected to Protect Ailing Treaty Oak</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Treaty Oak, whose canopy has provided
friendly shade during the dog days of summer, is itself getting some
cover by way of giant sunscreens to help save the venerable tree
from a poisoning attack.
   Park employees today began erecting 65-foot poles next to the
ailing, 400-year-old Treaty Oak and later this week will hang
40-foot screens.
   ``There is tender foliage up there. It would be real easy to fry
it,'' said Paul Roberts, a city environmental specialist.
   Leaves have turned brown and fallen off the beloved 65-foot tree
since a potent herbicide was poured at its base in what police said
was an attempt by a 45-year-old farm-supply salesman to cast a spell
or a curse.
   Police on Thursday charged Paul Stedman Cullen with criminal
mischief in the attack. He could receive 20 years in prison.
   Roberts said the screens will reduce the sunlight hitting the
tree by 50 percent to 60 percent. ``We're coming into a real
stressful period for the tree. We can expect upper 90s, 100 degrees
for the next two months,'' he said.
   The soil also is being replaced to a depth of about 30 inches,
and 12 sprinklers are shooting water on the tree five minutes every
hour.
   Legend has it Stephen F. Austin, the father of Texas, made peace
with the Indians under the tree's branches. Indians regarded the
tree with superstitious reverence, contending that tea made from its
acorns had the power to return straying lovers or protect warriors,
the Austin American-Statesman reported.
   Over the years, couples have married or gotted engaged under the
canopy of the tree, which has a 127-foot limb spread and is 52.5
inches in diameter at chest height.
</TEXT>
