<HEAD>Ben Wright of `The Sound of Music' Dies at 74</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS throughout to show that Zeller was a Nazi. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ben Wright, who played the Nazi Herr
Zeller in the movie ``The Sound of Music,'' died of complications
from heart surgery. He was 74.
   The character actor, who lived in North Hollywood, died Sunday at
St. Joseph's Medical Center. He underwent heart-bypass surgery June
23.
   Wright was born in London and studied at the Royal Academy of
Dramatic Arts.
   He arrived in Hollywood in 1946 and starred in radio programs
including ``Sherlock Holmes'' and ``Have Gun, Will Travel.'' The
actor also did voices for Disney animated hits such as ``101
Dalmatians'' and ``The Jungle Book.''
   In ``The Sound of Music,'' the 1965 film based on the Rodgers and
Hammerstein musical, he played a Nazi sent to ensure that Baron von
Trapp reported for German military duty.
   Several months ago, Wright finished recording the speaking role
of Sir Grimsby in the animated Disney feature ``The Little Mermaid.''
   Survivors besides his wife, Muriel, include a son and daughter.
   Services were to be private.
