<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 1403EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Palme     07-03 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Palme,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Witness Backs Alibi of Palme Murder Suspect</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVA JANZON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A witness Monday backed the alibi of the
man charged with killing Prime Minister Olof Palme, saying he saw
the accused at a train station 18 miles away about the time of the
downtown shooting.
   The witness, Algot Asell, later had his credibility questioned by
a newspaper reporter who testified Asell had changed his story.
   Asell was the first witness in Stockholm District Court to
support the alibi of defendant Christer Pettersson, who served a
jail sentence for manslaughter and has a long record of drug and
alcohol abuse.
   Pettersson, 42, has denied killing Palme. Asell was the last
scheduled witness in the trial, which began May 29 and is to end in
mid-July following summaries.
   Palme, who dominated Swedish politics for more than a decade, was
shot Feb. 28, 1986, as he walked home with his wife from a late
movie.
   Asell, 68, said he saw Pettersson waiting for a train at Marsta
Station between 11 p.m. and 11:30 p.m. on the night of the murder.
Palme was killed at 11:21 that night.
   The train station is about 18 miles from the crime scene and more
than 30 minutes by train.
   Newspaper reporter Sakari Pitkanen later cast doubt on Asell's
credibility, saying his testimony differed from what the witness had
said in an interview.
   Pitkanen, a reporter for the Aftonbladet newspaper, testified
that Asell's account, particularly on the train schedule and his
sighting of Pettersson, differed from what he said in a June
interview.
   Asell said he took the last train from Marsta and listened to the
midnight radio news after arriving home, according to Pitkanen.
   He said Asell changed his story after it was pointed out there
was no midnight radio news that night.
   Other witnesses have testified they saw Pettersson waiting for
Palme outside the movie theater and following Palme down the street.
Palme's wife identified Pettersson as the man she saw a few feet
away when her husband fell, fatally wounded.
   Asell said he did not notice the exact time he saw Pettersson,
but he said he bought a chocolate bar near the train station just
before the store closed at 9:30 p.m., then went into a nearby
restaurant until one of the last trains left the station at 11 p.m.
or 11:30 p.m.
   Asell said he knew Pettersson because they lived in the same
neighborhood. Also Monday, Ulf Akansson, who shared an apartment
with Pettersson for seven months, said Pettersson was an admirer of
Palme and never carried a gun.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
