<SECOND>PM-Fires Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0532,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Firefighters In West Hampered By Weather</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead and 4th graf pvs, `Gusts that ...' with authorities
now reporting that one house and a shed sted two houses destroyed. INSERTS
two grafs after 5th graf pvs, ``It must ...' with quote on destroyed home.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters from four states hope to contain by tonight a
1,200-acre blaze that destroyed a home near Grand Junction, Colo.
California firefighters fought a brush fire apparently sparked by
children playing with fireworks.
   Dry, hot weather hampered firefighters in those states and in
Utah, where lightning began several blazes in the eastern part of
the state and a cigarette-caused fire burning in the median of an
interstate closed the highway.
   The lightning-sparked blaze that forced 50 people from their
homes west of Grand Junction was the only one not contained of
several wild fires that have scorched parts of Colorado since
Wednesday.
   Gusts that came with 96-degree heat Sunday blew embers over fire
lines, starting numerous small blazes that frustrated fire crews
from Colorado, Wyoming, Utah and Idaho. A home and a shed were
reported destroyed.
   ``It must have been consuming an acre every 15 seconds,'' said a
resident, Tim Menger. ``Flames you would just not believe, just like
out of an Indiana Jones movie, just swept across that valley back
there.''
   Paul Hefner, commander of the firefighting effort, said the
intensity of the fire as it razed the home was stunning.
   ``I have never seen anything burn like that in my life,'' he
said. ``Twisted metal and melted glass, nails that melted right
through the glass.''
   Campfires and fireworks were banned over the July Fourth weekend
in the San Juan National Forest near Durango.
   ``It's so dry, one firecracker will be enough,'' said Kris
Damsgaard of the U.S. Forest Service.
   In California, the largest and most devastating of last week's
blazes, a 7,840-acre fire near Lake Elsinore, was surrounded over
the weekend, and firefighters hoped to extinguish it by Tuesday.
   Firefighters today also hoped to contain a 300-acre blaze in San
Bernardino County, 60 miles east of Los Angeles. Witnesses reported
three youngsters playing with smoke bombs Sunday, Forest Service
spokeswoman Lindsay Maierhofer said.
   About 300 firefighters battled the blaze overnight.
   ``The temperatures are hot and the terrain is very difficult,''
Ms. Maierhofer said. ``Some of the canyons dip in and slope back,
and the air tankers are having a difficult time going in to do a
direct drop. It's kind of scary.''
   In central Utah, a fire near Scipio Pass led authorities to close
Interstate 15 twice on Sunday.
</TEXT>
