<FIRST>r i AM-Irish     07-03 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Irish,0568</SECOND>
<HEAD>IRA Takes Responsibility for Killing Soldier, Airport Bombs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Irish Republican Army claimed responsibility
Monday for a bomb that killed a British soldier in West Germany as
his family watched and for a bomb attack at a Belfast airport.
   Cpl. Steven Smith died Sunday in West Germany when he opened his
car door and a bomb exploded. His wife and their four young children
were injured. Hanover police said they found and defused a bomb in
another soldier's car nearby.
   Three bombs exploded early Monday at Belfast's Harbor Airport,
damaging two parked airplanes and shattering windows in airport
buildings, but causing no injuries.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher called the bombers cowards, and
said Smith's killing was ``doubly horrific because the family both
were injured and saw what happened.''
   ``It just shows precisely the mentality of a terrorist,'' Mrs.
Thatcher said. ``It was another cowardly attack on people who were
very vulnerable, who do everything possible to defend us and keep
freedom and democracy safe.''
   The IRA, which is fighting to oust Britain from Northern Ireland
and unite the predominantly Protestant province with the Roman
Catholic Republic of Ireland, made its claims to Belfast news media.
   ``We are forced to take our struggle beyond Ireland because the
British public are restricted by their government from learning of
its failure in Ireland and the resistance to its rule,'' it said in
a statement.
   This apparently referred to the ban imposed by the British
government last October on broadcast interviews with members of the
IRA, their supporters, and other groups involved in violence in
Northern Ireland.
   The IRA statement said Smith, 31, a rations officer with the
Royal Tank Regiment, ``could be the last soldier to die as a result
of the British occupation of Ireland if the British government was
to accept that after 20 years its military and political policies in
our country have failed.''
   Next month marks the 20th anniversary of the arrival of British
troops in Northern Ireland. More than 2,700 people have since been
killed, 418 of them soldiers. Five soldiers have died in IRA actions
in West Germany, Holland and Belgium in the past 14 months.
   Smith's father, Brian, said from his home in Dewsbury, northern
England: ``I never dreamed in a million years that this would happen
to my son. He has become another innocent victim. The bombers who
did this can't have a heart when they must have known children could
have been victims.''
   The explosion occurred on a residential street on Hanover's
outskirts where many British military families live.
   Pete Brown, a spokesman for the British Rhine Army in
Moenchengladbach, said Smith's wife, Tine, and their four children
aged 2 to 11, were hospitalized in satisfactory condition.
   Hanover police issued composite sketches of two suspects in their
30s whom witnesses saw nearby shortly before the attack.
   Three bombs exploded at Belfast's Harbor Airport about 2:30 a.m.,
eight minutes after the airport received a telephone warning, police
said.
   One bomb damaged two prototype aircraft developed by Shorts
Brothers Ltd. The other two bombs exploded near the air traffic
control tower and on the airfield, police said.
   Short Brothers, Northern Ireland's largest employer, owns Harbor
Airport, the second-largest in the province after Aldergrove Airport
outside Belfast.
</TEXT>
