<DOCNO> AP890703-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 1427EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Airbus     07-03 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Airbus,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iranians Mark Anniversary of Iran Airbus Downing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran on Monday marked the first
anniversary of the U.S. downing of a civilian jetliner with a
memorial service at the airport where the flight originated, and it
demanded full compensation for the victims.
   The July 3, 1988, shootdown by the USS Vincennes, in which 290
people were killed, was a crime that showed the ``Great Satan'' _
the United States _ exercised ``state terrorism,'' Iran's Foreign
Ministry said.
   At a memorial ceremony at the airport in Bandar Abbas, the
director of civil aviation announced the airport had been renamed
``The International Airport of the Tir 12 Martyrs,'' Tehran Radio
reported. According to the lunar Persian calendar, last year's date
of Tir 12 coincided with July 3, 1988.
   Iran Air Flight 655 had left the city of Bandar Abbas en route to
Dubai, in the United Arab Emirates, when the USS Vincennes in the
Persian Gulf picked it up on radar and mistook it for an Iranian jet
fighter.
   The sailors, who had been involved in a skirmish with Iranian
gunboats earlier that day, opened fire, downing the A300 Airbus and
killing all 290 people aboard. Most of the victims were Iranians.
   At the airport ceremony, Civil Aviation Director Mohammad Nabi
Habibi unveiled a painting depicting the incident and displayed
several parts of the aircraft pulled from the gulf, said the
broadcast, monitored in Nicosia.
   ``The martyrs of this incident were another group of innocent
people who fell victims of American atrocities,'' it quoted him as
saying.
   Relatives of the victims, clergymen, and air force and civil
aviation officials attended the ceremony, Tehran Radio said.
   The Foreign Ministry demanded full compensation for all victims,
but it did not mention a figure. Washington has indicated it is
ready to pay compensation, but it wants to be sure none of the money
goes to the Iranian government.
   The Iranian daily newspaper Jomhuri Islami urged other countries
to ``counter U.S. brutalities.''
   The daily Abrar said an editorial, ``The Iranian nation will
never forget U.S. crimes.''
   ``This has kindled a fire in the heart of the Iranian nation
which would not be extinguished without the elimination of U.S.
criminals,'' it said.
   The English-Language Kayhan International said the incident
``proved that Tehran's relations with Washington are irreparable.''
   ``Those who feel the situation may change in the near future are
advised to go through the pictures of mutilated bodies of Iranians
on board the Airbus,'' it said.
   More than 200 relatives of the victims are suing designers and
manufacturers of the ship's radar system, a spokesman for the group
said Sunday in Abu Dhabi.
   Nagib Ghafoor, spokesman for the Flight 655 Litigation Group,
said the suit was filed June 28 in U.S. District Court in San
Francisco on behalf of relatives of 83 victims.
   Pentagon analysts have said split-second decisions aboard the
Vincennes were affected by the inability of radar operators to match
the plane's radar trace with digital direction, altitude and speed
information displayed on another screen.
   Ghafoor said the suit named the General Electric Co. ``and other
entities which designed and manufactured the radar equipment on
board the USS Vincennes.''
   A spokesman for GE, based in Fairfield, Conn., said Sunday the
company had not seen the suit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
