<FIRST>r a AM-People     07-03 0804</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,0836</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainer Lola Falana returned to the Las
Vegas stage over the weekend, showing no sign of the multiple
sclerosis that forced her from the footlights 1{ years ago and
threatened to end her career.
   She left out her sizzling dance routines and concentrated more on
singing, but Falana, 46, displayed the old zest as she performed
everything from Broadway hits to Michael Jackson songs.
   ``You don't know how I need you,'' she told her audience, which
included longtime friend Sammy Davis Jr., during her show Sunday at
the Sands Hotel and Casino.
   She took time to thank God for the improvement in her condition
and praised Davis for giving her a break as a teen-ager, when she
got a major role in Davis' Broadway show ``Golden Boy.''
   ``I wouldn't trade my life with anyone on this earth,'' she said,
her voice breaking. ``For in these past two years, God has opened me
up and taught me what life is all about.''
   Falana nearly died in 1983 when she suffered peritonitis
following abdominal surgery. Then in November 1987 she learned she
had multiple sclerosis, a neurological disease that short-circuits
the central nervous system. For a time, she was partially paralyzed,
but the worst symptoms of the disease have eased.
   In mid-June she was asked to play a weekend date at the Sands
Hotel.
   ``They called and asked me `Can you be ready by Friday (June
30),''' Falana recalled last week. ``I told myself it's now or never
_ I guess I'll have to be ready. I'm not into being a chicken.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RAPID CITY, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kris Kristofferson and Willie Nelson were
among the stars who performed for a crowd of 6,000 to raise money _
and awarness _ for the Indian cause.
   They, along with Neil Young, John Denver, Jackson Browne and
others, donated their talents Sunday at the Paha Sapa Music
Festival. Proceeds will go to a college, an alcohol- and
family-counseling center and a radio station serving Pine Ridge
Indian Reservation.
   Kristofferson said he's worried that the civil rights of Indians
and other people have been violated in recent years. He said he
hoped the concert raised awareness of the troubles Indians face.
   ``I think the main thing a concert can do is bring public
attention to the problems,'' he said.
   And he said he hopes the concert moved some people to be ``as
concerned about abuses to people as they are concerned about abuses
to the flag.''
   Browne told reporters before the benefit concert that he'd go
anywhere to play at a sober Fourth of July concert. It was billed as
a ``clean and sober'' event.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Juan Carlos of Spain arrived Monday
for a three-day state visit, the first trip to Finland by a reigning
Spanish monarch.
   The king was accompanied by his wife, Queen Sofia; Crown Prince
Felipe; and Spanish Foreign Minister Francisco Fernandez Ordonez.
Juan Carlos and Sofia were here in 1975, before he became king.
   President Mauno Koivisto and his wife, Tellervo, welcomed the
royal couple. The royal couple was scheduled to meet the diplamatic
corps Tuesday at the Presidential Palace, and go on a cruise in the
Gulf of Finland aboard the ship Silvia Regina.
