<NOTE>Eds: A version moving on sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former WBA heavyweight boxing champion
John Tate decided at the last minute he would keep his Olympic medal
but leave most of his other personal belongings on the auction
block, a spokeswoman said Monday.
   Auctioneers spent more than three hours Sunday selling the
one-time World Boxing Association champ's personal items.
   The 34-year-old Tate, whose finances are being handled by a
conservator, was allowed to recover some of his possessions before
Sunday's sale by Powell Auction Co.
   ``He got his Bronze medal and he did pick out some boxing gloves
and some photographs, some furniture _ enough to furnish his
apartment _ and some fishing equipment,'' said auction company
spokeswoman Barbara Phillips.
   Among the items left to be sold off were a pair of stereo
speakers that brought $1,200 and boxing shorts that went for $45.
Tate's robes sold for $200 while his boxing gloves brought $250 to
$300, Mrs. Phillips said. She declined to say how much the total
take was.
   Tate won a bronze medal in boxing in 1976. In October 1979, he
became WBA champ, but he lost the title five months later.
   In 1983, Tate signed a court paper authorizing the appointment of
a conservator to handle his affairs. He has since unsuccessfully
attempted to have the conservatorship dissolved.
   He has blamed his personal difficulties over the years on a
cocaine problem.
   Knox County Chancellor Sharon Bell ordered the auction to raise
money for Tate's living expenses.
</TEXT>
