<FIRST>r e BC-JVCJazz-Reeves     07-03 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-JVC Jazz-Reeves,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dianne Reeves Charms Carnegie Hall Crowd</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Eliane is cq in 3rd graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM GILLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was a hit-or-miss affair until Dianne Reeves
came on stage. Then the promise that had been a 50th anniversary
concert for the Blue Note record label became reality.
   Miss Reeves' mature talent and elegant presence redeemed the
concert, which amply illustrated the pitfalls such amalgam
programming invites.
   The Friday night event at Carnegie Hall, part of the JVC Jazz
Festival, began auspiciously with Brazilian pianist Eliane Elias
playing some driving music with a five-piece band. She then changed
pace, warming the audience with a lyrical solo piece.
   The Tony Williams Quintet succeeded the Brazilian sound with its
own high-intensity brand of jazz. The quintet, led by drummer Tony
Williams, went its own way; it failed to build on the mood.
   After the intermission, electrical guitarist Stanley Jordan
played a long, rambling, self-indulgent set. Although a trio was
listed on the program to back him up, they failed to appear on
stage. It wasn't clear whether his solos had used up his time
allotment or whether he had just forgotten about his fellow
musicians.
   Just when it appeared the evening might be a musical failure,
Miss Reeves appeared.
   She sang some standards _ ``My Funny Valentine,''``The Nearness
of You,''``How High the Moon'' _ and gave them her own signature.
She sang a slaves' field song and some blues.
   Throughout her performance, her wit and warmth charmed the
audience.
   Shortly after she came on stage, she confided that it was her
Carnegie Hall debut. By the end of her segment, the crowd was
willing to give her the deed to the place.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
