<DOCNO> AP890703-0152 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 1700EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Court-Scene     07-03 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Court-Scene,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Brief Silence _ Then the War of Words Resumed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus-Abortion, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the Supreme Court's decision on abortion
finally came, it brought momentary silence to the waiting crowd on
the sun drenched plaza outside.
   Then the two sides _ ``pro-life,'' ``pro-choice'' began screaming
at each other once again.
   But first, lawyers in dark suits stood on the white-marble paving
stones, hurriedly flipping through the 78 pages of the court's
decision in ``William Webster, attorney general of Missouri et al vs
Reproductive Health Services et al.''
   As it became clear that the court had strengthened the power of
the states to limit abortion, though stopping short of overturning
the landmark Roe vs Wade decision, a young man in the crowd held up
a prepared sign.
   ``Thank You Supreme Court,'' it read.
   ``Too bad you guys lost,'' a grinning teen-ager gloated as he
passed a group of abortion-rights demonstrators, their banner
drooping.
   ``Not the Courts, Not the States, Women Will Ddecide Our Fate,''
pro-choice demonstrators shouted.
   A bearded man in the brown robes of a monk knelt facing the
court, praying aloud.
   He was flanked by nine men and women, most holding anti-abortion
placards.
   A young man tossed a dozen paper-wrapped coat hangers, the symbol
of unsafe abortions, on the marble steps in front of the group.
   The praying man reached into his robes, removed a bottle of
water, and sprinkled the coat hangers.
   Volunteers picked up them up and hauled them away.
   Coat hangers were tossed down, removed, replaced, and soon the
steps leading to the plaza of the court were carpeted with coat
hangers, hundreds of them, most of them lettered in red: ``Never
Again.''
   Leaders of the fight for or against abortion trooped to clusters
of waiting microphones to hail the courts decision or to mourn it.
   Scores of spectators lined the rims of nearby marble fountains,
straining to hear.
   ``It is very clear the pro-life cause is galvanized,'' said Tom
Glessner, executive director of the Christian Action Council. ``It
was a major victory for the pro-life movement.''
   ``I think it's a serious setback,'' said Bella Abzug, the former
Democratic congresswoman from New York. ``I think women should
mobilize all over the country and make it clear that the people are
supreme, not the court. This is a creeping invasion of women's
rights. Thhat's what it is, a creeping invasion.''
   Molly Yard, president of the National Organization for Women, was
asked what impact the decision will have.
   ``It means that if you've got money, you can get an abortion,''
she replied. ``If you're poor, you're down the drain.''
   Inside the court, more than a hundred people waited in a basement
corridor to obtain copies of the decision.
   Near them, carved in gilt letters on white marble, were words
from an 1821 decision of the court: ``A Constitution is formed for
ages to come. ... The course cannot always be tranquil.''
   Outside on the plaza there was no tranquility.
   Two men shouted opposing slogans at each other, amplifying their
screams with bull horns.
   Groups of shouters appeared here and there, becoming more
animated and shrill with the approach of television cameras.
   A red-faced young man to a dark-haired woman: ``Is that what
you're saying, because I'm a man you're not going to listen to my
argument?''
   ``It's murder, that's what it is, murder,'' a man shouted at
another group.
   ``It's not yet a person,'' came the shouted reply.
   ``Yes it is, it's a baby, it's a life,''
   Over their heads the repeated chant could be heard: ``Not the
Courts, Not the States, Women Will Decide Our Fate.''
   And the reply: ``We Will. We Will. We Will Rescue Babies.''
   The Supreme Court of the United States had ruled.
   But the socially divisive battle over abortion rights was clearly
not over.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
