<FIRST>r i AM-Ferry 1stLd-Writethru a0622 07-03 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ferry, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0622,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Passenger Ferry Sinks Near Oslo, 7 Injured</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with 7 injured, 95 aboard ship, comments
from police, passenger. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A passenger ferry with 95 people aboard
collided with a West German freighter and sank Monday, injuring
seven people, police said.
   The panicked passengers, some clutching infants, jumped overboard
after the collision andwere saved by rescue helicopters, police and
pleasure boats, and scuba divers, witnesses said.
   Rescue officials said the ferry, the Oslo 6, sank near the island
of Langoeya, the ferry's destination, after colliding with the
freighter Achat. The West German ship remained afloat and reported
no casualties.
   State radio said the ferry captain tried to sail the badly
damaged ship at full throttle toward the dock on Landoeye. It came
within 200 yards of land before water flooded its engines and it
sank.
   ``There was wild panic on board,'' passenger Per Faltsen told the
radio. ``Adults and children started to jump into the water right
after the collision. ... I looked down and saw a hugh hole in the
ferry and could see down to the water.''
   Inspector Kolbjoern Skervengen said all passengers survived,
although seven were injured, one critically.
   It was the major second passenger ship accident off Norway within
two weeks. On June 20, a Soviet cruise ship with more than 950
people aboard rammed an iceberg in the Norwegian Sea. No serious
injuries were reported.
</TEXT>
