<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 1808EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Greece     07-03 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Parliament Sworn In After Unique Government Formed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DINA KYRIAKIDOU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new Parliament convened Monday under a
conservative-communist coalition formed for the specific task of
prosecuting those accused of corruption in the previous Socialist
government.
   Former Premier Andreas Papandreou, the Socialist leader, did not
attend the ceremony but said his party was ready to ``begin the
battle'' in opposition. Papandreou, 70, is recovering from pneumonia
and kidney problems at an Athens hospital.
   The 300 deputies sworn in Monday were chosen June 18 in an
election that denied Papandreou a third four-year term but also left
the conservative New Democracy party short of a majority.
   Two weeks of negotiation produced the coalition, and a 22-member
Cabinet led by Premier Tzannis Tzannetakis, a conservative, was
sworn in Sunday.
   Analysts described the arrangement by the conservative New
Democracy party and the Coalition of Left and Progress, an alliance
of the Moscow-line Greek Communist Party and the Greek Left, a
Eurocommunist group, as a ``national reconciliation'' government 40
years after the civil war.
   The 1946-49 civil war ended with the defeat of the communists by
a conservative government supported by the United States. The defeat
began decades of prosecution and exile on barren islands for the
communists, who now are involved in a government for the first time
in their 70-year history.
   Leaders of the conservatives and the communist alliance agreed to
a three-month coalition to prosecute members of Papandreou's
government allegedly involved in financial scandals.
   Under Greek law, ministers are immune unless prosecuted during
the Parliament following the one when the alleged crimes were
committed.
   Agamemnon Koutsogiorgas, former No. 2 man in Papandreou's
government, was suspended from the Socialist Party's executive
committee Monday. He is accused of taking a $2 million bribe to
amend a law while he was justice minister.
   The semiofficial Athens News Agency said Koutsogiorgas appeared
at a meeting of the committee and, after he refused requests to
leave, the members voted to suspend his membership.
   Papandreou's party have 125 seats in the unicameral Parliament.
New Democracy has 145 and the communist coalition 28. One seat went
to the conservative Democratic Renewal party and the other is held
by Sadik Ahmed, a Greek Moslem independent.
   The Communists were given the Interior and Justice ministries in
the new government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
