<FIRST>r a AM-Priest-Guns     07-03 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Priest-Guns,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Priest Makes Bid To Buy Parishioners Guns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAUGATUCK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two suicides and an accidental shooting
upset a Roman Catholic priest so much that he offered to pay $50 for
each gun parishioners bring to him.
   ``I just can't see Jesus saying, `I'm going to have a gun for
protection,''' the Rev. Edmund S. Nadolny said Monday.
   The priest said he's hoping to collect 100 guns. He has collected
two since he announced the plan June 25 during Mass at St. Vincent
Ferrer Church.
   Nadolny, 56, said he paid for one of the guns, while the other
was given to him by a 65-year-old woman parishioner who was stirred
by his call to disarm. Each gun he buys will be turned over to
police, Nadolny said.
   The priest said got his idea last month when an aging parishioner
called him and told him he was going to commit suicide. Nadolny said
the man had just learned he had cancer and did not have enough money
to fight to the disease.
   ``I told him I wanted to talk to him. I told him I would give him
$100 for the gun, and I took the gun from him. I realized that he
needed a lot of help,'' Nadolny said.
   Although Nadolny was able to help prevent that suicide, two other
young men in the Naugatuck area shot themselves in June. Both had
learned they had cancer, Nadolny said. He believes they might not
have died had someone been able to counsel them.
   That same month, a 12-year-old boy was accidentally shot in the
back of the head and killed by an 11-year-old friend. The two boys
were playing at the younger boy's home with a small handgun.
   ``In the hospital, I meet on a regular basis with people who cut
their wrists. The only place I meet someone who shoots themselves is
in the morgue,'' Nadolny said.
   Nadolny said he is not opposed to people owning guns for hunting,
but he said he wished hunters would store guns away from the
ammunition.
</TEXT>
