<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     07-03 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indian Soldiers Detain Scores of Suspected Tamils</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indian soldiers swept through the
northern jungles and detained 125 suspected Tamil Tiger rebels,
Indian officials said Monday. Five of the militants were killed in
the operation.
   The offensive, code-named ``Storm,'' was launched after the
rebels stepped up attacks on the Indian peacekeeping troops, said a
spokeswoman at the Indian High Commission, or embassy.
   Indian newspapers said the sweep against the dominant Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam group began 10 days ago and involved at least
20,000 troops backed by helicopter gunships.
   Five militants were killed during the operation, and troops have
been ordered to continue ``the pressure on the Tamil Tigers,'' said
the spokeswoman, who cannot be identified under briefing rules.
   She had no other details about the operation but said 108 rebels
were killed and 47 were captured last month, while the Indians
suffered 40 casualties.
   A Tamil rebel leader in Colombo said the Indian gunships shelled
and destroyed villages in the jungles of Vavuniya, Mullaitivu and
Kilinochi.
   The offensive was confined to aerial bombardment, but ``we have
yet to face the worst,'' said the rebel leader, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   A Sri Lankan military official said a dusk-to-dawn curfew had
been imposed in many towns in the area since Saturday.
   Last week, President Ranasinghe Premadasa asked India to cease
operations against the Tamil Tigers, the main rebel militia fighting
for an independent nation in the northeast.
   India rejected Premadasa's request, saying a decision could be
taken only if the Tamil Tigers surrendered arms and refrained from
violence.
   Premadasa's appeal came a day after his government opened
independent negotiations with the rebels, aimed at ending the
separatist campaign.
   An earlier attempt to end the movement was made by Premadasa's
predecessor, Junius R. Jayewardene, which resulted in an
India-brokered peace accord that brought the Indian troops to Sri
Lanka.
   The accord, signed on July 29, 1987, promised local autonomy to
the ethnic minority Tamils in exchange for an arms surrender by the
the various Tamil rebel groups.
   While most groups gave up the violence, the Tamil Tigers reneged
on the accord and began attacking Indian soldiers. At least 800
soldiers and 1,500 rebels have died in the two-year-old bush war.
   India has also rejected Premadasa's request to withdraw its
estimated 45,000 troops by the end of July, saying a hasty pullout
could lead to even greater violence.
   India became involved in the Tamil war because of the sympathies
of its own 60 million Tamils.
   Tamils in Sri Lanka form 18 percent of the country's 16 million
people and claim they are discriminated against by the majority
Sinhalese, who make up 75 percent of the population and control the
government and the military.
   At least 9,000 people have been killed in the Tamil separatist
war and another 3,500 have died in a backlash by radical Sinhalese.
</TEXT>
