<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 1959EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-HongKong     07-03 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hong Kong,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Howe: `No Way' Hong Kong's People Could Move to Britain</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe said
Monday there was ``no way'' Hong Kong's 3.7 million people could
move to Britain to escape communist rule.
   Protesters interrupted Howe's speech to community leaders,
unfurling a banner, reading ``Shame on the Thatcher government.''
   ``This ... speech is insulting the intelligence of Hong Kong
Chinese. We protest and we walk out!'' shouted Lee Wing Tat, a
community leader who stormed from the hall with about eight other
demonstrators.
   Local politicians criticized the speech as ``totally
unconstructive'' and ``disappointing.''
   Howe indicated some Hong Kong Chinese who have provided valuable
service to the colony would be allowed to settle in Britain, but he
provided no details.
   He also said Britain would open its doors to Hong Kong residents
and mobilize the international community to do the same ``if things
did go catastrophically wrong'' in the territory once China resumes
political control of Hong Kong in 1997.
   ``The plain fact is that there is simply no way that the British
government could grant to several million people the right to come
and live in Britain,'' Howe told about 250 community leaders.
   ``It dismays me that some have suggested that this is a matter of
race. It is nothing of the sort,'' Howe said. ``It is a practical
problem'' that would test Britian's capacity in housing, employment
and transportation.
   Howe said Britain is considering plans to speed up local
democratic reform and draft a bill of rights for the colony.
   He also pledged a thorough re-examination of a clause in the
constitution for post-1997 Hong Kong being drafted by China that
allows Beijing authorities to declare a state of emergency in the
territory.
   Hong Kong residents have demanded the right to live in Britain
since China unleashed a violent crackdown on the movement for
freedom in Beijing's Tiananmen Square.
   Although more than 3 million Hong Kong Chinese are eligible for
British passports, they are not allowed to live in Britain.
   Under the 1984 British-Chinese agreement, China guarantees that
Hong Kong can keep its capitalist system and freedoms for 50 years
after the turnover and enjoy a ``high degree of autonomy.''
   Howe, on a three-day mission to gauge opinion in the colony after
the Beijing crackdown, said China has a huge economic stake in Hong
Kong. He said China remains committed to keeping the territory
prosperous and stable.
   ``Hong Kong has seen hard times before. You've always shown the
resilience and the resourcefulness to live through such times and
emerge from them stronger than ever before,'' he said. ``Hong Kong's
future will I'm sure continue that bold tradition.''
   The heckling at Howe's speech was extremely rare in this British
colony. It demonstrated the degree of bitterness many of Hong Kong's
people feel toward London's refusal to grant them the right to live
in Britain.
   Albert Cheng, head of the Right-of-Abode organization, said he
found the speech ``totally unconstructive.''
   ``When someone comes to Hong Kong from so high up and delivers a
speech like that, I am sure it will hamper the confidence of the
people once more,'' he said.
   He described the feelings of Hong Kong's people as ``frustrated,
disappointed and angry.''
   Legislative councillor Dame Lydia Dunn said she found the speech
``disappointing'' because it included nothing new.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
