<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 2000EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-US     07-03 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-US,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Sees Final Settlement in Angola This Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Herman Cohen, the new U.S.
assistant secretary of state for African affairs, said Monday he
believes Angola's civil war will be settled by the end of the year.
   Angola's Cuban- and Soviet-backed government has been fighting
rebels armed by South Africa and the United States for 12 years, but
the two sides agreed last month at an African summit in Zaire to a
cease-fire and negotiations.
   ``There have been some tremendously important developments in
Angola and I believe it's on the right track,'' Cohen said. ``I
expect a final settlement in Angola certainly before the end of this
year.''
   The process is slower in Mozambique, he said. Both countries are
former Portuguese colonies where guerrillas wars broke out when the
Portuguese hastily withdrew in the late 1970s. South Africa
supported rebels in both countries but now states that policy has
ended.
   ``In Mozambique, I believe things seem to be moving toward a
political settlement a bit more slowly than Angola, but I think it's
on the right track as well,'' Cohen said.
   He arrived in South Africa on Sunday night and is to visit
Angola, Mozambique, Zambia, the Congo and Ivory Coast. He said in
general he is optimistic about the Southern African situation, but
would not comment specifically on U.S. policy toward South Africa
until President Bush's administration completes a policy review
expected by the end of September.
   However, he did say, ``There must be a negotiated settlement.
Nothing can be done unilaterally in this country anymore.''
   Foreign Minister Pik Botha, who had just met with Cohen for more
than an hour, nodded in agreement. Cohen spoke to reporters as he
walked out of the Foreign Ministry building.
   Cohen met Monday with Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok, and
invited Govan Mbeki, a member of the outlawed African National
Congress and the South African Communist Party, to dinner Monday
night.
   Mbeki was among eight ANC leaders given life sentences in 1964
for plotting to overthrow the government. He was released in 1987
because he was ill. Mbeki is banned from speaking publicly, being
quoted by the press, or leaving his home in Port Elizabeth without
police permission.
</TEXT>
