<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--LemonBus     07-03 0156</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Lemon Bus,0159</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Looking at $60,400 in Repairs to $38,800 Bus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police are reviewing repair records of a
company that charged the city $60,400 over the last year for work on
a 4-year-old bus that cost $38,800.
   Officials of Mobile Equipment Repair Service Inc., which repaired
Bus No. 8 and 26 others under a recently terminated agreement, would
not comment.
   Records for Bus 8, obtained by the San Jose Mercury News, show
the same parts being repaired and replaced month after month. Horns
broke repeatedly. Switches and circuit breakers failed over and over
again. The bus also had a new engine and a rebuilt transmission
installed.
   Police said they are investigating whether any of the repairs are
fraudulent or if the bus happened to be a real lemon.
   The city ended its repair contract with Mobile on Friday after
critical reports cited deficiencies in the maintenance and repair
operation.
</TEXT>
