<FIRST>r w AM-IMF-Panama     07-03 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IMF-Panama,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panama Barred from Loans by International Monetary Fund</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega
in Panama was declared ineligible on Monday for new loans from the
International Monetary Fund fund because it has fallen behind on
repayments of $163 million borrowed earlier.
   Panama's total debt is over $5 billion.
   There are 151 member governments in the fund, including Panama.
The United States has the largest bloc of votes.
   The fund's External Relations Department announced that the ban
on Panama was decided by the 22 members of the Executive Board, who
meet behind closed doors. They usually act by consensus.
   U.S. financial sanctions against Noriega since 1987, following
his indictment on drug charges in this country, have so far failed
to dislodge him from his commanding position at the head of Panama's
armed forces.
   Acting President Manuel Solis Palma said in March that the U.S.
ban on payments to the Panama government caused a 20 percent drop in
the country's production last year.
   Panama becomes the ninth government to be banned from receiving
new loans from the fund. The others are Vietnam, Guayana, Liberia,
Sudan, Peru, Zambia, Sierra Leone and Somalia. Arrears in repayments
to the fund have been authoritatively estimated at close to $3
billion, both from these nine countries and from others which have
not yet fallen far enough behind to be sanctioned.
   In the past, debtor countries gave priority to meeting their
obligations to the fund but arrears have piled up in the continuing
debt crisis that began in 1982.
</TEXT>
