<FIRST>r a AM-Lukens-Appeal     07-03 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lukens-Appeal,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Mulling Felony Charges Against Lukens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH GRACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors may seek felony charges against
Rep. Donald Lukens if he successfully appeals a misdemeanor
conviction of having sex with a 16-year-old girl, the prosecutor's
office said Monday.
   The charges would stem from accusations that Lukens had sex with
the same girl when she was 13, said Tom Tornabene, a spokesman for
Franklin County Prosecutor Michael Miller.
   ``If, on appeal, the conviction is overturned, we will consider
pursuing felony charges. No final decision has been made yet,''
Tornabene said.
   Thomas Tyack, an attorney for the 58-year-old Republican
congressman, said disclosing such a plan was an attempt to
discourage Lukens from pursuing an appeal.
   Lukens was sentenced Friday to 30 days in jail and fined $500 on
a charge of contributing to the unruliness of a minor. He is free on
bond pending appeal.
   On May 26, a Franklin County jury convicted Lukens after hearing
Rosie Coffman testify that Lukens paid her $40 and gave her gifts
after having sex with her at his Columbus apartment last November.
   Ms. Coffman, now 17, told the jury that Lukens knew she was
underage.
   In February, the grand jury that indicted Lukens on the
misdemeanor charge also considered allegations that he had sex with
Ms. Coffman not only last year when she was 16 but in 1985 when she
was 13, when it would have been a felony charge.
   But the grand jury cited conflicting testimony from the girl and
did not indict Lukens on the more serious charge.
   Tournabene said that since February, however, another witness
with information about the alleged 1985 incident has been located
who would be available to testify before a second grand jury.
   Little testimony relating to Ms. Coffman's relationship with
Lukens before last November was admitted at trial, but the girl
referred to it several times on the stand.
   Lukens served two terms in Congress in the 1960s and early 1970s
before dropping out in an unsuccessful try for the Ohio
governorship. He was elected to the House again in 1986 and was
re-elected last November.
</TEXT>
