<FIRST>r a AM-Abortion-Weddington     07-03 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion-Weddington,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Roe Attorney Says Future of Abortion Rests With Young Adults</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLEY SHANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sarah Weddington, the Texas attorney whose
victorious arguments in Roe vs. Wade legalized abortion 16 years
ago, called the Supreme Court decision Monday carving back that
right a personal defeat.
   Saying she was ``wrung out'' by the ruling upholding Missouri
regulations limiting abortion rights, Ms. Weddington said at a news
conference that it was up to the young to carry on the fight.
   Ms. Weddington, 44, represented Norma McCorvey, a Dallas woman
who took the pseudonym Jane Roe, in the landmark 1973 case.
   She called Monday's ruling a personal defeat and said the day had
been burned into her memory.
   ``My heart stopped and my mouth went dry,'' she said. ``I've
invested 20 years of my life in this and now have been handed a
major defeat.''
   Ms. Weddington said she had expected the court to ``whittle
away'' the case that established the abortion precedent.
   But she added: ``I did not expect what they did and that was to
chop away at that decision.''
   She said the future of the abortion issue rests with young
adults, but she vowed to continue to speak out for the cause.
   The court, in a series of mostly 5-4 votes, restored several
Missouri abortion regulations that a lower court had invalidated for
unduly interfering with women's constitutional right to abortion.
   Ms. Weddington questioned the implications of the Missouri law _
which defines life as beginning at conception _ on some forms of
birth control and in vitro fertilization.
   ``Frankly, it makes me tired to think about the future,'' Ms.
Weddington told reporters at Texas Woman's University, where she is
an adjunct professor.
   Young adults must pick up the fight to maintain abortion rights,
she said.
   ``If people don't really say `No we're not going to have this,'
if they don't lobby their own state legislatures,'' abortion will
become illegal, she predicted.
</TEXT>
