<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 2008EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     07-03 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmaker Who Went North to Be Charged With Espionage; More Sought</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawmaker who went to North Korea for
talks with communist leaders will be charged with espionage, and
arrest warrants were issued for five more people in the case,
authorities said Monday.
   A search was also under way for radical students who helped a
22-year-old student defy the government and travel to North Korea
for a youth festival.
   Prosecutors said Suh Kyung-won, of the opposition Party for Peace
and Democracy, would be charged with espionage. This brought to
eight the number of people charged in connection with the
legislator's trip to visit North Korean leader Kim Il Sung.
   Suh said the trip was to discuss unification of the two nations.
He was jailed June 28 after he returned and surrendered.
   One of the eight people charged in the case is Suh's secretary,
Pang Yang-hyun, who was accused of receiving $12,000 from a North
Korean agent in Frankfurt, West Germany, and giving $10,000 to Suh.
   Five more poeple believed to have known about Suh's trip were
being sought.
   President Roh Tae-woo went on national radio to remind citizens
that travel to North Korea is a crime, and he said that despite
talks on unification, North Korea is still intent on spreading
communism to South Korea.
   ``Unification is a national aspiration. It can be freely
discussed by anybody,'' Roh said. But he said direct contacts with
North Korea must be made only through government channels.
   Police said 2,757 students have been arrested since Friday for
trying to march to the North Korean capital of Pyongyang for the
World Festival of Youth and Students, now under way.
   About half were released and the others were being detained for
questioning, police said. Six students arrested en route to the
border were charged Monday with violations of the national security
law.
   One of those who reached North Korea is Im Suk-yong, of Seoul's
Hankuk University of Foreign Studies. She faces arrest when she
returns.
   Intelligence agents are investigating how Miss Im obtained a
passport and funding for her trip and whether there is a connection
between her trip and that of Suh.
   Intelligence officials said they would send investigators to
Japan and West Germany, where both Suh and Miss Im were believed to
have contacted anti-South Korean organizations before proceeding to
Pyongyang.
   Suh's case was considered more serious than the trip to the North
in March by a leading dissident clergyman, the Rev. Moon Ik-hwan,
who is on trial. Officials noted Suh was a legislator and unlike
Moon's visit, the trip was kept secret by both Suh and North Korea.
</TEXT>
