<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 1940EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Abortion-PublicHospitals     07-03 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion-Public Hospitals,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fewer Public Hospitals Performing Abortions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court ruling Monday giving states the
right to ban abortions in public hospitals and other
taxpayer-supported facilities comes as an apparently declining
number of such hospitals are performing the procedure.
   The number of public hospitals providing abortions in 1985 was
265, down from 331 in 1982, according to the latest complete
statistics from the Alan Guttmacher Institute, a private research
organization specializing in sexual issues.
   The total number of hospitals providing abortions in 1985 was
1,191, versus 1,405 in 1982, according to the institute.
   The institute had no figures on how many abortions are performed
in public hospitals.
   About 12 percent of the roughly 1.6 million abortions performed
in the United States each year are paid for with public money,
statistics indicate.
   The Supreme Court's rulings on Monday gave states the right to
ban the use of public hospitals or taxpayer-supported facilities to
perform abortions not necessary to save a woman's life. States may
also ban public employees from performing those abortions.
   In 1985, $66,171,000 in public money paid for 187,997 abortions,
according to the Guttmacher Institute. States paid for all but 484,
which were paid for by the federal government.
   In 1985, there were 1,588,550 abortions reported in the country,
11.8 percent of which were publicly funded. That percentage has
likely remained steady in succeeding years, the institute said.
   Thirteen percent of all abortions were performed in hospitals, 60
percent in abortion clinics, 23 percent in other clinics and 4
percent in physicians' offices, the institute reported.
   Abortion clinics made up only 15 percent of the providers, but
accounted for 60 percent of all abortions. Of all abortions
performed in 1985, 75 percent took place in facilities having annual
caseloads of at least 1,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
