<DOCNO> AP890703-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 2028EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Legislature     07-03 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Legislature,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Defense Minister Reappointed, But Just Barely</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Minister Dmitri T. Yazov won his bid for
reappointment Monday, but his support among Soviet lawmakers was so
lukewarm that he would have been rejected without a last-minute
procedural change.
   Yazov, criticized by some members of the Supreme Soviet as too
conservative and too old for the post, garnered 256 votes in his
favor, with 77 against and 66 abstentions, Soviet television
reported.
   Legislators' ``main objections concerned the age of the
candidate,'' and his ``traditional way of thinking,'' the official
news agency Tass said.
   Others accused Yazov, 65, of paying too little attention to
soldiers' living conditions, Tass said.
   Earlier Monday, the legislature decided that to be confirmed,
nominees needed only a majority of those members actually attending
the session. Formerly, nominees needed a majority of the entire
542-member Supreme Soviet.
   The procedural change followed last Friday's failure by Vladimir
Kamentsev, the nominee for head of the Foreign Economic Commission,
to receive the required 272 votes from among about 400 legislators
attending. Tass said Monday a second vote would be held on his
confirmation.
   Yazov, who holds the rank of general of the army, was appointed
defense minister in May 1987. He replaced Sergei Sokolov, who was
fired after West German teen-ager Mathias Rust evaded Soviet air
defenses and landed his light aircraft in Red Square.
   Several legislators said other generals were more qualified than
Yazov, including the head of the joint chiefs of staff, Gen. Mikhail
Moiseyev, and Gen. Boris Gromov, who commanded Soviet troops in
Afghanistan.
   ``But a majority regarded the candidate's stand, set out in his
answers to deputies' questions, as convincing enough for his
appointment to the post of defense minister,'' Tass said.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev endorsed Yazov, saying he ``holds
progressive views'' and has made impressive contributions in
restructuring the Soviet armed forces, Tass said.
   Yazov, replying to questions from deputies, said the military
doctrine of the Soviet Union should be defined only by the political
leadership and that the job of the defense minister is to implement
that doctrine.
   The Supreme Soviet, which has been revamped under Gorbachev's
political reforms into a smaller, full-time legislature, has broken
in the past days from its traditional automatic approval of the
leadership's nominees.
   Last week its committees rejected seven nominees, including a
Gorbachev protege who was nominated to head the government's food
program. Under pressure from lawmakers, Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov
withdrew their names from consideration by the full body.
   The rejected nominees included Culture Minister Vasily Zakharov
and Vladimir Gribov, head of the State Bank.
   In other action at Monday's session, the Supreme Soviet approved
as finance minister Valentin Pavlov, who told the legislature he was
against introducing currency reforms until the economy improves,
Tass reported.
   It appointed Lev Ryabev as the cabinet's energy chief after
grilling him on his positions on atomic power stations and nuclear
waste disposal.
   As Yazov's nomination was debated, the Defense Ministry released
draft changes in military manuals to bring them in line with the
latest changes in the country's political structure, Tass said.
   The drafts give greater legal protection for individual soldiers
and call for improved living conditions for soldiers and their
families.
   The Supreme Soviet is aiming to complete the formation of the new
Soviet government, involving about 50 additional appointments, by
the end of this week, Gorbachev announced Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
