<FIRST>u a PM-Bush 6thLd-Writethru a0694-a0589 07-03 0915</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0694-a0589,900</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Welcomes High Court's Abortion Decision</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS graf 15: ``Bush planned,'' with 3 grafs bgng: ``Bush was,''
to note brush-off reaction at golf course</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, welcoming the Supreme
Court decision allowing abortions to be restricted, said today the
court ``appears to have begun to restore to the people the ability
to protect the unborn.''
   Bush has voiced support for a constitutional amendment to
overturn the 1973 Roe vs. Wade decision that legalized abortions.
   ``We continue to believe that Roe v. Wade was incorrectly decided
and should be reversed,'' Bush's statement said.
   But, it said, ``by upholding the Missouri statute, the court
appears to have begun to restore to the people the ability to
protect the unborn.''
   Chief of Staff John Sununu told a White House briefing Bush would
continue to actively support a constitutional amendment. He said
today's ruling might help build support for one, ``now that the
court has moved incrementally in this direction.''
   In the written statement, Bush said: ``Americans obviously differ
over the difficult issue underlying this case _ the morality and
appropriate legal status of abortion.''
   ``Any decision in this area will stir strong feelings.
Nevertheless, I have confidence that the American people will
continue to express their deeply held convictions on this subject
within the bounds of civility and our legal institutions,'' Bush
continued.
   Earlier, he voiced condolences to the family of the late Soviet
President Andrei A. Gromyko.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the president would
be playing golf this afternoon and had no plans to react personally
to the abortion decision.
   ``He hasn't had a chance to look at it yet,'' Fitzwater said when
asked if Bush had any immediate reaction to the court's decision.
   Bush told reporters he first met Gromyko in 1971 when Bush was
U.S. representative to the United Nations. Gromyko, longtime Soviet
foreign minister, died Sunday at age 79.
   ``I'd just like to send condolences to his son, Anatoly, who I
also know, and to the rest of the family,'' Bush told reporters as
he began the day with a 20-minute jog.
   Bush was asked for his reaction on the Supreme Court decision as
he played golf with professional Doug Sanders at a local course.
   ``My position is very well known,'' Bush said. ``And now, I'd
like to concentrate on something else,'' he added, brushing off
further questions.
   Bush also planned to treat his neighbors to a day-early
Independence Day fireworks celebration.
   ``I'm tired,'' Bush, 65, confessed Sunday after a day of jogging,
tennis, swimming, fishing, golf and then more fishing.
   Bush said Sunday he regretted the decision of Adm. William J.
Crowe to step down as chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff in
September.
   ``Very candidly, I'd like to have had him stay,'' Bush told
reporters on the golf course. ``He did an outstanding job and is
doing an outstanding job.''
   Crowe announced his decision Sunday on NBC-TV's ``Meet the
Press.''
   Hundreds of people were expected to line the shoreline of this
oceanside resort to watch the Bush fireworks this evening, to be set
off from his six-acre compound on Walker's Point by the same company
that did the 1986 Statue of Liberty fireworks in New York Harbor.
   Fitzwater said an anonymous donor helped subsidize the $20,000
display by the New Castle, Pa., company of pyrotechnics specialist
George Zambelli. Zambelli has said he expects to set off two tons of
aerial explosives in the 15-minute display.
   Bush's stand on abortion has changed since he supported the right
of a woman to choose an abortion when he first ran for president in
1980. More recently he has favored a constitutional amendment to
outlaw the procedure.
   It is one of four constitutional amendments Bush is advocating.
The others call for a balanced federal budget, line-item veto
authority on spending bills and, most recently, an amendment to
restore the right of states and Congress to ban flag-desecration, a
power the Supreme Court stripped away last week in a controversial
5-4 decision.
   The president's flag pronouncements won Bush a fair degree of
public support, including from Bartley's Dockside Restaurant in
downtown Kennebunkport, which displays a different sign out front
each time the president visits.
   This weekend's offering: ``Protecting our flag means protecting
our freedom. Thanks Mr. President. We're glad you're here.''
   Bush on Sunday jogged, went to church, swam, played tennis, got a
carry-out lunch in his boat, went ocean fishing, played nine holes
of golf and then waded into the Kennebunk River to cast for striped
bass.
   Aides said the president also planned during his five-day
extended holiday to bone up with briefing books for his upcoming
trip to Poland, Hungary and the seven-nation economic summit. But so
far his days have been crammed with recreational activities.
   Thirty-five members of the Bush family are in town for the
Independence Day festivities.
   After morning services at St. Ann's Episcopal Church, Bush
plunged into a crowd of several hundred onlookers who had gathered
outside, shaking hands and wishing people well.
   ``I hope we get out there on the water, do some fun stuff,'' Bush
told one person in the crowd.
   The Independence Day fireworks have become a Bush family
tradition in recent years.
   However, because this year's display was to be more ambitious
than previous ones, the Bush fireworks were moved up to Monday night
so they would not compete with town fireworks scheduled for the
Fourth of July.
</TEXT>
