<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 1650EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Obit-Gromyko 1stLd-Writethru a0683 07-03 1141</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Gromyko, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0683,1172</SECOND>
<HEAD>Andrei A. Gromyko, the Kremlin Survivor, Dead at 79</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 15 grafs UPDATING with Bush's comment, DEFINES Gromyko
survival formula. Picks up 13th graf, James Callaghan .. .</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY23,24; LaserColor MOSB3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Foreign Minister Andrei A. Gromyko, the dour
diplomat who served and survived every Soviet leader from Josef
Stalin until Mikhail S. Gorbachev's ``new thinking'' pushed him out,
has died at age 79.
   A tough negotiator, he helped guide Soviet foreign policy through
the twists of Cold War and detente whoever was in charge at the
Kremlin.
   Gromyko spent 28 years as foreign minister and held several other
government and Communist Party posts over half a century, including
the then-largely ceremonial post of president, but was a private
citizen in retirement when he died Sunday, 16 days before his 80th
birthday. He lost his last position, a seat on the party Central
Committee, in April.
   No cause of death was announced, but a Foreign Ministry spokesman
said Friday that Gromyko had undergone surgery for an unspecified
vascular problem. Soviet TV, in a five-minute announcement reviewing
Gromyko's life, said he died after ``a long illness.''
   Gorbachev announced the statesman's death Monday in a session of
the Supreme Soviet legislature.
   ``His whole life was connected with history, with our
achievements, our problems, with everything that falls on the lot of
a person in the thick of events for whole decades,'' Gorbachev said
after deputies observed a minute of silence.
   Tass, the official news agency, called Gromyko ``one of the major
Soviet diplomats and statesmen of the senior generation.''
   Gromyko was the ultimate technocrat and a model bureaucrat,
executing policy without shaping it. With no political constituency
of his own, he posed no threat to the Kremlin hierarchy _ a surefire
formula for surviving.
   As a diplomat and foreign minister, Gromyko helped forge the
alliance that won World War II. He joined in drafting the U.N.
Charter and participated in superpower talks that shaped the modern
world.
   He outlasted Stalin, Nikita S. Khrushchev, Leonid I. Brezhnev,
Yuri V. Andropov and Konstantin U. Chernenko. As an ambassador, he
served in the United States, Britain and the United Nations.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov said Gromyko
``was part of our history, with all its good sides and all its bad
sides,'' and historians should judge whether his ``influence was
good or bad.'' Gerasimov spoke to reporters in Paris where he had
gone in advance of a visit by Gorbachev.
   The funeral will be held Wednesday after the body lies in state
for five hours in the Red Banner Hall at Soviet army headquarters,
the nightly news program ``Vremya'' reported.
   Burial will be at Novodevichy Cemetery, the second most
prestigious resting place after the Kremlin, it said. Khrushchev,
Anastas I. Mikoyan and Vyacheslav M. Molotov are buried there.
   In a condolence statement on behalf of the U.S. government,
President Bush noted that Gromyko ``knew every U.S. president from
Franklin Roosevelt to George Bush, and every secretary of state from
Cordell Hull to James Baker.''
   Gromyko's death ``marks the passing of a generation that
witnessed many of the most historic events of this century,'' Bush
said.
   James Callaghan, the former British prime minister and foreign
secretary, said Gromyko ``was a good executor of a bad foreign
policy that has now changed.''
   Jean Francois-Poncet, a former French foreign minister, said
Gromyko ``was certainly one of those who incited the Soviet Union to
invade Afghanistan, and as a consequence, one of those whom Mr.
Gorbachev wanted to put ... aside.'' U.S. Ambassador Jack Matlock
said: ``Even when relations were difficult, he was always
professionally courteous and considerate.''
   Andrei Andreyevich Gromyko was born July 18, 1909, into a
Byelorussian peasant family.
   During World War II, he took over the Foreign Ministry's U.S.
section and was appointed ambassador to Washington in 1943, at 39
the youngest ambassador in Soviet history.
   His career took him to Tehran, Potsdam and Yalta, where one story
says Winston Churchill threw cigar butts at Gromyko after he
whispered into Stalin's ear that he should demand Germany's
unconditional surrender.
   Gromyko stepped down as the first Soviet ambassador to the United
Nations in 1948 but returned almost annually to rail against U.S.
policies.
   Some observers attributed Gromyko's political longevity to his
flexibility, diplomatic expertise and apparent disinterest in
obtaining power for himself. He was not admitted to the Politburo
until 1973.
   Khrushchev, who appointed Gromyko foreign minister in 1957 and
often insulted him, once said in his presence: ``If I tell him to
sit on an iceberg, he'll stay there and freeze, but he won't move.''
   Gromyko gained a reputation as ``Mr. Nyet'' for casting frequent
vetoes as U.N. ambassador. He was nicknamed ``Grim Grom'' because he
rarely smiled, and his craggy face was instantly recognizable to the
world.
   During Andropov's leadership in 1982-84, Gromyko's star rose. In
March 1983, he became first deputy premier in addition to foreign
minister and Politburo member.
   When Gorbachev gained power in 1985, Gromyko supported his
reforms and displayed official respect even when the new leadership
condemned some foreign policy decisions taken during his tenure,
including the Soviet intervention in Afghanistan.
   Gromyko did not escape unscathed.
   A delegate to a party conference last summer suggested he and
others who shaped policy in the Brezhnev era resign. The delegate
was rebuffed, but Gromyko was dropped from the ruling Politburo and
presidency a few months later.
   To replace Gromyko as foreign minister in 1985, Gorbachev chose
Eduard A. Shevardnadze, a party official with no previous foreign
experience, to represent ``new thinking'' intended to dispel the
Kremlin's ``enemy image'' and improve relations abroad.
   Gromyko served as president, a largely ceremonial post, after
Shevardnadze replaced him. Gorbachev, in taking over the job of
president Oct. 1, has transformed it into a powerful executive
position.
   Gromyko had not appeared in public for months and little was
known about his health. He is believed to have suffered a mild
stroke several years ago that may have partially paralyzed his face
and affected his speech.
   At the U.N. General Assembly in September 1978, he slumped while
speaking and had to be escorted away. He returned to the podium an
hour later and finished the speech.
   Many officials have been dismissed and written out of official
history books when new leaders took over the Kremlin, but Gromyko
ended his career gracefully after helping vote Gorbachev into power.
   Former Secretary of State Cyrus R. Vance praised Gromyko's skill.
   ``As a thoroughly professional practitioner of the diplomatic
trade, he has few peers in the modern world,'' Vance said. ``He
represents his country with great skill, high intelligence and
spirit, tempered in decades of experience.''
   Behind Gromyko's poker face was a sharp wit. Asked once whether
he had enjoyed his breakfast, he replied: ``Perhaps.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
