<SECOND>AM-People-Blanc,0200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mel Blanc, Man of Many Voices, In Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mel Blanc, the voice behind Bugs Bunny, Porky
Pig, the Road Runner's ``Beep!'' and Woody Woodpecker's laugh, was
in serious condition Monday at Cedars Sinai Medical Center, a
spokesman said.
   Blanc, 81, was suffering from several medical conditions,
including a heart problem, said hospital spokesman Ron Wise. His
condition has remained unchanged for a week. He entered the hospital
on May 19.
   Blanc has been one of the best-known voices in movies, radio and
television _ although that voice has a thousand names and a thousand
accents and tones.
   Since 1937 he has been the voice of such Warner Bros. cartoon
characters as Bugs Bunny, Porky Pig, Sylvester and Tweety-Pie, Woody
Woodpecker, Daffy Duck, Yosemite Sam and many other characters.
   He was a regular on ``The Jack Benny Show,'' as Benny's violin
teacher, Professor LeBlanc, and the train dispatcher who announced
``Ana-heim, A-zusa and KOOK-amunga!'' He was also Sy the Mexican
gardener and made the sounds of Benny's ancient Maxwell automobile.
   In later years, he became the voice on numerous commercials and
gave life to many Saturday morning cartoon characters.
</TEXT>
