<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 2032EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TreatyOak     07-03 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Treaty Oak,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Workers Labor to Save Historic Tree</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT ROTHSCHILD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The historic Treaty Oak, which has provided
shade for generations of Texans, will itself be shaded as part of
the effort to save the majestic tree that was poisoned with a
herbicide.
   ``The whole plan of attack is to try and minimize the stress on
the tree,'' Paul Roberts, an environmental specialist with the
Austin Parks and Recreation Department, said Monday.
   Later this week, 40-foot screens will be stretched across sets of
poles on the east and west sides of the 65-foot-high, centuries-old
tree. The mesh screens are made of a fabric similar to the kind used
to block sun and wind at tennis courts.
   ``There is tender foliage up there. It would be real easy to fry
it,'' Roberts said. He said the screens will reduce sunlight hitting
the tree by 50 percent to 60 percent.
   ``We're coming into a real stressful period for the tree. We can
expect upper 90s, 100-degrees for the next two months,'' he said.
   Legend has it Stephen F. Austin, the father of Texas, made peace
with Indians under the tree's branches.
   Leaves have turned brown and fallen off the tree since it was
poisoned with the potent herbicide Velpar, in what police say was a
ritual act to cast a spell or curse. Police have charged a man with
criminal mischief; he could get 20 years in prison.
   Workers are replacing soil that was excavated around the tree to
a depth of about 30 inches to remove any herbicide residue.
   In addition, 12 sprinkler heads have been placed in the tree's
canopy to mist the foliage with water five minutes per hour to cool
the tree, Roberts said.
   Latest test results indicate the tree was poisoned with more
Velpar than first suspected, nearly three times the amount needed to
kill the tree.
   But tree experts determined the poison did not seep as far down
in the ground as had been feared, said Bill Edelbrock, another
environmental specialist with the parks department.
   The poison travels through a plant's roots and into the leaves,
and when the leaves fall the poison they contain soaks into the
ground and the cycle begins again, Edelbrock said. ``We're out there
raking up leaves every day,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
