<FIRST>r w AM-Scotus-Labeling     07-03 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Labeling,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>States Can Enact Tougher Hazardous Substances Laws</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Monday refused to bar
states from imposing rules on labeling hazardous workplace
substances that are more rigorous or extensive than federal
regulations.
   The court, without comment, rejected a challenge to a New Jersey
law by business and industry representatives who said federal law
preempts such state rules.
   The 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last February upheld a
federal judge's ruling that allowed New Jersey officials to enforce
that state's Worker and Community Right to Know Act of 1983.
   The appeals court said the judge was ``not clearly erroneous'' in
deciding the state law ``does not stand as an obstacle to the
accomplishment of the purposes'' of the federal Occupational Safety
and Health Act of 1970.
   The two laws are similar in their aim, requiring employers to
warn workers of hazardous materials. The New Jersey law also is
intended to warn the public about potential threats to the
environment.
   The state law goes further than the federal law in some respects.
New Jersey requires all chemical containers to be labeled, while the
federal law requires only containers of hazardous chemicals to be
labeled.
   The state requires that the five most predominant substances in a
mixture be labeled; the federal law does not.
   And New Jersey requires most labels to include the chemical name
and a special number used to identify the substance. The federal law
requires the chemical or common name, but not the number.
   The state law was challenged by the New Jersey Chamber of
Commerce and numerous chemical, flavor and fragrance manufacturers.
   They said dual labeling would confuse and overwhelm workers.
   The 2nd Circuit court said there was adequate testimony by
opposing experts that proper worker training would clear up any
confusion.
   The cases are New Jersey Chamber of Commerce vs. Hughey, 88-1845,
and Fragrance Materials Association vs. Van Note, 88-1868.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890703-0183 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 1734EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Bush-Abortion     07-03 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Abortion,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Hails Supreme Court Decision on Abortion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Monday hailed the
Supreme Court decision on abortion as a beginning ``to restore to
the people the ability to protect the unborn.''
   But a top aide said Bush does not plan to campaign on the issue
in the states that now will have the power to restrict abortions.
   The president also cautioned Americans who have strong feelings
on the issue to ``continue to express their deeply held convictions
on this subject within the bounds of civility and our legal
institutions.''
   In a two-paragraph statement released by his staff while he was
on the golf course during his five-day Maine vacation, Bush said:
``We welcome this decision ... The court appears to have begun to
restore to the people the ability to protect the unborn.''
   Chief of Staff John Sununu told reporters that Bush continues to
support a so-called human life amendment to the Constitution that
would bar abortion.
   Anti-abortion members of Congress have repeatedly pressed for
such an amendment without success.
   Bush supports the approach of Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., said
Sununu. However, Hyde has not introduced a constitutional amendment,
but rather an amendment to the Health and Human Services
approprations bill that would bar use of federal funds for abortion
except when the mother's life is endangered.
   Bush's position on abortion is that it should be allowed only in
cases of rape, incest or endangerment to the life of the mother.
   While Sununu was briefing reporters, Bush was playing golf for
much of the afternoon. The president deflected questions on the
abortion issue from reporters who accompanied him to the golf
course, referring them to the statement his staff released.
   ``Not when I'm doing this,'' he said swinging his golf club. His
written statement, he said, would express his ``very strong
feelings. My position is very well known and now I'd like to
concentrate on something else.''
   Sununu said Bush had been on the telephone with White House legal
counsel Boyden Gray and other advisers talking about the ``legal
nuances'' of the ruling. He said it would merit further analysis,
but that Bush wished initially to put out a statement expressing his
support for the direction the court took.
   ``This is the kind of issue that he is strongly supportive of but
he understands that it moves now out into the states.''
   With Monday's court decision restoring to the states the powers
to restrict abortion rights, Sununu noted, many states now will see
legislative efforts to restrict abortion. Bush does not intend to
personally lead the crusade for legal changes in those states, said
Sununu.
   ``He would probably continue to speak on it as a national issue
rather than carrying the concern into the state capitals,'' Sununu
said.
   Asked about a controversy that arose in last year's presidential
campaign when Bush indicated during a debate with Democratic
contender Michael Dukakis that a woman who has an abortion should be
penalized, Sununu said that Bush did not want that result from
future state laws on abortion.
   ``When laws are written, we would hope that they would focus on
those who perform the abortion.''
   Bush's staff hastened after last year's debate to say that Bush
had not intended to call for penalties against women who had
abortions.
   The Monday ruling stopped short of overturning the historic 1973
Supreme Court Roe Vs. Wade decision legalizing abortion.
   Bush said in his statement that that decision ``was incorrectly
decided and should be reversed.''
   The president opposes violent activism such as the arson fire at
a Concord abortion clinic that occurred just hours before Monday's
high court ruling, said Sununu.
   ``Violent protest is against the law. Whoever is involved in that
should be apprehended and punished.'' he added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
