<DOCNO> AP890703-0190 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 2035EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-WeaponsBuying     07-03 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weapons Buying,370</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Study Says Independent Body Should Buy Pentagon's Weapons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration should set up a weapons
``procurement corps'' independent of the Pentagon to eliminate
conflicts of interest in Defense Department buying practices, a
private group study said Monday.
   ``The only way to stop the arming of our military with defective
weapons is to take responsibility for buying those weapons away from
the military,'' said Louis Nemeth, co-author of the study by the
Ralph Nader's Center for Study of Responsive Law.
   ``We're spending billions of dollars for planes that can't fly,
missiles that can't find their destinations and tanks that can't
roll,'' Nemeth said. ``The Pentagon has over and over proven itself
unwilling or unable to improve our procurement process.''
   The study cited a number of reasons for the Pentagon's weapons
problems, including overreliance on new technologies, insufficient
testing of new weapons, inadequate competition among contract
bidders and a ``revolving door'' between the Pentagon procurement
system and private defense contractors.
   It also blamed members of Congress for judging new weapons
projects on the potential economic payoff for their own state or
district rather than the actual need for the weapons.
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney recently forwarded to President
Bush a package of recommendations for improving management of the
Pentagon, including changes in the procurement process. Details of
Cheney's recommendations have not been made public.
   The Nader group's study cited numerous weapons systems that have
been plagued by previously reported problems, including the
Midgetman and MX Peacekeeper intercontinental ballistic missiles,
the M-1 Abrams tank, the F-14 Tomcat fighter jet and the Bradley
Fighting Vehicle. It said this formed a pattern of ineffective
Pentagon control of procurement that undermines U.S. security.
   Among the study's recommended reforms:
   _Establish a ``procurement'' corps of weapons experts independent
of the Defense Department and the military services, to manage all
phases of weapons system acquisition. It would analyze the services'
weapons requests, determine when development of new systems was
needed, award production contracts and oversee testing.
   _Increase competitive bidding, in part by inviting foreign
military contractors to participate in design competitions.
   _End the practice of beginning production of a new weapon system
before the development stage has been completed.
</TEXT>
