<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 2036EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Baker-Asia     07-03 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baker-Asia,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker, En Route to Japan, Seeks Stable Relations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ELMENDORF AIR FORCE BASE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James
A. Baker III was flying to Japan Monday, intent on keeping
U.S.-Japanese relations on an even keel despite the setbacks
suffered by the government of Prime Minister Sosuke Uno.
   Talking to reporters while en route here for a refueling stop,
Baker said it is important to ``studiously avoid involving ourselves
in the internal affairs of the government of Japan.''
   Uno's Liberal Democratic Party was handed a stinging defeat in
municipal elections Monday, and the prime minister has been fighting
allegations that he kept several paid mistresses. Uno has denied the
reports.
   Baker was asked whether inviting Uno to a dinner Tuesday evening
was an attempt to deflect attention from Uno's problems.
   Baker indicated that he disagreed with the premise of the
question.
   He said stability in U.S.-Japanese relations is important not
just for the Pacific region but for the world as a whole.
   During his talks in Tokyo, Baker said he will emphasize the need
for the world's two largest economies to form a ``global
partnership.''
   Some analysts believe that the accumulation of problems over the
past month may force Uno to resign soon.
   The main purpose of Baker's visit is to take part in a conference
of donor nations on a proposed $10 billion, five-year multilateral
assistance and investment program for the Philippines.
   The meeting is being held under the sponsorship of the World Bank
with participation by the European Economic Community, Canada,
Australia and the United States, among others.
   The Bush administration has asked Congress for $200 million as
the U.S. contribution for the first year.
   Baker said he strongly supports the multilateral effort, arguing
that the Philippines is now on a democratic path and still faces a
determined communist insurgency.
   Questioned on another subject, Baker said he didn't find it
``particularly disturbing'' that two communists have been named to
the newly formed cabinet in Greece, a NATO ally.
   Baker noted that the coalition government in Greece has only a
three-month life expectancy and that, in any case, neither of the
posts occupied by communists deals with defense or foreign policy.
   After a day in Tokyo, Baker will fly to Brunei where he will meet
with his colleagues from the six-nation Association of Southeast
Asian Nations.
   One goal of that meeting is to try to find ways of avoiding civil
war in Cambodia after Vietnamese forces complete their scheduled
troop withdrawal in September.
   After two days in Brunei, Baker heads for Poland where he will
link up with President Bush for his four-nation European visit.
   He has a rest stop of a day and a half in Oman en route to Poland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
