<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 1800EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-BlackCatholics     07-03 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Black Catholics,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspension of Priest ``Virtually Assured'' for Starting New Church</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. George Stallings, founder of an
unauthorized new congregation for black Catholics, is ``virtually
assured'' of being suspended as a priest, a Roman Catholic official
said Monday.
   ``The penalty is given in such cases not for punishment, but in
hopes of reconciliation,'' said the Rev. William Lori, secretary to
Cardinal James A. Hickey, archbishop of Washington. He said he
thought Hickey would act ``quite soon.''
   Lori said Hickey might make a decision by Wednesday, three days
after Stallings celebrated the first mass of his Imani Temple.
   Should Stallings be suspended, he would lose his right to preach,
celebrate mass or officiate at weddings and funerals, Lori said.
   Efforts to reach Stallings by telephone for comment were
unsuccessful.
   Stallings, a convert to Catholicism, said Sunday, ``The church
can't throw me out, and even if they do throw me out, I have my own
opinion ... they have theirs.''
   He said he created his congregation because the established Roman
Catholic Church is not responsive to the cultural and spiritual
needs of black parishioners.
   The church hierarchy is not opposed to Stallings' efforts, only
the way he is going about them, said Lori, the cardinal's secretary.
   ``As Catholics, we look to the bishop for overall guidance on
when to establish a new parish,'' Lori said. ``We can't have a
priest setting up a new parish and saying, `Hey, we have a better
product over here.'''
   Eileen Marks, a spokeswoman for the archdiocese, said that more
than 40 parishes in the Washington area incorporate elements of the
African-American culture Stallings plans to emphasize in his
services.
   The ceremony at his church Sunday included traditional Catholic
prayers and liturgy, along with elements borrowed from African and
Southern black revival traditions. Black representatives of other
faiths, including Baptists and Muslims, attended to show support for
Stallings' move.
   At one point, Stallings told his congregation, ``We can't wait.
How much longer does the Roman Catholic Church need?''
   Later, he said, ``We can't just be sitting on the pew anymore.
We've got to start standing up on the promises.''
   Since Stallings announced his plans two weeks ago, he has been on
a collision course with church leaders.
   ``In spite of his claims to the contrary, Father Stallings'
action is a serious step toward separating himself from the Roman
Catholic Church,'' Hickey said recently in a statement.
   ``This situation has more to do with the needs and expectations
of Father Stallings than with broader questions about the adequacy
of Catholic ministry within the black community,'' Hickey said.
   Lori said Monday, ``Suspension is virtually assured.''
   Stallings said last week he had been fired by Hickey as
evangelist for the archdiocese, but Lori said no official action had
yet been taken.
   If Stallings is suspended, church officials will continue meeting
with him in hopes of solving their differences, Lori said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
