<FIRST>r w AM-US-PLO     07-03 0121</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-PLO</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Official Denies Meetings With Arafat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. envoy holding discussions with
mid-level Palestine Liberation Organization officials has not met
PLO chief Yasser Arafat, a State Department official said Monday.
   Radio Israel's report that Robert Pelletreau, the U.S. ambassador
to Tunis, has twice met Arafat is ``categorically denied,'' the
official said. He declined, however, to be quoted by name.
   The Radio Israel broadcast quoted a Kuwait newspaper's Monday
report as the source of its information.
   Pelletreau has been holding occasional talks since the end of
1988 with lower-ranking PLO officers after the U.S. government said
Arafat had met its conditions for the discussions by renouncing use
of violence and recognizing Israel's right to exist.
</TEXT>
