<FIRST>u i AM-Gromyko-Reax     07-03 0714</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gromyko-Reax,0738</SECOND>
<HEAD>World Leaders Recall Gromyko's Toughness upon His Death</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Obit-Gromyko</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   World leaders recalled Andrei Gromyko's toughness and tenacity
upon word of his death Monday, but former President Richard M. Nixon
summed it all up _ ``Gromyko was above all a survivor in the most
ruthless sytem in the world.''
   Nixon, himself no stranger to crises, noted that as Soviet
foreign minister Gromyko served leaders as different as Josef
Stalin, Nikita Khrushchev, Leonid Brezhnev, Yuri Andropov and
Konstantin Chernenko.
   ``While I generally knew him as an adversary, I also respected
him as one of the most tenacious and able diplomats of the
post-World War II era,'' Nixon said.
   Gromyko, later Soviet president, died at the age of 79 in the
Soviet Union on Sunday. President Mikahil S. Gorbachev announced the
death Monday in a session of the Supreme Soviet legislature.
   President Bush also noted Gromyko's long service in a statement
expressing his condolences and those of his wife Barbara.
   ``Gromyko's career paralleled the course of U.S.-Soviet relations
for nearly 50 years,'' Bush said. ``Mr. Gromyko knew every U.S.
president from Franklin Roosevelt to Geroge Bush ... Andrei
Gromyko's death marks the passing of a generation that witnessed
many of the most historic events of this century.''
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar messaged Gorbachev
to express ``profound sorrow'' over the death. He described Gromyko
as ``one of the foremost architects'' of world society after World
War II.
   ``The absence of another such global conflict, as well as the
peace and stability enjoyed by his own continent over the past four
decades, owes much to his experience and wisdom,'' the message said.
   Perez de Cuellar arrived in Geneva on Monday for the 1989 session
of the U.N. Economic and Social Council.
   Former British prime ministers Ted Heath, a Conservative, and
Lord Callaghan, a Laborite, harkened back to their experiences with
Gromyko.
   ``He was more notorious, perhaps, for saying `no' than for his
constructive work, but in the negotiations which led to the
successful conclusion of the first Test Ban Treaty in 1963, he
played a positive part. ... For the next 15 years he pursued the
same purpose with the consequent decrease in tension between East
and West,'' said Heath, who was prime minister from 1970-74.
   ``He was a good executor of a bad foreign policy that has now
changed,'' said Callaghan, who, as James Callaghan, was foreign
secretary in a Labor government from 1974-76 and prime minister from
1976-79.
   Callaghan called Gromyko ``a very hard man to negotiate with. .
.. He represented Soviet foreign policy at a time when it was
expansionist and dogmatic. Toward the end of his period, especially
as president, he softened and I was astonished when he described me
as a good friend.''
   Spanish Foreign minister Francisco Fernandez Ordonez sent a
message expressing condolences to his Soviet counterpart Eduard
Shevarndnadze.
   Abba Eban, Israel's foreign minister in 1966-1974, said on Israel
radio that Gromyko ``no doubt, was the high priest of diplomacy. He
was no prophet or reformist, and he owed his remarkable survival to
his ability to adjust to many successful leaders.''
   Recalling the days leading to the November 1947 U.N. decision on
the partition of Palestine, Eban said:
   ``The image of Gromyko is engraved in the memory as a positive
one.
   ``The surprising day was in April when Gromyko rose up at the
preparatory U.N. meeting ... and announced that there are two
possibilites. One is a federal state with Jewish and Arab cantons.
And if there is no agreement on it, we should not rule out the
possibility of dividing the land into two states, a Jewish one and
an Arab one. It changed all the prognoses and for the first time we
saw a real chance for success.
   ``This was a pleasant surprise because none of us could predict
this development. The assumption was that the Stalinist regime was
anti-Zionist and anti-Jewish in principle.''
   But Eban noted that ``the main strategic task of the Soviet Union
was to drive out the West that was then represented by Great
Britain.''
   And Eban also recollected about Gromyko:
   `He had that sorrowful expression, it was so characteristic of
him.
   ``I had said once that he smiled like a blue lamp in a
refrigerator.''
</TEXT>
