<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Israel     07-03 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Israel,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Security Council Postpones Meeting on Israeli-Occupied Territories</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Security Council on Monday postponed a
scheduled meeting on the Israeli-occupied territories, and diplomats
said the United States sought to water down criticism of Israel's
latest deportations.
   The meeting was rescheduled for Wednesday at 11 a.m.
   European diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
delay was caused by a U.S. bid to tone down language in a resolution
on Israel's expulsion of eight Palestinians from ``deplore'' to
``regret.''
   The U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, Thomas R. Pickering,
would not comment on language used in the draft resolution and said
only, ``We will continue to hold discussions.''
   Other diplomatic sources suggested the United States wanted to
hold off on the resolution until after Israeli Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc meets to consider Shamir's
peace plan. Shamir has proposed elections in the occupied
territories to choose Arab representatives to negotiate limited
autonomy with Israel.
   Last week Israel deported eight Palestinians from the Gaza Strip
and West Bank to neighboring Lebanon, saying they were leaders of
the Palestinian uprising against Israeli rule.
   The United States, as one of five permanent members of the
Security Council, could veto any measure critical of its Israeli
ally. Last year the United States supported one resolution calling
on Israel not to expel Palestinians and it abstained from another
measure of condemnation.
   Israel has deported 55 Palestinians from the occupied territories
since the Palestinian uprising began 19 months ago. At least 538
Palestinians and 23 Israelis have been killed in the so-called
intefadeh for independence from Israel.
   The proposed resolution, sponsored by Syria and the Arab League,
deplores the deportations by Israel. It calls upon Israel to ensure
immediate return to the territories of deported Palestinians and to
stop deporting Arab civilians.
   It cites the Geneva Convention of 1949, which covers treatment of
civilians in time of war and prohibits their explusions.
   The council members are Algeria, Brazil, Canada, Colombia,
Ethiopia, Finland, Nepal, Malaysia, Senegal, Yugoslavia and the five
permanent members, the United States, the Soviet Union, Britain,
China and France.
</TEXT>
