<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 1834EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Mexico     07-03 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mounting Cries of Fraud in Five Mexican State Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN WRIGHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICALI, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leaders from left and right
accused Mexico's long-governing Institutional Revolutionary Party on
Monday of committing fraud in state elections that officials
promised would be clean.
   The charges came after the party, known as PRI in Spanish,
claimed victories in four of the five states that held elections for
new legislatures and mayors Sunday.
   In Baja California, which also chose a new governor, Margarita
Ortega, 38, of the PRI and Ernesto Ruffo, 37, of the conservative
National Action Party both claimed victory.
   Parties in this border state were basing claims on their own
counts and projections. By law, election boards have until July 9 to
announce official returns.
   If he wins, Ruffo, a former mayor of Ensenada, will become the
first opposition governor in Mexico since the PRI was founded and
took power 60 years ago.
   National Action leaders in Baja California and leaders of the
leftist Democratic Revolutionary Party, running a tight race for the
state legislature in Michoacan, complained of balloting irregularies.
   ``The PRI has taken the decision to impose itself at whatever
cost,'' Cuauhtemoc Cardenas told a news conference Monday.
   Cardenas is the Democratic Revolutionary leader and a native son
of Michoacan.
   PRI-dominated electoral commissions in Baja California and
Chihuahua said irregularities existed, but denied they were
important or affected the results. In Michoacan, the PRI accused the
leftist opposition of irregularities.
   The opposition complained that ballot boxes were stolen, voter
credentials were burned, and voter registration rolls were tampered
with so many people could not cast ballots when they showed up at
polling stations.
   Congressman Norberto Corrella said he and other National Action
workers spent the night recovering ballot boxes stolen by PRI
workers. Corella said PRI workers stuffed the boxes and planned to
turn them over to the election commission in Mexicali, the state
capital.
   ``We recovered 17 ballot boxes,'' Corrella said, and complained
that tampered boxes ``all of a sudden'' showed the PRI winning
10-to-1. He said he filed complaints with the election commission
and the district attorney's office.
   Similarly, the Citizens' Action Committee of Human Development
reported 266 irregularities that included multiple voting, people
casting ballots without registration cards and harassment of
opposition poll watchers at the state's 1,166 polling places.
   The PRI said it also won a majority of the state legislature's 19
seats, but gave no figures.
   In Michoacan, the PRI said it won in 10 districts and led in
others and would get a majority of the 24 seats in the state
legislature.
   Opposition leaders and many reporters who watched the polls said
voter registration rolls were altered, other documents were tampered
with and many people were kept from voting.
   In elections for mayors in Chihuahua, where PRI said it was
ahead, National Action leaders complained that many PRI sympathizers
voted several times and that indelible ink to mark voters' fingers
to prevent fraud either was removed or was not indelible.
   The PRI claimed victories in its strongholds of Campeche and
Zacatecas, also electing state legislatures.
   Reports of turnouts ranged from 30 to 65 percent, depending on
which party was doing the reporting. Official figures were not
available.
   President Carlos Salinas de Gortari has been promising clean
elections since he took office Dec. 1. But National Action spokesman
Jesus Hernandez in Ciudad Juarez called this ``just words.''
   ``These elections were dirty,'' he told reporters Sunday night.
   Baja California and Michoacan held center stage Sunday because
voters in both states gave Salinas one-third or less of their votes
in July 1988 presidential elections.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
