<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-03 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heavy Rain In The Southeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms with locally heavy rain were scattered
across much of the southeastern quarter of the nation Monday, and
extended northward into the Ohio Valley.
   Thunderstorms brought heavy rain to western sections of the
Carolinas and the central Gulf Coast.
   Some streets and small streams flooded in the Columbus, Ga.,
area, where 3.42 inches of rain fell in the six hours up to 2 p.m.
EDT, the National Weather Service said. Heavy rain also fell around
the Atlanta area, which got 1.37 inches in the same period.
   During the same six hours, 3.21 inches fell at Clemson, S.C., and
Montgomery, Ala., got 1.22 inches.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered from Florida to the
Middle Atlantic States.
   Thunderstorms associated with a weak cold front were scattered
over upper Michigan and northern Wisconsin.
   Elsewhere, a few showers were scattered along the coast of the
Pacific Northwest, and there were a few thunderstorms along the
eastern slopes of the Colorado Rockies.
   Temperatures in the lower deserts of Arizona and California were
well over 100 degrees by noon. Record heat is possible during the
next couple of days over sections of Colorado, Utah and Arizona
because of an upper-level high-pressure system. Readings in Phoenix
could reach near 115 degrees, the weather service said.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 58
degrees at Quillayute, Wash., to 109 at Phoenix and Palm Springs,
Calif. Monday's low in the Lower 48 states was 28 at Truckee, Calif.
   The forecast for Tuesday called for scattered showers and
thunderstorms from the East Coast to the Ohio, Tennessee and lower
Mississippi valleys and the eastern and southern sections of Texas,
and a few showers in the Pacific Northwest.
   Highs in the 70s were predicted along the California coast; in
the 60s and 70s in the Pacific Northwest; in the 80s in the Rockies,
and from the Mississippi Valley to the East Coast; in the 90s in
Florida; in the 90s to almost 100 degrees in the great Plains, the
Intermountain region between the Rockies and the Sierra Nevada, and
interior valleys of California; and between 100 and 115 degrees in
the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
