<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 2042EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AtlantaFire     07-03 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Atlanta Fire,0548</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigator Concluded Seven Years Ago Peachtree 25th Was `Fire Trap'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire investigator concluded seven years ago that
a 10-story office building which burned last week, killing five
people, was a ``firetrap,'' officials confirmed Monday.
   A woman who had been in critical condition since the fire died
Monday at Piedmont Hospital, said Sgt. Steve Martin of the Fulton
County Medical Examiner's Office.
   Fire officials said their investigation continues to point to an
electrical worker who apparently triggered an explosion while
changing a fuse.
   An inspector from the Atlanta Bureau of Fire examined the
Peachtree 25th building in July 1982, and concluded a disaster was
possible if fire broke out in the sprinklerless building, Acting
Fire Chief Tom Perrin said Monday.
   ``When he conducted his investigation some years back, he felt
like it was a firetrap,'' Perrin said. He added that at the time the
investigator, now a lieutenant with the fire department, did
``stipulate some things that needed to be done.''
   Perrin said the lieutenant reminded him of the 1982 inspection on
Friday, hours after the fatal fire at the midtown building.
Officials want more information from the lieutenant but he has since
left on vacation and will not be back for a few days, the chief said.
   The building apparently underwent some renovations in July 1982,
around the time of the lieutenant's inspection, but the
investigative file is inconclusive as to whether the renovations
would have placed the building under any additional code
requirements, said Deputy Chief A.D. Bell.
   ``We're still looking at how much renovation was conducted at
that time, and that would determine what type of codes would have to
be abided by,'' Bell said. ``Once we can determine that ... we can
ascertain what should or should not have been done.''
   American Management Co. of Torrance, Calif., which manages the
Peachtree 25th building, referred reporters to a representative of
its Atlanta office, Ken Poole, who did not return a reporter's call.
   Perrin said investigators were ``getting close'' to knowing
exactly what happened Friday, and believe the electrical repairman
was involved when he tried to change a fuse following a power outage.
   ``On that floor, where he had inserted the 200-amp fuse, we feel
... when he inserted that fuse, with the current still on, that's
what caused the explosion, and that's what caused the fire,'' Perrin
said.
   Perrin said errors on someone's part apparently contributed to
the fire, but declined to elaborate.
   The investigation could be finished this week, he said.
   Perrin said firefighters responding to the fire turned in a
textbook performance in saving people, but might have been able to
work faster if they'd had more help. Bureau officials estimate that
Atlanta's fire department, with about 1,070 employees, is about 105
short of its minimum needs.
   ``We're really strained,'' Perrin said. ``We don't have the
manpower we need for a major city. ... It's time to quit playing
games.''
   Bureau of Fire officials have been asking for more manpower for
about seven years, but have been thwarted by budget considerations,
officials said Monday.
   Several of the more than 30 people injured remained hospitalized
Monday.
</TEXT>
