<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador     07-03 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salvadoran Rebels Attack Army Post, Try Ambush Chief Justice</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas attacked a
military guard post in the capital early Monday after they tried and
failed to ambush a car carrying the nation's chief justice.
   Three people were reported killed and three wounded in the two
attacks.
   An army news release said rebels opened fire with automatic
weapons and rocket-propelled grenades on the military post guarding
a San Salvador residential suburb southwest of the capital where
many army officers live.
   Witnesses said the grenade explosions and rattle of gunfire at
dawn sent many residents in the Arce neighborhood tumbling out of
their beds. They said several officers rushed out of their homes in
pajamas or shorts, assault rifles in hand, and helped repel the
attack.
   The army said no military men were hurt, and the dead body of a
guerrilla, seen lying across the street from the guard post,
appeared to be the only casualty of the 30-minute gun battle.
   In a broadcast over their clandestine Radio Venceremos, the
Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front rebels said the attack was
part of a renewed action ``against the officers who command the
Salvadoran war.''
   At estimated 75,000 people have been killed since the rebels
started fighting for power in October 1979.
   On Sunday, Supreme Court Chief Justice Mauricio Gutierrez Castro
said another group of rebels tried but failed to ambush him and his
family as they drove back from a day at a beach near the port of La
Libertad.
   Gutierrez told a television news show Monday morning he was
grazed by a bullet in the neck, but that one of several bodyguards
riding in a second car behind the family was killed and another was
wounded.
   Authorities said a woman driving a car on the same road also was
killed and a male companion was wounded during the attempted ambush
about 10 miles south of the capital.
   Gutierrez said his bodyguards opened fire when they saw the
rebels had blocked the road with a parked bus, and the guerrillas
returned the fire. He said his driver made a quick U-turn and sped
away from the fighting.
   ``I don't think it was an attack on me personally, as they had no
way of knowing I would be traveling on that road,'' Gutierrez said.
   President Alfredo Cristiani named Gutierrez, a conservative,
chief justice last week. Cristiani was sworn in June 1 after being
elected on the rightist Republican Nationalist Alliance ticket.
   Gunmen in June killed Antonio Rodriguez Porth, Cristiani's chief
of staff, and several others were slain later in similar attacks.
The government has blamed the guerrillas for the assassinations, but
the rebels have denied responsibility.
</TEXT>
