<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 2046EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-HungaryBroadcasting     07-03 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Hungary Broadcasting,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. to Open Budapest Studios in Budapest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radio Free Europe and Radio Liberty said Monday
they will open a full-time news bureau and transmission studios
later this summer in Budapest, Hungary, the first in a Soviet-bloc
country for the U.S.-financed broadcast systems.
   Hungary announced in March that Radio Free Europe would be
allowed to accredit a reporter to work in Hungary without any
restrictions.
   The new Budapest bureau ``will provide an invaluable window for
our newspeople and analysts covering events in Eastern Europe,''
said Gene Pell, president of Raqdio Free Europe and Radio Liberty,
which broadcasts to Soviet-bloc countries from Munich, West Germany.
   ``We welcome this development as a sign of the Hungarian
government's growing acceptance of the free flow of information and
ideas,'' Pell said.
   The announcement said other journalists from Munich headquarters
will make frequent visits to Hungary on reporting assignments, it
added.
   For years Hungary accused Radio Free Europe of meddling in its
internal activities. Accusations were also raised in the United
States and elsewhere that Radio Free Europe broadcasts in 1956
falsely encouraged the Hungarian people to expect U.S. and Western
support of the anti-Soviet uprising quelled by Soviet tanks that
year.
   Radio Free Europe broadcasts to Eastern Europe and Radio Liberty
to the Soviet Union in 23 languages for a total of more than 1,000
hours a week. News of the region unobtainable in official media
forms a heavy proportion of the broadcasts.
   Under its new ``glasnost,'' or openness, policy, the Soviet Union
ended 35 years of jamming Radio Liberty last November. Hungary and
Poland much earlier halted interference while Czechoslovakia and
Bulgaria stopped jamming in December.
</TEXT>
