<FIRST>r i AM-Argentina     07-03 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Furor Over Convicted Navy Chief Seen on Street, Not in Jail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By OSCAR SERRAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal court on Monday ordered
the Defense Ministry to explain why a former junta member sentenced
to life in prison for human rights abuses was seen walking in the
city last week.
   Defense Minister Horacio Jaunarena said Sunday that former navy
chief Emilio Massera, 63, was given permission to leave Magdalena
military prison to be treated for a liver ailment at the naval
hospital in the capital, 60 miles away.
   But a photographer spotted Massera on Friday outside a building
about 60 blocks from the hospital. The newspaper Nuevo Sur published
the pictures on page one Saturday.
   Massera, a member of the junta that ousted President Isabel Peron
in March 1976, was convicted in December 1985 of human rights abuses
under the military dictatorship.
   Security forces arrested at least 8,960 purported leftists who
then vanished and are presumed to have been killed.
   A civilian government ended military rule in December 1983.
   The Massera incident caused an outcry.
   Attorney Eduardo Barcesat, a member of the Argentine League for
the Rights of Man, called it ``an affront to civilian rule and shows
the military is mocking justice.''
   Hernan Patino Mayer, a military adviser to President-elect Carlos
Menem, said, ``I knew the outgoing government had lost control of
the situation, but I didn't think it had gone so far.'' Menem,
elected on May 14, is to take office on Saturday, succeeding
President Raul Alfonsin.
   Justice Minister-designate Julio Oyhanarte said, ``If it is
confirmed that Massera was released from prison (on his own
recognizance), that would be really scandalous.''
   Civilian courts sentenced Massera and six other officers for
human rights offenses before Alfonsin, sensing military unrest,
pushed through Congress a partial amnesty that sheltered about 1,100
others from prosecution.
   The army staged insurrections in April 1987 and January and
December 1988 to force trials to end. Three admirals and 15 generals
still face prosecution.
   Menem says he will act quickly on the issue, but gives no
specifics. He and his aides indicated he favors calling off the
trials and possibly pardoning officers already convicted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
