<FIRST>u w BC-Scotus-AbortionVotes 2ndLd-Writethru a06erScottMcCartney
07-03 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Scotus-Abortion Votes, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0652,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS grafs 5-7 1st Ld bgng: ``By a 6-3,'' with 4 grafs bgng
``The court,' to CORRECT that court ruled Missouri's ban on use of tax
money has become moot, picks up 10th graf 1st Ld, now 11th graf: ``O'Connor's
reasons,''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court decision Monday reinstating
key provisions of a Missouri abortion law yielded five separate
opinions _ 78 pages in all.
   The five basic votes in the majority came from Chief Justice
William H. Rehnquist and Justices Sandra Day O'Connor, Antonin
Scalia, Byron R. White and Anthony M. Kennedy. The four basic
dissenting votes were cast by Justices Harry A. Blackmun, John Paul
Stevens, Thurgood Marshall and William Brennan.
   Rehnquist, O'Connor, Scalia, Blackmun and Stevens filed written
opinions.
   Here is a breakdown of the significant votes in the case:
   The court ruled unanimously that the Missouri provision banning
the use of tax money for ``encouraging or counseling'' women to have
abortions not necessary to save life has become moot.
   The court voted 5-4 that Missouri, and other states as well, may
ban abortions in public hospitals or by public employees.
   The majority consisted of Rehnquist, O'Connor, Scalia, White and
Kennedy. The minority included Blackmun, Marshall, Brennan and
Stevens.
   By a 5-4 vote, the court upheld the Missouri provision that
doctors may have to determine whether a fetus at least 20 weeks old
is capable of surviving outside the womb, by determining lung
maturity and other testing.
   O'Connor's reasons differed from the other four.
   By a 5-4 vote, the court ruled that part of the Missouri law
declaring that the ``life of each human being begins at conception''
and that ``unborn children have protectable interests in life,
health and well-being'' is not a live controversy because the
declaration has no legal impact. Stevens, Blackmun, Marshall and
Brennan dissented.
   Four justices _ Rehnquist, White, Kennedy and Scalia _ voiced
support for scrapping the trimester-by-trimester approach in Roe vs.
Wade. Only Scalia called for the outright reversal of Roe vs. Wade.
</TEXT>
