<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Poland     07-03 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Poland,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kohl Drops Hope of Visiting Poland This Month; Talks Stalled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Germany said Monday that
Chancellor Helmut Kohl has dropped any plans to visit Poland this
month, and obstacles persist in talks aimed at binding up wounds
between the two countries.
   The two nations have been negotiating for six months on West
German economic aid in exchange for Polish recognition of its German
minority.
   It is believed the Polish government is not satisfied with the
amount of economic aid _ not disclosed _ that has been offered by
the West Germans. Poland is in an economic crisis.
   A final agreement and a visit by Kohl would be a symbolic boost
toward patching up bad feelings that predate Nazi Germany's 1939
invasion of Poland.
   But chief government spokesman Hans Klein said Kohl no longer is
thinking about going to Poland this month.
   Klein on Monday cited ``questions'' remaining in the negotiations
and a changing political scene in Poland.
   He said a visit this year cannot be excluded, but acknowledged no
definite date has been set for that or for the next round of
negotiations.
   The last round recessed on June 26.
   Klein said a Kohl visit ``should not be put under any pressures
of time.''
   He also said Kohl believes it will be ``in the best interests of
both sides'' to wait and see what changes will result in Poland
because of the changing political scene there.
   The Solidarity trade union has been scoring major political gains
in Poland at the expense of the governing Communist Party.
   Klein told reporters that Bonn solidly supports reforms under way
in Poland.
   ``The chancellor has underlined his great interest in supporting
the Polish reform process,'' Klein said.
   Lack of movement in Polish relations has been a nagging foreign
policy disappointment for Kohl's coalition government. The coalition
has built on earlier agreements with other East European countries
and considerably expanded its political, economic and cultural ties
in the region.
   West German officials want more recognition of ethnic Germans in
Poland, including teaching of German language in schools.
   Polish officials said they agreed to Bonn's conditions, but
disagreement remains on the issue of economic assistance.
</TEXT>
