<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 2133EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MonkeyHerpes     07-03 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Monkey Herpes,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawsuit Says Ex-Lab Worker Was Never Warned of Deadly Monkey Virus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former monkey handler at a research lab
sued the company, alleging he was not told that many of the animals
carry a deadly virus until after it killed a co-worker.
   Terrence Young said in a complaint filed in U.S. District Court
on Friday that unsafe working conditions at International Research
and Development Corp. of Mattawan may have exposed him to the herpes
B virus.
   The virus is found in more than 50 percent of rhesus monkeys, a
type of macaque, which are used in many laboratory experiments. The
virus is relatively harmless to the animals but has an estimated 70
percent mortality rate among humans once symptoms appear.
   Herpes B commonly is transmitted through bites and scratches.
Only about 30 cases of human infection have been documented in the
last 57 years.
   Young was employed at the company from April 28 to May 28. He
alleges in the complaint that he often was bitten and scratched
while handling monkeys.
   On one occasion, a monkey bit him so hard that a tooth penetrated
his thumbnail and went completely through his thumb, Young said. He
said he was treated by a staff nurse who told him the wound ``was
nothing to worry about.''
   Young also said protective gear for monkey handlers was
inadequate, including leather gloves with holes in them and a body
suit that was neither bite- nor puncture-proof.
   About a month after he quit, Young was given company forms
detailing the hazards of working with monkeys and the proper
procedure for caring for monkey bites and scratches, the complaint
said.
   Company officials didn't return telephone calls Monday seeking
comment, but have said in the past that every new employee is warned
of the virus before handling the monkeys.
   Young's co-worker Thomas McGeorge, 23, died of the virus June 20,
and another co-worker, who quit after one week at the company, has
been diagnosed with the virus and has been hospitalized since late
June.
   Young said he has been informed he also may have been exposed and
has been given a prescription for an anti-viral drug.
   Other current and former employees of the company also have said
they weren't told about the potential risks associated with handling
the monkeys until after McGeorge was diagnosed.
   Michigan Department of Public Health officials are awaiting
results from blood tests on about 50 current and former company
employees.
   Young is asking for at least $10,000 in damages and for pain and
suffering, alleging he ``lives in continual fear.''
   In addition to allegations of failing to maintain a safe
workplace, intentional infliction of emotional distress, breach of
implied contract, general negligence and misrepresentation, the
lawsuit also alleges the company violated the Michigan Occupational
Safety and Health Act and the Federal Occupational Safety and Health
Act.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
