<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--UtahQuake     07-03 0157</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Utah Quake,0160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moderate Quake Hits Northern Utah</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TREMONTON, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A moderate earthquake struck an
unpopulated region of northern Utah on Monday afternoon, but no
injuries or damage were reported, authorities said.
   The quake measured 4.5 on the Richter scale, and was centered 11
miles west of this town in the Blue Spring Hills, said Jim Pechmann
of the University of Utah Seismology Center.
   A June 21 temblor measuring 3.7 occurred in the same area June
21, Pechmann said.
   Monday's quake was felt in Box Elder and Salt Lake counties,
Pechmann said.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude. Thus a reading of 7.5 reflects an earthquake 10 times
stronger than one of 6.5.
   An earthquake of 3.5 on the Richter scale can cause slight damage
in the local area, 4 moderate damage and 5 considerable damage.
</TEXT>
