<FIRST>r i AM-Nazis-Catholics     07-03 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nazis-Catholics,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commission to Investigate Link Between Nazis, Right-wing Catholics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LYON, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A commission of historians will investigate
the link between Paul Touvier, one of France's most notorious Nazi
collaborators, and conservative Roman Catholics, the archbishop of
Lyon said Monday.
   The eight-member commission will have unrestricted access to
diocese files and will carry out its work with the ``required
independence,'' said Cardinal Albert Decourtray.
   ``I much prefer the truth, even unpleasant, to a lie, even
pleasant,'' Decourtray said.
   The commission will try to clarify any connection between the
Catholic community and Touvier, the archbishop said.
   Touvier, 74, headed a pro-Nazi French militia in Lyon during the
German occupation in World War II. He was arrested on May 24 at St.
Francis Priory in Nice. The priory is run by followers of Monsignor
Marcel Lefebvre, a fundamentalist priest who was excommunicated by
the Vatican last year.
   Touvier faces trial on charges of crimes against humanity.
   His arrest renewed questions about a possible relationship
between Roman Catholics and Nazi collaborators. There have been
persistent reports in recent years that extreme-right Roman
Catholics were protecting Touvier, who was in hiding for nearly four
decades.
   Named to head the commission was historian Rene Remond, president
of the High Council for Archives. Other members included Jean-Pierre
Azema, a specialist in World War II history from Paris' National
Foundation for Political Sciences.
</TEXT>
