<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 2153EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HusbandKilled 1stLd-Writethru a0814 07-03 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Husband Killed, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0814,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Officer Run Over and Killed by Wife</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to CORRECT that car was luxury sedan, sted
sports car; fix attribution in 4th graf; picks up 5th graf pvs, `Howard,
a ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HELEN SIMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer who did marital counseling with her
police-officer husband chased him in a luxury car for two blocks and
ran over the off-duty lawman, killing him, authorities said.
   City police Sgt. Frank Howard and his wife, Olivia, both
practiced law, doing a lot of work in marital counseling, said
Police Director Claude Coleman.
   ``We knew he was having marital problems. We never knew they were
at that point,'' Coleman said. ``It's ironic that they were both
doing marital work and they were both suffering from marital
problems.''
   Howard, 48, of Orange, was knocked to the ground by a Jaguar XJ6
luxury sedan driven by Mrs. Howard, his wife of about 20 years,
Coleman said.
   Howard, a member of the force since 1967, was pronounced dead at
University Hospital in Newark, said hospital spokeswoman Ann Edgar.
   Howard was a legal analyst for the department and was to be
promoted shortly to lieutenant, police said.
   Mrs. Howard, 48, was being held in the Newark Jail and was to be
arraigned Wednesday on homicide charges, Coleman said.
   The couple had arranged to meet during their lunch hour, police
said. Both were in the car when Howard got out. Witnesses said Mrs.
Howard pursued him for at least two blocks the wrong way down a
one-way street.
   She then knocked him down with the car and ran over him, said
police Lt. McKinley Jackson.
   ``A police officer had tried to stop her and she almost ran him
over,'' Coleman said.
   Howard had a law practice in East Orange and graduated in 1978
from Rutgers Law School. Mrs. Howard shared a practice with her
husband but they had two offices, both in Orange, Coleman said.
   ``We're all very shocked by this turn of events,'' Coleman said.
``Everyone liked Frank. Everyone knew him.''
</TEXT>
