<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--OilSpill 1stLd-Writethru a0674 07-03 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Oil Spill, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0674,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tanker Arrives Outside Harbor En Route to Drydock</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with ship arriving at shipyard;
picks up 3rd graf pvs, `The World ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Greek tanker that spilled 420,000 gallons of
heating oil off the Rhode Island coast arrived Monday evening at a
shipyard here for repairs, the Coast Guard said.
   The World Prodigy arrived at New York Shipyard Corp., site of the
old Brooklyn Navy Yard, around 7:30 p.m., said Coast Guard Petty
Officer Kevin Moisan.
   Coast Guard spokesman Jim McGranachan said earlier that
commercial traffic in the harbor was normal but pleasure craft were
out in great number because of the holiday weekend.
   The World Prodigy was escorted from Rhode Island by the Mark
McAllister, a private tugboat with pollution gear aboard. A Coast
Guard port safety officer Lt. Cmdr. Larry Brooks, was aboard for the
trip, but the vessel's captain, Iakovos Georgudis, 43, was at the
helm.
   Aerial inspections on Sunday and early Monday showed no oil
leaking, he said.
   The tanker grounded on Brenton Reef on June 23, spilling a
portion of its 8 million-gallon cargo. Georgudis, who faces federal
pollution charges, has said it was a mistake to have entered
Narragansett Bay without a harbor pilot on board.
</TEXT>
