<FIRST>r a AM-RapeRecant     07-03 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rape Recant,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hearing on Dotson Retrial Continued Until July 24</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gary Dotson has no right to a retrial on his 1979
rape conviction because he waited too long to request it,
prosecutors contended Monday at a hearing on his bid for another day
in court.
   However, Dotson's lawyer argued that the technology he says will
exonerate his client has only been available for a few years.
   Dotson was convicted of raping Cathleen Crowell Webb and
sentenced to a 25- to 50-year prison term.
   But in 1985, Ms. Webb recanted her testimony against him in a
case that drew nationwide attention.
   Gov. James R. Thompson granted Dotson clemency, saying his
punishment had been sufficient. The governor, however, said he did
not believe the recantation, and has refused to pardon Dotson.
   Dotson attorney Thomas Breen's bid for a retrial is based on
recent genetic tests that the attorney says prove Dotson was not Ms.
Webb's assailant.
   Assistant State's Attorney Gayle Shines said Dotson's right to
ask for a retrial expired two years after his conviction, even
though the genetic tests were not available then.
   Circuit Judge Thomas R. Fitzgerald continued the hearing until
July 24, saying he needed more time to study the matter.
   Dotson, 32, remains in an alcoholism treatment center as a
condition of his parole last August. He had been returned to prison
in December 1987 for a parole violation.
   Since his 1985 release, Dotson has had recurring problems with
the law.
</TEXT>
