<FIRST>r i AM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0735 07-03 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0735,0692</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leading Opposition Strategist Proposes Solidarity Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 10th graf pvs, ``Jaruzelski must...'' to CORRECT that protesters
opposed candidacy of Kiszczak; Pickup 11th pvs, ``The Polish...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading opposition theorist Monday
proposed that Solidarity support a Communist candidate for president
in exchange for a Solidarity candidate becoming prime minister and
forming the next government.
   The proposal by historian-essayist Adam Michnik, in a front-page
column in the opposition's Election Gazette, drew no immediate
response from Communist Party officials who have failed to name a
presidential candidate to succeed Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski.
   Also Monday, the White House reported President Bush urged the
Kremlin to withdraw its troops from Poland.
   The White House released the text of Bush's interview with Polish
reporters, whom he told Friday: ``Very candidly, I'd like to see
Soviet troops out. ... I would like to see them start withdrawing
troops from Poland because I think there is no danger at all of an
invasion of Poland from the West.'' Bush is to visit Warsaw on
Sunday.
   Poland's PAP state news agency said the Military Council of
generals who oversee the armed forces held an extraordinary meeting
to discuss the army's position after a party plenum failed to name a
presidential candidate.
   In an apparent indirect endorsement of Jaruzelski, the council
said it expects ``the chairman of the State Defense Committee and
the chief of the army to be a person of proper competence and giving
constitutional guarantees for the safe development of the country.''
   It stressed ``the significance of strengthening of Poland's
international position'' within the Warsaw Pact.
   The next president will have charge of the military, and the
other candidate mentioned for the post, Interior Minister Gen.
Czeslaw Kiszczak, has no foreign policy experience.
   About 200 people demonstrated against Jaruzelski outside
parliament Monday, and a small group of youths later hurled tear gas
and threw stones at police. No one was reported injured.
   ``Jaruzelski must go!'' and ``Soviets go home!'' chanted
protesters from the banned Confederation for an Independent Poland.
They also opposed the candidacy of Kiszczak, Jaruzelski's longtime
associate.
   The Polish leader declared Friday he is too closely linked with
the 1981 martial law crack down on Solidarity to lead the country
during an era of reconciliation.
   The Communist Party has asked him to reconsider, however, and
party consultations continued Monday to try to persuade him.
   With Solidarity's support evidenced by overwhelming victories in
parliamentary voting and growing independence shown by the two
parties allied with the Communists, it does not appear that internal
discipline is strong enough to translate the Communists' 300-259
National Assembly majority into a sure victory for Jaruzelski.
   The assembly, composed of the existing Sejm and a new freely
elected Senate, is to convene for the first time Tuesday. A vote on
the presidency is expected Thursday.
   Solidarity legislators say they will not vote for Jaruzelski,
though a formal decision was postponed until Wednesday.
   ``Poland needs now a strong and trustworthy arrangement of
authority,'' Michnik wrote. ``No facade-like changes are sufficient.
   ``Discussing the personal advantages of generals Jaruzelski and
Kiszczak is a false road,'' he wrote. ``What is needed is a new
arrangement that can be accepted by all main political forces.''
   He suggested a Communist Party candidate become president and a
Solidarity candidate become prime minister. Under Poland's revised
constitution, the president has charge of the army and foreign
affairs, and the prime minister names the Cabinet.
   Walesa previously has rejected suggestions the independent
movement become part of a governing coalition, insisting it remain
an opposition force.
   But Michnik, who is close to Walesa, said his plan is the only
way to ``practice the postulate of a grand coalition'' and receive
Western help to rebuild Poland's economy.
   The government negotiated political and economic freedoms with
the opposition after realizing it could not control social unrest or
end Poland's financial plight.
   The atmosphere of reform has attracted Western interest in
renewing aid and investment cut off since martial law.
</TEXT>
