<FIRST>r a AM-BusCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0809 07-03 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bus Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0809,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bus Crash Injures 23 Migrant Farm Workers, Driver</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to restore time element, UPDATE casualty total; EDITS
throughout to UPDATE with details on hospitalization, other details; no
pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ITHACA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bus plunged down a 10-foot embankment after
its brakes failed on a hill Monday, injuring 23 migrant farm workers
and the driver, officials said.
   The bus, which had been traveling down the steep hill at about 50
mph when the brakes failed, came to rest in a cornfield, said
Tompkins County Sheriff's Deputy Mark Dresser.
   ``He was whistling along pretty good,'' Dresser said. ``They were
very fortunate. They just missed two very large trees. They went
right between them.''
   At least one of the injured required surgery, but none of the
injuries appeared life-threatening, said Gail Longfellow, a
spokeswoman at Tompkins Community Hospital in Ithaca.
   The hospital treated all 24 people on the bus, including several
children and two pregnant women, for broken bones, cuts, back pains
and other injuries, Longfellow said.
   All but five were released Monday night, she said. Four were
admitted, one in serious condition and the others in satisfactory
condition, while the fifth was transferred to St. Joseph's Hospital
in Elmira for treatment of spinal injuries.
   The workers were being taken from Florida to a farm in Kings
Ferry, about 30 miles southwest of Syracuse, Dresser said.
   Many of the workers originally were from Haiti and did not speak
English. French-speaking hospital workers were brought in to
translate, Longfellow said.
   The sheriff's department impounded the converted school bus and
planned to check whether it had been properly maintained.
</TEXT>
