<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 2236EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru   07-03 0765</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush, 1st Ld -Writethru,a0698,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Challenges Soviets to Withdraw Troops From Poland</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 8-9 bgng: ``Bush boated,'' with 4 grafs on fireworks
display, picking up 10th graf pvs: ``Poland is,''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush has challenged the
Soviet Union to withdraw all its troops from Poland and take
advantage of ``an historic opportunity to help end the postwar
division in Europe.''
   Bush, who visits Poland on Sunday on his way to the seven-nation
economic summit in Paris, made the proposal in an interview with a
group of Polish reporters last Friday in the White House. The
transcript was released Monday by Bush's vacation White House.
   The Soviets should withdraw their troops from Poland because
``there is no danger at all of an invasion of Poland from the
West,'' Bush asserted. It was the first time the president called
for a total Soviet withdrawal of troops from Poland.
   Bush, here for an extended Independence Day holiday, issued a
statement Monday welcoming the Supreme Court decision restricting
women's right to end pregnancies.
   ``By upholding the Missouri statute, the court appears to have
begun to restore to the people the ability to protect the unborn,''
he said.
   Bush has voiced support for a constitutional amendment to
overturn the 1973 Roe vs. Wade decision that legalized abortions.
Chief of Staff John Sununu told a White House briefing the president
would continue to actively support such an amendment.
   Earlier, the president voiced condolences to the family of the
late Soviet President Andrei A. Gromyko, saying his death ``marks
the passing of a generation that witnessed many of the most historic
events of this century.''
   Bush boated, jogged and played golf for the third day in a row as
he continued to enjoy a five-day July Fourth holiday.
   He also mounted a $20,000 fireworks display for his neighbors
Monday evening from his six-acre compound on a point jutting out
into the Atlantic Ocean.
   Thousands of people lined the shore to watch the 15-minute
display, with more in hundreds of small boats in nearby waters.
   The fireworks, produced by Zambelli International of New Castle,
Pa., the same company that did the 1986 Statue of Liberty fireworks
in New York Habor, were paid for by an anonymous donor, White House
aides said.
   Poland is Bush's first stop on a trip that will also include
visits to Hungary, France and the Netherlands. He arrives in Warsaw
on Sunday and will remain in Poland through Tuesday.
   Bush, in the interview with Polish reporters, said he was not
seeking to ``inflame'' the situation in Poland or ``do anything that
is going to cause a crisis.''
   But, he said that when he visits Poland next ``I'm going to feel
free to speak out about ... what we hold dear and what Polish
Americans think and what we want to see about a freer, a more whole
Europe.''
   The challenge of Soviet troop withdrawal builds on the plan he
proposed last month while attending a NATO summit in Brussels that
called for reducing NATO and Warsaw Pact forces in Europe to no more
than 275,000 apiece.
   ``Very candidly, I'd would like to see Soviet troops ... out,''
Bush said in his interview with reporters for three Polish news
organizations.
   The Soviet Union currently maintains 40,000 troops in Poland,
according to the London-based Institute of International and
Strategic Studies.
   Bush conceded it was probably unrealistic to envision a complete
withdrawal of all Soviet forces in eastern Europe ``as long as we
have this tremendous disparity in Soviet-deployed troops.''
   He said, however, Poland would be a good place for the Soviets to
start.
   ``In Poland, there's an historic opportunity now to help end the
postwar division of Europe,'' Bush said.
   He said he hopes to carry through on a package of economic aid to
Poland as a reward for its recent steps toward democracy. But, Bush
told the Polish reporters: ``We need to know that you're going to be
able to not only continue existing reforms, but expand on reforms so
that the economic system that works will be given a chance to work
unfettered.''
   Bush said that he wasn't going to be naive in suggesting ``that
we have no differences'' with Soviet Leader Mikhail Gorbachev on the
future of divided Europe.
   ``It doesn't bother me as president of the United States that he
(Gorbachev) gets a good standing on the applause meters over there
in Europe, western Europe,'' Bush continued. ``Nor should it bother
him when I take (my) message of freedom and democracy to eastern
Europe.''
</TEXT>
