<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 2258EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AmericanHomecoming     07-03 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-American Homecoming,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abe Stolar to Celebrate First American 4th of July in 58 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEGGY ANDERSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abe Stolar is coming home for his first Fourth of
July in America in 58 years. Both he and the city have changed since
1931, when dreams of a Soviet workers' paradise inspired a journey
into disenchantment.
   Since leaving his West Side neighborhood at 19, Stolar lost his
father during the Stalinist purges, his mother and sister to camps
in Siberia and the sight in one eye to a German hand grenade.
   A Chicago-born U.S. citizen, he served in the Red Army during
World War II, then worked as a translator and announcer for Radio
Moscow. Even after nearly six decades in the Soviet Union, however,
his accent is pure West Side.
   After a 14-year fight to emigrate, Stolar, 77, left the Soviet
Union for Israel in March with his wife, son, daughter-in-law and
two grandchildren.
   ``He's a very up person no matter what's happening. ... I think
that has helped him stay healthy. I think that has helped him stay
young,'' said Linda Opper of Chicago Action for Soviet Jewry, which
is financing and arranging his visit.
   Though the family has settled in Israel, Stolar is still drawn by
Chicago _ the first stop Wednesday on a 12-city tour by Stolar and
his wife, Gita Rozovskaya, that covers both coasts. They also will
visit Anchorage, Alaska, and Miami before winding up with an Aug. 13
trip to Los Angeles.
   Stolar's hometown has changed.
   ``His memory of Chicago is just frozen in time, in 1931,'' said
David Carle, a spokesman for Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., who helped
draw attention to Stolar's efforts to leave the Soviet Union.
   ``It will be a new look at the old town, which will really be all
new to me,'' Stolar said in a letter to Simon's staff.
   The Depression is over. The skyline is taller, marked with new
silhouettes. Humboldt Park, a working-class neighborhood of mostly
Eastern European Jewish immigrants in the 1930s, is largely
Hispanic. Tuley High School, his alma mater, has been replaced by
Roberto Clemente High.
   But Wrigley Field looks much the same, and the recent addition of
lights at the venerable ballpark will make it possible for him to
catch Wednesday's night game between the Cubs and the San Diego
Padres.
   Stolar dreamed of one day staying in the posh, 3,000-room Stevens
Hotel, a dream that will come true.
   The hotel, now the Conrad Hilton and Towers, has offered the
Stolars its 23rd-floor Chicago Suite. Despite recent refurbishing,
the grand ballroom and grand salon _ glittering with mirrors and
gold leaf _ are virtually unchanged, said assistant manager Peter
Borup.
   No special menu is planned during Stolar's weeklong stay _ he's
``a junk-food junkie'' who likes hamburgers and hot dogs, Borup said.
   Stolar plans meetings with old friends throughout his visit, and
there is talk of a high school reunion while he is in Chicago, Ms.
Opper said.
   When Stolar's Russian-born parents headed home to help build a
new Soviet society, he ``planned to stay only a short time,'' Ms.
Opper said.
   But change was shuddering through the Soviet Union, and history
got in the way. Years passed. There was little hope of leaving, and
Stolar gave it little thought.
   Then he married and had a son, Michael. One day, the boy came
home excited at winning a school contest.
   ``He looked at his son, so full of hope, so full of enthusiasm,
and he thought, `This boy will never go anywhere in this country.
We've got to get out,''' Ms. Opper said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
