<FIRST>a a BC-History Adv15   07-03 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-History, Adv 15,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Saturday, July 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Saturday, July 15, the 196th day of 1989. There are 169
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   Twenty-five years ago, on July 15, 1964, Sen. Barry M. Goldwater
of Arizona was nominated for president by the Republican National
Convention, meeting in San Francisco.
   On this date:
   In 1606, the Dutch painter Rembrandt was born in Leiden, the
Netherlands.
   In 1870, Georgia became the last of the Confederate states to be
readmitted to the Union.
   In 1918, the Second Battle of the Marne began during World War I.
   In 1948, President Harry S. Truman was nominated for another term
in office by the Democratic National Convention in Philadelphia.
   In 1958, President Dwight D. Eisenhower ordered U.S. Marines to
Lebanon at the request of that country's Christian president,
Camille Chamoun, in the face of a perceived threat from Moslem
rebels.
   In 1965, U.S. scientists displayed close-up photographs of the
planet Mars taken by the spacecraft Mariner IV.
   In 1971, President Richard M. Nixon announced he would visit the
People's Republic of China to normalize relations. (Nixon made the
trip the following February.)
   In 1975, three American astronauts blasted off aboard an Apollo
spaceship several hours after two Soviet cosmonauts were launched
aboard a Soyuz craft for a mission linking the two ships in space.
   In 1976, a 36-hour kidnap ordeal began for 26 schoolchildren and
their bus driver as they were abducted near Chowchilla, Calif., by
three gunmen and imprisoned in an underground cell. (All the
captives escaped unharmed.)
   In 1978, President Jimmy Carter, in West Germany for an economic
summit, presided over a ``town meeting'' where he fielded questions
from about 1,000 Berliners.
   In 1982, the U.S. Senate confirmed George P. Shultz as America's
60th secretary of state by a 97-0 vote.
   In 1986, the American League beat the National League for only
the second time in 15 years, winning baseball's 57th All-Star Game
by a score of 3-2.
   Ten years ago: In a national broadcast, President Jimmy Carter
delivered his now-famous ``malaise'' speech in which he lamented
what he called a ``crisis of confidence'' and scolded Americans for
lacking the spirit and self-discipline needed to combat energy
shortages and inflation.
   Five years ago: In the face of protests, Democratic
nominee-apparent Walter F. Mondale reinstated Charles T. Manatt as
the party's national chairman, after trying to oust him in favor of
President Carter's old confidant, Bert Lance.
   One year ago: The leadership of the Teamsters Union chose William
J. McCarthy to fill out the remaining term of the late Jackie
Presser as president, narrowly rejecting Secretary-Treasurer Weldon
Mathis, Presser's hand-picked successor.
   Today's Birthdays: Actor Ken Kercheval is 54. Actor Alex Karras
is 54. Actor Jan-Michael Vincent is 45. Singer Linda Ronstadt is 43.
Actor Willie Aames is 29.
   Thought for Today: ``Conform and be dull.'' _ J. Frank Dobie,
American folklorist and author (1888-1964).
</TEXT>
