<DOCNO> AP890703-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 1055EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv05   07-03 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 05,0632</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wednesday July 5</HEAD>
<HEAD>Corporate Manners: Wither Have They Gone?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It will be a seething second half of the year in
corporate society _ in New York, in Washington and Tokyo, and
wherever else the captains of industry and their lawyers meet to
scrap.
   Corporate society, once a comradely caste who sat on each other's
boards, talked yachting at ``the'' club and shared the same parlor
car from summer-home communities, are now brawling like street
fighters.
   Why, you can hardly lift your arm in a toast to continued good
profits without some scoundrel picking your pocket. You never know
if the rascal you're chatting with might raid your operation
tomorrow and dump you on the streets.
   Corporate good manners, steadily eroding since the great
Industrial Revolution, have now been abandoned. The devices employed
by today's new and avaricious tycoons are ungentlemanly, even
scandalous and often illegal.
   Nobody knows how to behave. Michael Milken, the most successful
financier of all time, measured by the billions he has raised, has
been indicted. Paul Bilzerian has resigned as Singer Co. chairman
after being convicted of criminal charges. And, of course, several
big financiers are residing in the cooler.
   The decline is international. In Japan, T. Boone Pickens, the
Texas investor, was denied three seats on the board of Koito
Manufacturing, Tokyo, although he owns 20 percent of the company. An
insult, to be sure, but it gets worse.
   Pickens said he was prepared for the rebuff, but he probably
wasn't ready for the accompaniments. Days before the meeting, rumors
spread that the company had hired toughs to disrupt his
presentation. Then the company's Japanese and American advisers
issued claims that he had ties to the Japanese underworld.
   It was no better in New York, where J. Richard Munro, Time Inc.
chairman, erupted in anger when the nervy Martin Davis, Paramount
Communications chief, thwarted Munro's dream of a quick Time-Warner
Communications merger.
   Munro unloaded all his ammunition. He wrote a personal letter to
Davis, who offered $175 a share _ and later $200 _ for shares then
selling at about $l25, saying he had ``serious questions about your
integrity and motives.'' Davis, he added, was motivated more by
spite than strategy, and his offer was ``cynical if not downright
deceptive.''
   Indicating that some of the good old days somehow managed to
survive, Time had the foresight to induce several big banks to
refuse money to anyone seeking to raid the company.
   Time also determined that it could avoid giving shareholders a
say in the Time-Warner deal, although it is sometimes alleged that
shareholders own the companies in which they invest.
   Time's lawyers asked various communities in which Time held
cable-TV franchises to complain to federal officials about Davis'
offer. The Time board rejected Paramount's offer out of hand. It
declined to speak with Davis.
   Throughout this maneuvering the world wondered whatever happened
to shareholder rights, to the obligation of multi-millionaire
executives to those who helped make them that way, to noblesse
oblige or the appearance of it.
   As the first half of the corporate social year drew to a close,
an answer to those questions was scheduled for the courts. Maybe the
Securities and Exchange Commission would get involved, too. And the
Federal Communications Commission.
   And that, of course, meant more uncivil scrapping, right out
there in the public arena for all the hoi polloi to witness.
Couldn't anything be kept quiet anymore? Didn't anyone have a sense
of propriety?
   For the executive class it was downright embarassing and
degrading, and it seemed to be getting worse.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wednesday July 5</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890703-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 1121EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-NNTN Adv04   07-03 0747</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-NNTN, Adv 04,0762</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues PMs, July 4, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>HBO's `Not Necessarily the News' Returns</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It looks more like a network newscast than its
predecessors, and the news reports are the freshest yet _ live, in
fact, the first showing each week.
   But first-time viewers of ``Not Necessarily the News' on Home Box
Office won't be confused for long. Particularly when the news anchor
reports that the Chinese are claiming the leader of the student
uprising was Morgan Fairchild. Or that Yassir Arafat's mother is
upset that he didn't come to dinner Sunday.
   The HBO comedy series that began seven years ago started its new
season May 31 with a new cast and new format but with the old
irreverence still intact.
   ``Not Necessarily the News'' also airs live each Wednesday, to
give it a topicality it didn't have before. It will be repeated, but
only within the same week.
   The new version has two anchors, Annabelle Gurwitch and Tom
Parks, plus some contributing editors. Lucy Webb is the only
returning member of the old cast.
   ``The trouble before was that it had no linear construction, no
link,'' said co-executive producer John Moffitt. ``You had four or
five cast members who played all parts, from newsmen to crazy
general. Our trademark was taking real news footage and manipulating
it and cutting it with phony questions from our newsmen cast.
   ``But there was no audience identification with our people. It
never achieved an audience following. It was bounced around the
schedule and there was never anyone in the cast you could get
attached to because no one ever had enough air time.''
   Nevertheless, the show is the most honored program on cable. It's
won 12 ACE awards, plus numerous other citations.
   The show was adapted by Moffitt and his partner, Pat Tourk Lee,
from the British program ``Not the Nine O'Clock News.'' It was
originally sold to ABC, but the network didn't know how to program
it and turned it back to Moffitt and Lee. They sold it to HBO.
   ``We'd previously done `Fridays' for ABC and it was censored,''
said Moffitt. ``We have no censorship on HBO, but now that we don't
have to push to get things on, we're more circumspect. Take China,
for instance. Now that things have turned sour there and the
students were killed and people are being executed, we're being more
delicate.
   ``We used President Bush's response to the China situation, which
was so wishy-washy. He expressed `deep regret,' which we said falls
just short of `total regret.' We made a point and made people
think.''
   The show was less forthright in poking fun at the proposed
Time-Warner merger and the subsequent bid by Paramount to take over
Time. HBO is a division of Time Inc. ``It's hard to bite the hand
that feeds you,'' said Moffitt.
   ``We did have a test tone like that of the Emergency Broadcast
System. The announcer said, `This is a test from the Corporate
Takeover Service. If this had been an actual takeover you would have
been advised what action to take.'''
   ABC's ``Fridays'' was a copy of NBC's ``Saturday Night Live.'' It
lasted two years, 1980-82, and is best known for the amazing
realistic fight scene that the late comedian Andy Kaufman engineered
on the show. ``There are still people who refuse to believe we
didn't set that up,'' said Moffitt.
   Moffitt and Lee also produce the annual ``Comic Relief'' for HBO,
which has raised more than $10 million for medical aid to the
homeless.
   ``Not Necessarily the News'' began on HBO in September 1982, and
in its first four years was a half-hour show. Later, it became a
series of one-hour specials, which made it difficult to be topical.
The show was severely affected by the writers' strike last year, but
returned in time to wrap up ``the Reagan legacy.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   BY ANY OTHER NAME _ Paramount's upcoming half-hour news and
information series has had its name changed from ``Tabloid'' to
``Hard Copy.'' The syndicated show will debut Sept. 18 and so far
has been sold in 120 markets. Alan Frio will be the news anchor of
``Hard Copy,'' which will ``delve behind the headlines to report the
untold stories about the people, places and events making news
today,'' according to Paramount executive Frank Kelly.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tues PMs, July 4</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890703-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 1129EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-Denver Adv05   07-03 0747</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Denver, Adv 05,0773</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed PMs, July 5, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Denver, Playing White House, Wants to Play Horseshoes With President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Denver had more in mind than playing guitar
when he signed on as host of the first ``In Performance at the White
House'' of the Bush administration.
   ``I have a personal agenda in this. I want to play horseshoes
with the president,'' Denver said on a recent visit to New York as
host of a United Nations dinner on World Environment Day.
   ``I have tandem (horseshoe ) pits at my home,'' Denver said.
``I've been home in April and May for the first time in over 10
years, and my game has sharpened.''
   The one-hour ``In Performance at the White House'' airs tonight
on PBS. It also features actor Barry Bostwick, opera star Simon
Estes, Broadway singer Judy Kaye, the ragtime ensemble from the
Marine Band and ragtime pianist Joshua Rifkin.
   The executive producer of the show, John Musilli, presented
President and Mrs. Bush with several possible formats for this
season's ``In Performance at the White House'' series. They selected
one based on Earl Robinson's song, ``The House I Live In,''
referring both to the White House and the United States. Musilli
chose Denver as host of the opening concert.
   ``I called the Bushes,'' Musilli said. ``They said, `That would
be terrific. Do you think he'll do it?'''
   Denver, who was delighted to accept, said, ``Mr. Bush attended my
first concert at Carnegie Hall, in 1971, I think. I think he has
been a fan of mine.''
   Musilli hopes the two other shows in the series, like this
post-Fourth of July special, will have holiday themes, airing around
Columbus Day and Thanksgiving.
   The ``In Performance at the White House'' season in the Reagan
administration featured Broadway music.
   Denver will sing and play guitar as well as serve as host. He
said he would include his popular hits ``Rocky Mountain High,''
``Annie's Song'' and ``Country Roads.''
   Three ragtime pieces by Scott Joplin will be included, ``Pleasant
Moments,'' by Rifkin, ``The Pineapple Rag,'' with Rifkin
accompanying Miss Kaye, and ``Magnetic Rag,'' the last one Joplin
composed, by the Marine musicians, with Bostwick reading from E.L.
Doctorow's ``Ragtime.''
   Bass-baritone Estes will sing ``The House I Live In.'' The finale
will involve everybody joining in on ``Play a Simple Melody'' then _
since demand for an encore is expected _ Miss Kaye will sing ``Take
Care of This House'' from Leonard Bernstein's 1976 Broadway show,
``1600 Pennsylvania Avenue.''
   In the interview, Denver asked for maple syrup for his coffee,
but none is to be had. He likes it in coffee, he said, and on the
sourdough pancakes he makes for Sunday breakfasts. His sourdough
batter ``starter,'' he said, is more than 100 years old and gets
better all the time.
   Denver and his Australian wife, Cassie, had their first child, a
girl, in May. Jesse Belle was born by natural childbirth with Denver
assisting at Aspen Valley Hospital, where Denver had donated money
for a pediatric wing, named for his two older children, Zack and
Anna Kate. Denver said before the baby was an hour old, he held her
and sang to her. He can't remember what he sang except for an Indian
chant and a song he wrote in April, ``The Gift You Are.''
   He thinks it's one of his particularly good compositions. He'll
record it in July on an album for his own label, Wind Star. ``I love
it when I write a good song. You know when you've got a good one,''
he said.
   The song isn't just for the baby, he said. Denver said all people
must participate in the struggle to save the environment so that
human life can continue. ``The song is saying that each of us is a
gift to the world and to the people we love and we should live up to
that, in a sense.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   BACK TO `FRESNO' _ CBS is going to rebroadcast ``Fresno,'' the
satire on night-time soaps, beginning July 17. It will air over five
nights, concluding Friday, July 21, with a two-hour finale. Carol
Burnett, Dabney Coleman, Teri Garr, Gregory Harrison and Charles
Grodin starred in the hilarious and critically praised comedy
miniseries, but it didn't do well in the ratings when it first aired
in the 1986-87 series.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed PMs, July 5</NOTE>
