<FIRST>s i BC-APN--FranceToday Adv16-2Takes   07-03 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--France Today, Adv 16-2 Takes,0701</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 16</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 3 b&amp;w photos,
1 graphic. ColorFoto subscribers get 3 35mm slides.)    </HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   In this the bicentennial of the French
Revolution, France's influence as a world power is waning. Be that
as it may, a large proportion of Frenchmen insist Charles de Gaulle
proved a generation ago that even a France on the ropes is a vital
force in the world.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MORT ROSENBLUM_ ^AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Divided at home, humbled abroad, the French
resolutely resist the judgment of a growing number of outsiders that
the nation has slipped into the second ranks of world power.
   France's economy is three-quarters the size of West Germany's, a
third of Japan's. Its latest foreign adventure, a relief attempt in
Lebanon, ended in debacle. Its influence in Africa is melting away.
   Although France keeps its own nuclear arsenal, it is edging
closer toward NATO, seeking a part in the vast electronic air
defense and battlefield command system planned by Atlantic allies.
   Steadily, its once influential foreign policy is slipping into
the shadow of West Germany.
   The comfortable old channels of domestic politics are blurred by
rebellion at the center, a new appeal by ecologist candidates toward
the left and anti-immigrant extremism at the far right.
   Traditional values are changing at an unprecedented pace. Young
rockers, new conservatives, rootless travelers _ the ``new tribes,''
according to pop commentators _ splinter sectors of society.
   And the nation that traces itself back to feisty Gauls who stood
up to Caesar is joining 11 European partners in a dream of unity a
popular French thinker calls a ``Darwinian nightmare.''
   Whatever indicators might show, however, a sizable proportion of
Frenchmen insist Charles de Gaulle proved a generation ago that even
a France on the ropes is a vital force in the world.
   Jacques Chirac, the former premier who lost presidential
elections last year to Francois Mitterrand, told reporters recently
that France was a waning power only because it acted like one.
   ``Gaullism is not an ideology, but a way of behaving,'' said
Chirac, now mayor of Paris, before leaving for New York to talk
about France on the bicentennial of its revolution.
   Chirac, a conservative who heads France's neo-Gaullist Rally for
the Republic party, argued that countrymen from across the political
spectrum subscribed to what the former president represented in
rebuilding postwar France.
   ``General de Gaulle followed two basic concepts, a certain idea
of the nation, and a certain idea of man,'' he said.
   ``Exactly,'' said Philippe Gillieron, marketing director for the
Eiffel Tower, who considers the soaring steel girders a symbol of
what France means to the world. He explained:
   ``Economically, if maybe we're bigger than Togo, or even Greece,
we're no major power. But in culture, for our ideas on human rights
and the evolution of humanity, we have an active, distinct role.''
   When the Eiffel Tower opened 100 years ago, Gillieron said, it
marked a new epoch of industrial prowess. Today, he said, centennial
festivities heralded a revolution in global communications.
   ``After all,'' he concluded, ``the Eiffel Tower is as well known
to the world as Coca-Cola.''
   Mitterrand is hard at work realizing an old dream, to build the
world's most modern library. According to the plan, work starts in
1991 on the billion-dollar complex, covering 17.3 acres.
   To emphasize its role as at least a symbolic power, France is
celebrating its bicentennial with everything from a string of
summits to sheep on the Champs Elysees.
   A two-hour July 14 parade, named ``La Marseillaise,'' included
Chinese break-dancers among the 8,000 participants from around the
world.
   Counting such monuments as the Opera Bastille, a glass pyramid
for the Louvre and new gold leaf for the Invalides dome, the cost
ran into the billions of dollars.
   Frenchmen who date their history back 2,000 years, not 200, tend
to dismiss the revolutionary rage as unseemly. Many regard
image-building abroad as a diversion from pressing problems at home.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890703-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 1418EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-APN--FranceToday Adv16-1stAdd   07-03 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--France Today, Adv 16-1st Add,0644</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday July 16</HEAD>
<HEAD>PARIS: at home.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``It's a fiasco,'' said Serge Barbarin, a 27-year-old winemaker
in Medoc, north of Bordeaux. ``Celebrations were planned at the last
minute, to lure tourists. These people in power are not serious.''
   Barbarin, heir to the Biston-Brillette vineyards at Moulis, is
not worried about grandeur. France, he said, has never failed to
change with the times and come out at the head table.
   Instead, he fears a race to compete on uncertain ground might
damage the quality, proportion and pace of life that once made
France so pleasant for Frenchmen.
   He leads a visitor among the oaken casks where deep red wine
takes its time to mature in centuries-old cellars. Suddenly, he
glances at his watch and says: ``Sorry to rush, but my computer is
arriving.''
   In almost every aspect, France today takes the cliche ``land of
contrasts'' to extremes.
   Along the Champs Elysees, franchise burgers are sold at seven
outlets between the Arc de Triomphe and the Concorde, but to most
Frenchmen ``fast food'' means leaving the table after the first hour.
   North of Paris, supersonic Concordes swoop over the farmlands of
Picardy, studded with stone cathedrals and still partly tilled by
peasants for whom a restaurant meal is an unthinkable luxury.
   Fast trains streak by canals where tiny boats carry produce to
the floating market at Amiens, not all that unlike traditional
markets in the far-flung places that France once colonized.
   Up along the English Channel and just inland from the Riviera,
speculators pay inflated prices for stately old houses and flimsy
eyesores that are popping up in empty spaces once left for gardens.
   On the beach near San Raphael, just down the coast from Cannes, a
developer is building a tourist village of 10,000 beds.
   But across vast sections of the center, historic hamlets collapse
in disrepair, and small farm families throw in the towel after
centuries on the land.
   At the edge of little towns all over the French countryside, vast
tin-sided ``hypermarche'' shopping centers are becoming as
ubiquitous as the mossy church on the square.
   In the Picardy town of Roye, Marcelle Carpentier-Vasset, in her
70s, still sizes up her customers to determine how many eggs to put
in the omelete. When impressed, she goes up to five.
   ``I'm afraid for my kids,'' she says. ``Things are going badly in
France. No jobs, few prospects. I don't know what to expect.''
   Unemployment, in fact, seems to be easing slightly from its
persistent level of 10 percent, and officials insist things will
improve after 1992 when European partners forge a single market.
   Premier Michel Rocard, along with most of France's political
leaders, pushes hard for a tightly linked Europe in which France,
they say, will inevitably play a leading role.
   Chirac wields a sheaf of studies that predict Paris will evolve
back into its natural role as the capital of Europe.
   But that seems to be at the heart of the malaise Barbarin
mentioned, which few of the people who share his sentiment can put
in specific terms.
   The attraction of Paris is largely geographic. Its fast trains
and large airports will accommodate a polyglot tide, ebbing and
flowing from Portugal to the Baltic Sea.
   Already, the treasured City of Light is slipping from real life
into tourist brochures. Paris awakes to rebroadcasts of Dan Rather,
in English. Its menus are subtitled in German and Japanese.
   On the outskirts, EuroDisneyland is hiring 12,000 people and
training them to smile at strangers all day long.
   If the French capital is the capital of a borderless Europe, a
lot of people are beginning to ask, what happens to their certain
idea of France?
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
</DOC>
