<DOCNO> AP890703-0253 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 1424EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-APN--Jones'Travels Adv16-1stAdd   07-03 1088</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Jones' Travels, Adv 16-1st Add,1114</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday July 16</HEAD>
<HEAD>UNDATED: the cage.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   On one trip, as we reached the Kansas-Nebraska line, Dad decided
to look up a distant cousin whom he hadn't seen since boyhood.
   ``Ed is the Burlington Railroad station agent in Beatrice,'' said
Dad.
   ``I thought he lived in Wymore,'' said Mother.
   Dad snorted in disgust at fallible female memories. We roared
through Wymore and proceeded 14 miles on an unbelievably bad road to
Beatrice. Cousin Ed ran the station in Wymore.
   Furious, Dad retraced the route as though he were driving Ben
Hur's chariot, and I remember poor Tony, hanging upside down and
squawking, ``Good night! Good night!''
   Blig was not a pet, but a four-footed family member. When the
snooty desk clerk at the Hotel Fontenelle in Omaha made it plain
that dogs were unwelcome, Dick and I managed to get the terrorized
animal seven floors up the fire escape. The next morning, we all
came grandly down the elevator to the astonishment, if not delight,
of the staff.
   Blig's trust in us was deep, but not bottomless. Once, following
a sudden rain, when our car had slipped off the road three times in
a mile, Blig took his place in the truck at the head of the tow
line, gazing back at us anxiously through the rear window. The bones
that served him for 16 years lie beneath a handsome oak in south
Tulsa. He deserves his rest.
   The good earth of the Midwest, as the world knows, grows fine
corn and wheat, and, properly graded, it makes a tolerable road if
you can stand the dust. But the first sprinkles of an earnest rain
back in the early '20s meant things would happen fast to cars with
narrow, high-pressure tires (guaranteed for 8,000 miles).
   One time, the storm hit us when the Lamoni, Iowa, water tower was
already in sight. We didn't make it, and had to be hauled to the
beginning of Lamoni's brick pavement by a team. There we stayed for
three days, waiting for the roads to dry out enough to get us to Des
Moines.
   In three days, you can get pretty well acquainted with Lamoni,
which got its name out of the Book of Mormon and still possesses a
Latter-Day Saints college. In driving I-35, I have occasionally
turned off two miles to see if Lamoni has changed. It hasn't.
   Another town I knew intimately was Wamego, Kan., where we
remained for five days while a differential gear was making its way
on the Union Pacific from Kansas City. At Wamego there was a summer
Chautauqua, a strictly American invention named for the vacation
colony in New York state. They flourished best in the pre-movie and
pre-radio days and brought culture and entertainment to the
boondocks.
   Chautauquas featured famous preachers, humorous speakers,
ex-governors, Swiss bellringers, and dramatic selections like East
Lynne and Simon Slick from Punkin Crick. But for the faulty gear, I
would never have seen one.
   Much of city-living Young America today, alas, rides the
interstates, which is like going through a pipeline, or flies over
the clouds, either way without contact with rural life. It was
different if you cross-countried in the '20s.
   Our favorite touring car was a large open Marmon, painted in two
shades of green. We called it the Cucumber. It was marvelously
commodious, but its make was rare, and when we snapped a fan belt
and sought a replacement in village garages we might as well have
asked for new main bearings for the Mauretania.
   Thus it was that we once went boiling across southern Nebraska
from windmill to windmill, making the acquaintance of astonished
farmers and harvest hands. Of course, we were invited to lunch.
   Rural hospitality was great, partly out of native kindness and
partly because our windblown party with its traveling zoo generated
irrestible curiosity. But there were dangers, too.
   On one occasion, when the Cucumber spent the night in the ditch
near Storm Lake, Iowa, a concerned farm wife accommodated Dick and
me on a straw tick in the attic with a kerosene lamp for company.
   There was nothing to read but Dr. Winfield's Home Counselor, and
for weeks thereafter I came down successively with polio, leprosy,
appendicitis, tuberculosis and various dementias.
   No modern youngster has any idea of the confusion when all
America simultaneously was trying to struggle out of the mud. Road
improvements meant detours and a detour (French for ``turn from'')
was invariably worse than the road for which it substituted. Once,
when they were trying to build a passable road between Nowata and
Coffeyville, we literally drove down a creek bed.
   At that time, it was impossible to get a car from Tulsa to St.
Louis, for there was no road at all over the Ozarks. Citizens of
Springfield, determined to visit relatives in Lebanon or Rolla, took
the Frisco.
   On our second or third trip, Dad did succeed in getting in one
day from Tulsa to Horton, Kan. _ 265 miles. The speed impressed him
so much that he wrote an editorial about it.
   Usually, it took us from seven to nine days to reach Grandma's,
barring a major breakdown. In the meantime, unexpected intelligence
came to us.
   I remember a Lions Club luncheon to which we found ourselves
listening in the hotel dining room at Iola, or was it Yates Center?
Enthusiastic evangelists from Claremore described the therapeutic
effects of ``radium water'' in such technicolor detail _ the
bleeding sores, the running pus _ that we had a short lunch.
   We would finally arrive at the wonderful Victorian house that
Grandpa had ordered built for $4,000, a prodigy of extravagance for
a young lawyer. It is now 125 years old and occupied by a bishop.
   In spite of Dad's clenched teeth and unpredictable explosions, I
think, as I look back on it, that he was a paragon of patience.
   The best, I'm sure, Dad never intended. But by daring to drive
his family to Wisconsin when roads featured dust or gumbo, when
accommodations were chancy or worse, when tires were thin and gear
boxes fragile we all had a look at an America that the city kids
were missing and that would never come again.
   After almost seven decades, our journeys to Grandma's still live
with me. They added much to the wonder of it all.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Jenkin Lloyd Jones is publisher of the Tulsa
(Okla.) Tribune.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
