<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 1434EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-APN--ColaWars Adv16   07-03 0833</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Cola Wars, Adv 16,0859</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday July 16</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w photo,
1 cartoon.)</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Pepsi Cola recently found a buyer for 20 outmoded
Soviet warships, giving ``down the hatch'' a new meaning. Indeed,
Pepsi has had its toe in the Soviet Union for years, now operating
21 plants there. In exchange, it helps Moscow import Stolichnaya
vodka into the United States.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By SID MOODY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Are the fizzy ``cola wars'' about to be fought on a brand-new
battleground?
   Pepsi recently helped the Soviet Union sell 20 warships. That
puts them 13 more than seven-up on Coca-Cola. Coke has no navy. So
far.
   Has arms dealing opened a new chapter in American business? Will
Avis try harder by leasing tanks? Will Whoppers come with sesame
seed bombs?
   Pepsi Cola entered the arms race _ backward, actually _ by
finding a Norwegian scrap buyer for 17 Soviet submarines. Not the
kind of subs that in Boston come with sandwich meats, lettuce and
dressing. The kind that come with torpedoes.
   Pepsi was also middleman for sale of a Soviet cruiser, destroyer
and frigate, which is not exactly a glass of carbonated nost. It
gives ``down the hatch'' a new meaning for a soft drink guzzler.
   Pepsi scored a Kremlin coup over Coke in 1959 when boss Donald M.
Kendall adroitly cooled off the heated and world-televised
Khrushchev-Nixon ``kitchen debate'' by offering the combatants some
of his cola. Pepsi has had its toe in the Iron Curtain ever since.
   Pepsi now has 21 plants in the Soviet Union. In exchange it helps
Moscow import Stolichnaya vodka into the United States, which gives
parents pain relief from coping with the Pepsi Generation. Call it
fair trade.
   Recently Mikhail Gorbachev decided to sell off for scrap and hard
currency the 20 outmoded warships. It has been reported Pepsi
actually bought them. Nyet. It just found a buyer, for free.
Customer relations. Like taking a client to a ball game.
   Still ...
   Normally the weapons of business success in the United States
have been a better mousetrap or a smart lawyer. There have, however,
been infrequent corporate calls to arms.
   The very Associated Press that brings you this dispatch had its
origins in 1848 partly because packet boats of rival New York papers
hunting the seas for incoming European news began shooting at one
another in an excess of competitive zeal. Damn the torpedoes! (and
the expense) cried Manhattan's many publishers. Let's buy one packet
and pool the news. And the costs.
   One of the most memorable corporate defense forces belonged to
Jim Fisk, unarguably profiled by his biographer as ``an improbable
rascal.''
   Fisk rose from circus hand and Yankee peddler after the Civil War
to become a boardroom buccaneer, great of mirth and girth and a
waxed mustache ``the color of a Jersey cow.''
   When he acquired two steamers that plied between New York and New
England, he ornamented the staterooms with 250 singing canaries and
himself in the dress uniform of a U.S. admiral further embellished
with diamonds that festooned his corpulence.
   Admiral Fisk, who his biographer says couldn't distinguish a
compass from a capstan, later added a land force, New York's
languishing Ninth Regiment. He became its colonel and recruited from
his Grand Opera House where he oversaw both his Erie Railroad, whose
stock he lavishly watered, and the Demon Can-Can girls whom he as
liberally champagned.
   He enlisted the Opera House orchestra as regimental band, which
saluted him by playing ``Hail to the Chief.'' The colonel-admiral
even took the boys with him on bivouac to fashionable Long Branch,
N.J., where maneuvers were described by cynics as ``a monumental
weeklong drunk'' in the command post at the Continental Hotel.
   Fisk's army, alas, could not protect their leader from being
slain by a jealous rival for the pudgy but bejeweled hand of Josie
Mansfield, an aspiring actress delicately said to have bartered
``purity for subsistence.''
   Since Fisk's day, the corporate uniform of the day has quieted
down to dark suits enlivened by a necktie somber enough to be buried
in. Rather than 250 canaries and a regimental orchestra, Pepsi has
only Michael Jackson to sing its praises.
   But Pepsi has struck first in the battleship biz. While it is
helping to recycle old warships, Coke has only its familiar aluminum
cans to send to the smelter. Is there an arms racer on the horizon?
   Kendall reportedly chortled to Brent Scowcroft, the White House
security adviser, that Pepsi is ``disarming the Soviet Union faster
than you are.''
   If that is so and nose-tickling cola turns out to be the missing
key to world peace, Pepsi can boast it started the dove rolling
ahead of Coca-Cola. Somehow Coke is going to have to get into the
peace race, strive for the higher ground.
   Maybe, for starters, make a bid on scrapping the Iron Curtain.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
</DOC>
