<FIRST>s i BC-AsianStudents-India Adv09   07-03 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Asian Students-India, Adv 09,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday July 9 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>U.S.-Educated Whiz Kid Comes Home to India</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Asian Students, b0763-b0764</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIJAY JOSHI</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Satyen G. Pitroda was an Indian village
boy who had never used a telephone when at the age of 21 he went off
for a U.S. education.
   Twenty-two years later, after acquiring a degree in electronics
at the Illinois Institute of Technology in Chicago, a
multimillion-dollar bank account, 50 international patents on
digital switching systems and the American nickname ``Sam,'' he came
home to try to revolutionize India's telecommunications system.
   Pitroda gave up the U.S. citizenship he had acquired and an
annual income of $550,000 when he returned to India in 1986 and
offered to work for the government for one rupee (6 cents) a year.
   Today he is Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi's technology adviser and
holds the rank of minister of state.
   ``After 40 you don't get trapped in making money. You don't have
to worry about survival,'' said Pitroda, who retained major U.S.
shareholdings after selling his Chicago-based digital switching
company for $50 million.
   His main job now is to add 27 million telephone lines to the
existing 3 million connections in this nation of 880 million people
by the year 2000 and to integrate overall telecom development with
other national modernization programs.
   Gandhi entrusted him with other prime programs, safer drinking
water, eradication of illiteracy, immunization of children, dairy
development and cooking oil production.
   ``I would like to describe myself as a bit of a manager, a part
entrepreneur, a good telecom engineer and a committed worker,'' said
the 46-year-old Pitroda.
   The son of a carpenter, Pitroda was graduated from Maharajah
Sayajirao University in the western town of Baroda in 1964 with a
degree in physics. The university had telephones but Pitroda said he
never had the need to use one.
   He enrolled at the Illinois Institute of Technology and got a
master's degree in electronics in 1966.
   After working for other people, Pitroda set up a digital
switching company that in eight years commanded annual sales of $100
million.
   ``I really don't know why I went to the U.S.,'' Pitroda said. ``I
also don't know why I came back. But it has been immensely
satisfying. I don't think I'll go back to the U.S., although my two
kids miss it terribly.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday July 9</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890703-0262 </DOCNO>
