<FIRST>s i BC-AsianStudents-Taiwan Adv09   07-03 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Asian Students-Taiwan, Adv 09,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday July 9 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>U.S.-Educated Officials Dominate Taiwan's Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Asian Students, b0763-b0764</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE HUANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nationalist Chinese government and
party hierarchy have a distinct U.S. background and this has been
reflected in the more liberal policies of President Lee Teng-hui's
administration.
   Lee, 66, who is also chairman of the Nationalist Party, was
educated at Iowa State University at Ames and Cornell University in
Ithaca, N.Y., and 17 of the 25 members of his Cabinet studied in the
United States.
   Observers say time spent in the United States has made Taiwan's
new leaders more pragmatic and liberal than the older generation of
Nationalist leaders who fled to Taiwan in 1949 when they lost a
civil war to the Communists on the Chinese mainland.
   One of the new leaders regarded as the brightest is James Soong,
47, secretary general of the party, No. 2 behind Lee.
   Soong was educated at the University of California at Berkeley
and Catholic University of America in Washington, D.C., before
earning a doctorate in political science from Georgetown University
in the U.S. capital.
   ``His U.S. education has made him bold to make reforms while most
bureaucrats merely followed old practices to avoid backlashes from
changes,'' said Kan Yu-lung, chairman of the China Daily News. Kan
spent five years as deputy to Soong when the latter was director of
the Government Information Office, which controls the media in
Taiwan.
   Insiders say Soong, when he was the party's deputy secretary
general in 1987, encouraged Lee's predecessor, Chiang Ching-kuo, to
end 38 years of martial law and allow Taiwanese and mainland Chinese
to exchange visits.
   Last year, after Chiang died, Soong risked his political career
by rebuking the party's old guard for their reluctance to support
Lee, Chiang's hand-picked successor, as chairman of the Nationalist
Party. The party, in the end, made Lee chairman.
   Soong, son of a Nationalist general, has shunned interviews and
maintained a low profile, but this had not hurt his popularity. He
also has won over party elders.
   ``He is a man of vitality who still retains many traditional
Chinese virtues such as modesty and respect to elders,'' said Kan.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday July 9</NOTE>
</DOC>
