<DOCNO> AP890703-0263 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 2140EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--FilmReview Adv00   07-03 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Film Review, Adv 00,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At The Movies: `Weekend at Bernie's'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Film opens July 5.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Can dead bodies be funny? Alfred Hitchcock thought so, and in
1955 he made a minor classic, ``The Trouble With Harry,'' Harry
being a murdered man nobody could get rid of.
   One of the most side-splitting sequences of TV's ``Fawlty
Towers'' concerned John Cleese's attempt to hide a guest who had
checked out _ mortally _ at the hotel.
   Comedy corpses had less success in Blake Edward's ``S.O.B.,''
with Richard Mulligan as the errant cadaver, and ``W.C. Fields and
Me,'' in which Fields and friends took the deceased John Barrymore
on a last tour of nightclubs (it supposedly happened).
   Now comes ``Weekend at Bernie's'' to prove that yes, stiffs can
be hilarious. Credit goes to the feathery direction of Ted Kotcheff
(``Fun With Dick and Jane''), a wildly improbable script by Robert
Klane (``Where's Poppa''), and the razor-sharp work of two young
farceurs, Andrew McCarthy and Jonathan Silverman.
   McCarthy and Silverman are ambitious young employees at a
Manhattan insurance company. While preparing a moneymaking venture
for the firm, they uncover evidence of a complicated fraud scheme.
   When the pair present their boss, Bernie, with the discovery, he
suggests they join him for Labor Day weekend at his pleasure palace
at the Hamptons on Long Island. What they don't know is that Bernie
has been running the scam with the help of the Mafia.
   McCarthy and Silverman arrive at Bernie's and find him dead,
plugged by a hit man with pride in his job. To save themselves, the
two must make it appear that Bernie is still alive and well. They
somehow accomplish this at parties, on streets and in boats.
   That's about it, except for a romantic sideplot with Silverman
and Catherine Mary Stewart, the office beauty. But the interplay
between the two young men and their late boss is enough to keep one
helplessly laughing.
   What keeps ``Weekend at Bernie's'' from being a perfect comedy
such as ``Big'' is the sketchy characterization of the two leads.
McCarthy is an overbearing slob, and Silverman is so timid he can't
ask the gorgeous Stewart for a date. Both actors flawlessly handle
the comedy; too bad their roles weren't better defined.
   Special credit must go to Terry Kiser as Bernie. Playing dead
through most of a feature movie is no joke, and he admirably meets
the challenge.
   Victor Drai produced the 20th Century Fox release for Gladden
Entertainment. The rating is PG-13 with some swearing and much
macabre humor. Running time: 100 minutes.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for children
under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890703-0264 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 2141EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo Adv00   07-03 0696</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Home Video, Adv 00,0726</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``The Cocoanuts'' (MCA Home Video. VHS-Beta, $19.95)
   
   Dare we call a film starring the Marx Brothers, with music and
lyrics by Irving Berlin, and with a book by George S. Kaufman, a
bore?
   We dare.
   The movie in question is ``The Cocoanuts,'' made in the infancy
of the talk era.
   Now, to the balance sheet:
   No film with Groucho Marx could be all bad. Groucho, who plays
the proprietor of the ``Hotel de Cocoanut,'' has an absolute
monopoly on the funny moments in this spoof of the 1920s Florida
land boom.
   He and Chico do their classic ``Why a duck?'' bit. And as usual,
Groucho labors tirelessly and hilariously for the affections of
Margaret Dumont, the rich and available heiress in practically every
Marx Brothers film.
   ``You wouldn't love me if I was poor,'' she protests.
   ``I might, but I'd keep my mouth shut,'' replies Groucho.
   It's also kind of fun to see the flapper costumes the women wore.
And Hollywood historians can probably find all sorts of interest in
how paralyzed cameramen and sound crews were at that time.
   But beware _ of the long, long, long, long music and dancing
interludes. Every Marx Brothers film featured musical bits by Chico
and Harpo, as well as several songs by an annoying tenor _ facts
that Groucho himself often bemoaned.
   In ``The Cocoanuts,'' the long-forgotten Oscar Shaw, the
ostensible ``love interest,'' sings and acts so ridiculously and
badly that you will reach for your fast-forward button. It hardly
seems possible to make Berlin tunes sound rotten, but Shaw does it.
   The choreography is unwatchable, a kind of dopey callisthenics
rather than dancing, and not very strenuous at that.
   This is definitely not a Marx Brothers picture to create new fans
for the boys. Repeated viewing could even lose some old ones. Made
in 1929 in living black and white.
   _ By Lee Mitgang, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Talk Radio'' (MCA Home Video. VHS-BETA, $89.95. Rated R)
   
   ``Talk Radio,'' Eric Bogosian's dialogue with the depraved and
the depressed as a talk show host, is one hour and 40 minutes of
compelling chatter.
   He roves out loud through the ravages of his own twisted
consciousness, and the net effect leaves one feeling like he or she
has scaled the Tower of Babel.
   ``Talk Radio'' is Oliver Stone's adaptation of Bogosian's one-act
play of the same title about a provocative radio personality. It
also is based in part on the story of radio talk show host Alan
Berg, who was killed in 1984 by white supremacists.
   Bogosian goads his racist callers, ridicules his fans and offers
a sympathetic ear to the truly troubled. His monologues build a
frenetic pitch of words, then stall for a gasp, and then begin all
over again.
   The talk show format is anything goes, so long as what's going is
controversial. A rapist calls to beg for help and describe his last
attack. Anti-Semites reel off strings of Jew-hating epithets.
Paranoids detail their convoluted fears, including one woman who is
obsessed with what she'll find at the bottom of her garbage disposal.
   Much of movie itself, in fact, resembles the verbal equivalent of
that goo and grime languishing in the dank crevices of a garbage
disposal. It's humanity at its worst, which leads Bogosian to
wistfully conclude, ``I guess we're stuck with each other.''
   It's riveting for a while, as voyeuristic thrills go, but after
the din dies the final sensation is exhaustion. That, and an intense
desire to shower off all that scum.
   _ By Patricia Bibby, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for children
under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
