<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Griffin Adv14-16   07-03 0868</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Griffin, Adv 14-16,0886</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 14</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv 16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions July 14-16 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Star Watch: From Band Singer to Billionaire</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Merv Griffin made $250 million in
one week.
   Coca-Cola offered to buy his production company, and paid $250
million. In seven days, he became a Great American Fortune _ ``for
me and, I'm sure, for great-great-great grandchildren _ if I don't
blow the whole thing.''
   Griffin's transformation from band singer to talk show host to
billionaire is one of the remarkable stories of show business. It
amazes him, too. The latest phase, he admits, is all due to a few TV
game shows he concocted _ ``Wheel of Fortune'' and ``Jeopardy.''
Those were the prizes for which Coca-Cola paid all that money.
   Even with an empire that includes film and television companies,
the Beverly Hilton Hotel, resorts and casinos in the Bahamas and
Atlantic City and four radio stations, Griffin still yearns to sing
with a band. He was to do just that over the Fourth of July weekend
at his Resorts International in Atlantic City.
   ``You know something?'' he muses. ``Exactly 40 years ago I played
the Atlantic City Steel Pier with Freddy Martin's band. We appeared
before 150,000 people over the July 4th weekend.
   ``How much was I getting? Let's see, I started with Freddy at
$125, then got a raise to $150. When I had a hit record with `I've
Got a Lovely Bunch of Coconuts,' he raised me to $200.''
   Griffin, 64, talked about a variety of matters during a lunch at
his regular table in Mr. H's, the Beverly Hilton restaurant. He is a
bit stouter than in his talk-show days (``it's a constant battle''),
but he spoke just as ebulliently as when he was questioning authors
about their new self-help books.
   He gazed with pride at the swimming pool area that had once
looked like a motel with its all-weather carpet. Now it resembled an
oasis with lush greenery. Griffin also was adding a small forest on
the Wilshire Boulevard frontage, and everywhere in the hotel signs
of change could be seen.
   ``I have the most valuable property in Beverly Hills, nine acres
in the best location,'' he said. ``I had an offer two weeks ago from
the Japanese. I said, `No, thanks, I haven't finished it yet.' ''
   ``The Merv Griffin Show'' went off the air in 1986 after 23
years, and he devoted his attention to his busy production company.
Then the Coca-Cola buyout provided a shower of cash that was almost,
but not quite, embarrassing.
   ``I called Arthur Laffer, who was largely responsible for Mr.
Reagan's economic program,'' Griffin said. ``Arthur told me, `Spread
it around, Merv. Some in Treasury bonds, a little in the stock
market, a little in this.' He sent a lot of people to me, and I
chose the ones I liked.
   ``I did all that, and I was never so bored in my life. First of
all, they don't come and pile (the money) on a desk so you don't
know you got it. They call and say they wired it to your bank. They
wired my bank and the computer broke down. Then they roll it over,
and you get interest statements and all that.
   ``I said, `I'm not going to sit and do this for the rest of my
life.' That's when Barron Hilton said, `Merv, do you wanna buy the
Beverly Hilton?' I couldn't believe it.
   ``I had a little tussle with the Japanese. They topped my offer
by a lot, but then they had their Black Monday the same time we did.
So they pulled out, and I went back with my original offer ($102
million).''
   Then came the battle with Donald Trump over possession of Resorts
International. In the end they settled the dispute with Griffin
getting most of Resorts except for the unfinished Taj Mahal in
Atlantic City.
   Griffin, who doesn't seem to get mad at anybody, has mellowed in
his relationship to Trump.
   ``We're not buddies; we don't talk on the phone every day,'' said
Griffin. ``We speak through our representatives, but we get along
fine. His goals are a bit different from mine. He's a young man, and
he must constantly let the crowd out there perceive that he has won
on everything. He's only here on Earth to win.
   ``That's OK, because that's the business he's in. I am not in
that same business. I buy what I enjoy.''
   Griffin reported gleefully that he and Trump will join in a
mutual enterprise: as judges in the Miss America pageant _ ``we'll
both vote for each other.''
   The golden touch of Merv Griffin will soon fall on another TV
game show based on Monopoly, the venerable board game that uses
street and place names of Atlantic City. Pilot programs have been
produced under his supervision.
   ``It's so funny,'' he said. ``On the show we move these little
red houses around on Boardwalk and North Carolina and Connecticut
Avenue. In real life I own them anyway.''
</TEXT>
