<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Karsh Adv14-16   07-03 0834</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Karsh, Adv 14-16,0859</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 14</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv 16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions June 14-16 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: Not Just the Famous Were `Karshed'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The light playing off the glass entryway to the new
National Gallery of Canada was dazzling as photographer Yousuf Karsh
arrived for his first glimpse of the largest retrospective ever
prepared of his work.
   ``No two mornings are alike,'' the 80-year-old photographer
observed.
   Given the choice of taking an elevator or walking up the ramp
full of light and shadow, Karsh started walking without hesitation.
   This, after all, is a man who describes his craft with such words
as dedication, curiosity, responsibility and challenge, then adds
that none of it should be evident.
   ``The human face is the great challenge in the world,'' Karsh
said, conducting the interview as he toured the gallery. ``I never
tire of it _ and everyone is different.''
   He described his recent trip to photograph Pakistani Prime
Minister Benazir Bhutto as enthusiastically as his recollections of
getting Winston Churchill to pose in 1941.
   ``It's still to date my greatest diplomatic triumph,'' Karsh said
of the session nearly half a century ago that ended up on the cover
of Life magazine and clinched his reputation.
   The photo of a defiant Churchill ``appealed to the whole world,''
he said. ``It caught all the bulldog determination of the British
Empire. ... It was done without premeditation but with great
admiration and respect.''
   The portraits of the rich, talented, powerful and famous
certainly are the most prominent among the 198 photographs on
display at the National Gallery's main exhibition space through
September, but the retrospective shows that Karsh has other
interests as well.
   ``This is a very tender picture,'' he said, stopping at a
photograph for a commissioned ``Faces of Canada'' series taken at a
hospital in Edmonton, Alberta, in 1952. ``She was just a sick lady,
but look at the serenity of that face.''
   Karsh said the idea that he only photographed celebrities ``is
totally wrong, because I have photographed the people who are less
famous for all of my life.''
   Closest to the entrance to the exhibit are photos taken for
muscular dystrophy fund-raising campaigns, a special interest of
recent years and virtually the only ones he has taken not on
assignment or commission.
   The retrospective at the year-old National Gallery takes on
additional significance because it is just blocks away from Karsh's
studio in Ottawa's landmark Chateau Laurier hotel.
   The studio features Karsh trademark photos in its foyer _ the
writer Ernest Hemingway, Churchill, the artist Georgia O'Keeffe and
cellist Pablo Casals.
   The photographer described his living situation as ideal, being
able to maintain a home in peaceful Ottawa while traveling the world
on his assignments.
   Karsh is from an Armenian family that fled Turkey in 1922. He
came to Canada two years later, where he joined an uncle who was a
photographer. Although Karsh originally planned to become a doctor,
by 1932 he had opened his first Ottawa photography studio.
   His training was to photograph using available light, but
involvement with the Ottawa Little Theater taught him to use studio
lighting to create a mood. As a result, the lighting is often
dramatic in his photographs.
   He said he preferred to photograph his subjects as much as
possible in their own environment.
   ``The question is to know as much about the people as possible,
to do your homework in advance and to listen,'' he said. ``You have
to have true understanding of the subject you photograph.''
   Karsh's advice also is to be a student of the humanities, to
learn about history, music, art and travel. ``All this allows you to
be a more sensitive recorder of what you are doing,'' he said.
   The actual moment of taking a photograph, he said, ``becomes
intuitive more than anything else. You don't have time to analyze.''
   As he sat at the exhibition before his portraits of a young Fidel
Castro and author Vladimir Nabokov to have his own picture taken,
Karsh asked to be involved in conversation, to be provoked, so that
more action and expression could be captured.
   The Cuban president, he said, is ``never tiresome.'' Nabokov was
``a beautiful, sensitive, colorful writer, but as a human being he's
not my number one choice.''
   Karsh's wife, Estrellita, travels with him and had memories of
her own on seeing the photographs hanging at the National Gallery.
Artist Man Ray was ``so wonderful''; the artist Joan Miro gradually
relaxed as he sat in the Paris studio where he did lithographs, and
the manifestations of a famous artist faded into the kindly man seen
in his portrait.
   Estrellita Karsh stopped for a moment in front of the 1946
photograph of a young, spectacularly beautiful Ingrid Bergman.
   ``Was she that gorgeous, Yousof?'' she asked. ``Jeepers.''
   ``Yes, she was,'' Karsh quietly replied about the late actress.
</TEXT>
