<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Riders Adv14-16   07-03 0802</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Riders, Adv 14-16,0830</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 14</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv 16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions July 14-16 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Buckaroos and Buckarettes Saddle 'em Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OK, buckaroos and buckarettes. Return
with us now to those thrilling days of yesteryear when cowboys rode
into the sunset in a wild, untamed land.
   Riders in the Sky, a buckskin singing trio, have rejuvenated the
Western radio serial with their weekly Riders Radio Theater on 100
National Public Radio stations.
   For 30 minutes each week, the three sing such Western tunes as
``Tumbling Tumbleweed,'' perform zany skits and present serials with
old West and contemporary themes.
   ``We've staked out a patch of range on the airwaves,'' says
Ranger Doug, who calls himself ``the idol of American youth.''
   Ranger Doug, who really is Douglas Green, is joined by cowboy
cohorts Woody Paul, ``the king of the cowboy fiddlers,'' and Too
Slim, ``bassist and mercantilist supreme.''
   The gunslingers and desperadoes don't stand a chance against
these guys.
   ``I think we're bringing back a tradition that had been forgotten
for the last 25 or 30 years,'' said Too Slim, who is Fred LaBour in
real life.
   Taped in Nashville in the format of an old-time radio show, the
program has become one of the most popular on public radio since
Garrison Keillor's ``Prairie Home Companion.''
   The show, which airs in Canada and Australia besides the United
States, just won awards from the Corporation for Public Broadcasting
for technical achievement and general music.
   Commercial radio stations are beginning to sign up for the
program as well.
   ``This is a real breakthrough,'' said Woody Paul, who really is
Paul Woodrow Chrisman. He has a doctorate in physics from
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, but would rather earn his
living playing the fiddle.
   Playing cowboy has enabled him and his faithful sidekicks to do
battle against the villainous Slocum, their arch enemy on the show
since its premiere last October.
   In a continuining saga titled ``Meltdown on the Mesa,'' Slocum
and other bunkhouse badmen tried to use a nuclear reactor against
prairie dogs. They attempted to buy off the good guys by generously
offering a condominium.
   The trio got able assistance from Sidemeat, their devoted trail
cook who bakes biscuits referred to as ``the hardest substance known
to man.''
   Another show fixture is the announcer, Bix Bender, ``the voice
that sold a million baby chicks.''
   But the program is more than humor. The trio sing with pristine
precision while playing acoustic guitar, fiddle and standup bass.
   ``Several people say it's the fastest half-hour in radio,''
Ranger Doug said.
   The three, all around 40 years old, say the show has developed a
cult following.
   ``There are people who know the plots and want to discuss them,''
Too Slim said. ``They miss a week and want to know what happened.
Some people make up their own plots and send them in, like `Sidemeat
and the Beanstalk.'
   ``They write long, literate letters about the show,'' he said.
``The public radio audience is quick and appreciative when you do a
quality show.''
   The trio have been donning 10-gallon hats, kerchiefs and faded
chaps to sing their Western music for more than 10 years. They
perform regularly on the Grand Ole Opry, and were hosts of a Western
movie show, ``Tumbleweed Theater,'' for three seasons on The
Nashville Network on cable TV.
   They have recorded about a dozen albums, including the current
``Riders Go Commercial.'' They were in the movie ``Sweet Dreams,''
about the life of country star Patsy Cline, and in the Kenny Rogers
TV movie ``Wild Horses.''
   They also were favorites on ``Prairie Home Companion.''
   The trio believe they have filled a void by representing Western
heroes for youngsters. For the past few years, kids have embraced
such characters as Luke Skywalker, Han Solo, Indiana Jones and now
Batman as their heroes instead of such buckskin baritones as Tex
Ritter who were idolized by their parents, the three said.
   ``They just don't know any singing cowboys,'' Ranger Doug said.
``A kid age 7 doesn't even know Roy Rogers. They know He Man and
Batman.''
   A key to the show has been its family orientation.
   ``We're in an age where there is not a lot of mass popular
culture that parents feel comfortable enjoying with their
children,'' Ranger Doug said. ``Riders Radio Theater has something
for everybody.''
   For Woody Paul, his role fulfills a childhood ambition.
   ``I dreamed of playing a cowboy when I was a kid and here I am,''
he said. ``I ask the kids at the concerts what they want to be when
they grow up and they say they don't know. I say I don't know
either.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions July 14-16</NOTE>
</DOC>
