<TEXT>
   Stock prices were mostly lower in a sluggish,
holiday atmosphere on Wall Street today.
   The 10 a.m. Dow Jones average of 30 industrials stood at
2,440.06, unchanged from Friday's close.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by more than 5 to 3 in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 331 up, 568
down and 396 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 12.22 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Wall Street was expecting a slow session, given the absence of
many market participants taking a long July 4 weekend. The markets
will be closed on Tuesday.
   That helped make it difficult for stocks to mount a rally from
last week's decline, which was the steepest in more than 15 months.
   Analysts said traders' thoughts had begun to focus more intently
of late on the chances that the economy might in for something worse
than the much-ballyhooed ``soft landing'' bullish forecasters have
been predicting.
   New evidence of softening business activity emerged this morning
from a monthly survey of corporate purchasing executives, who
reported the first drop in new orders in more than three years.
   Minnetonka, traded in the over-the-counter market, fell 2| to
22]. The company agreed to be acquired by Unilever N.V. for $22.86 a
share.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks lost
.31 to 177.59. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .54 at 358.43.
   On Friday the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 18.21 to
2,440.06, stretching its loss for the week to 91.81 points.
   That marked the biggest weekly drop for the average since it
tumbled 108.42 points March 21-25, 1988.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 7 to 5 on the
NYSE, with 637 up, 894 down and 437 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 170.49 million shares, against 167.10
million in the previous session.
