<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 1209EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-RigCount     07-03 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Rig Count,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rig Count Increases for Sixth Straight Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of working oil and gas rigs increased
by seven rigs this week to 817, marking the sixth straight weekly
gain, according to Baker Hughes Inc.
   The nationwide count increased by 15 last week. A year ago, the
count totaled 921, Baker Hughes reported Monday.
   The company's rig count _ the widely watched industry index of
drilling activity _ reflects the number of rigs actively exploring
for oil as of last Friday, not the number of rigs actively producing
oil.
   Houston-based Hughes Tool Co., an oil tool making company that
merged with Baker International Corp. of Orange, Calif., has kept
track of the rig count since 1940.
   In December 1981, at the height of the oil boom, the rig count
reached a peak of 4,500. But oil prices plunged to less than $10 per
42-gallon barrel in the summer of 1986, prompting a collapse in the
rig count that bottomed out at 663 _ the lowest since Hughes began
compiling figures.
   Among major oil producing states, California saw the biggest gain
with eight additional rigs, followed by Wyoming, five; Oklahoma,
three; Colorado, two and Louisiana and Ohio, one each.
   Texas had the biggest drop with nine fewer rigs, followed by
North Dakota, three; Michigan and New Mexico, two each, and
Pennsylvania, one. Kansas remained unchanged from last week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890703-0280 </DOCNO>
