<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 1228EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   07-03 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mixed on Weather, Stocks Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices were lower, corn was higher
and soybeans were mixed this morning on the Chicago Board of Trade
in reaction to dry weather forecasts for the Midwest and a
government report on grain stocks.
   Wheat's modest decline stemmed from an Agriculture Department
report released Friday that pegged U.S. wheat stocks at 694 million
bushels as of June 1, far above the approximately 625 million
bushels that traders had expected.
   The USDA's tallies of warehoused corn and soybeans also were
larger than the market anticipated, but not to the same degree as
the wheat number.
   Corn and soybean traders paid closer attention to forecasts for a
weak of hot, dry weather in the Midwest. Crops in the western Corn
Belt are especially in need of rain.
   Soybean prices for near-term delivery were a little lower in
reaction to the devaluation of Brazil's currency, making Brazilian
soybeans more competitive on the world market.
   Early activity was quiet, with many traders stretching the Fourth
of July holiday into a four-day weekend.
   In early trading, wheat was 1 cent to 3{ cents lower with the
contarct for delivery in July at $3.96\ cents a bushel; corn was }
cent to 2{ cents higher with July at $2.67{ a bushel; oats were 2}
cents to 3\ cents higher with July at $1.52\ a bushel; soybeans were
2 cents lower to 7} cents higher with July at $7.33 a bushel.
   On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, trading in hog and pork belly
futures was virtually frozen with all contracts down their permitted
daily limits in reaction to Friday's USDA hogs and pigs report.
   The USDA counted substantially more animals that the market had
expected.
   Cattle futures were sharply lower in sympathy with the pork
complex.
   Live cattle were .37 cent to .67 cent lower with August at 69.30
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .52 cent to .60 cent lower with
August at 80.30 cents a pound; hogs were 1.50 cents lower across the
board with July at 47.17 cents a pound; and, frozen pork bellies
were 2 cents lower across the board with July at 33.85 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled lower on Friday while pork futures
finished mixed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
