<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 1232EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-ConstructionSpending 1stLd-Writethru f0030 07-03 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Construction Spending, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0030,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Projects Push Construction Spending Up in May</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS last graf to change new housing units figure to $138.6
billion annual rate. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Construction spending, continuing to be led by
an increase in work on government projects, rose 1.3 percent in May,
the government reported today.
   The Commerce Department reported that spending on both public and
private construction rose to a seasonally adjusted $421.3 billion in
May, following a 0.8 percent drop in April and a 0.2 percent rise in
March.
   While public construction rose 6.7 percent in May to $86.2
billion, private construction remained flat at a seasonally adjusted
annual rate of $335.1 billion, the department said. Private
construction had fallen 1.6 percent in March.
   The construction industry has been among the sectors of the
economy hardest hit recently by the Federal Reserve's campaign to
halt inflation by tightening credit and thus boosting interest rates.
   May's spending level was 3.3 percent above the pace in May 1988.
   Spending on private, non-residential construction projects rose
2.6 percent in May to an annual rate of $98.7 billion.
   But construction of new housing units fell 2.5 percent to a
$138.6 billion annual rate. Spending on single-family homes fell 1.5
percent, while construction of multi-family units was off 6.7
percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
