<DOCNO> AP890703-0283 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 1359EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-LIN-McCaw     07-03 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-LIN-McCaw,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>LIN Asks Stockholders To Reject McCaw $120-a-Share Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   LIN Broadcasting Corp.'s board of directors has
rejected as inadequate a $5.85 billion takeover offer from McCaw
Cellular Communications Inc. and is calling on stockholders to do
likewise, the company said Monday.
   LIN said its board concluded at a special meeting on Saturday
after conferring with financial advisors Wasserstein Perella &amp; Co.
that the $120-a-share offer was not in the best interest of
shareholders.
   LIN originally decided on June 19 to reject the offer from
McCaw's parent MMM Holdings Inc., and explore other alternatives.
   Lin, which has interests in cellular telephones, television and
publishing, said its alternatives included staying independent,
recapitalizing or selling itself to other potential buyers.
   On Friday, LIN lost a legal fight with Metromedia Co. over LIN's
claims to interests held by Metromedia in cellular telephone
companies in New York and Philadelphia.
   Had LIN prevailed over Metromedia, its stock value might have
risen as much as $40 a share, some analysts said. A defeat, they
predicted, could prompt McCaw to amend its offer.
   LIN's stock price tumbled $7.12{ a share on Friday to $115.87{ in
national over-the-counter trading.
   LIN said Monday that the company had rejected McCaw's offer last
month without taking the Metromedia litigation into consideration.
   ``Some might assume we thought our stock was worth more than $120
a share with the possible favorable outcome with Metromedia,'' said
Michael Plouf, a LIN vice president. ``We think it was worth more
than $120 regardless of the Metromedia litigation.''
   LIN said further that McCaw had not received approval from the
Federal Communications Commission and state regulatory authorities
to purchase LIN common stock and had not obtained adequate financing.
   James Abernathy, a spokesman for Kirkland, Wash.-based McCaw,
said there was no new comment from the company. After Friday's
ruling, McCaw had said it was disappointed in the outcome of the
litigation and would review the court's decision.
   It also noted that McCaw reserved the right to amend its June 8
offer, which expires Thursday, in the event of adverse developments
in the LIN-Metromedia litigation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
