<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     07-03 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0294</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices staged a modest upswing in very
quiet pre-July 4 trading today.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, down 91.81 points last
week, recovered 10.05 to 2,450.11 by 2 p.m. today on Wall Street.
   Gainers slightly outnumbered losers in nationwide trading of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 668 up, 611 down and 534
unchanged.
   Wall Street was expecting a slow pace of activity, given the
absence of many market participants taking a long July 4 weekend.
The markets will be closed on Tuesday.
   That helped make it difficult for stocks to mount a rally from
last week's decline, which was the steepest in more than 15 months.
   Analysts said traders' thoughts had begun to focus more intently
of late on the chances that the economy might in for something worse
than the much-ballyhooed ``soft landing'' bullish forecasters have
been predicting.
   New evidence of softening business activity emerged this morning
from a monthly survey of corporate purchasing executives, who
reported the first drop in new orders in more than three years.
   Gainers among the blue chips included International Business
Machines, up \ at 112[; USX, up [ at 34|; Philip Morris, up } at
139], and General Electric, up \ at 51~.
   Minnetonka, traded in the over-the-counter market, fell 2{ to
22{. The company agreed to be acquired by Unilever N.V. for $22.86 a
share.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.45 to 178.35. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .62 at 358.35.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 51.76 million shares with two
hours to go.
