<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 1436EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-BritishStocks 1stLd-Writethru f0017 07-03 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0017,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Rise</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later activity, closing index;
No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices staged a modest rebound from last
week's losses to close significantly higher Monday on the London
Stock Exchange.
   Enthusiasm generated by corporate takeover activity overcame the
negative implications of a sharp upward revision in British retail
sales for May, analysts said.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index finished 14.6
points, or 0.67 percent, higher at 2,165.6. At its best, the index
was up 16.0 points at late morning, shortly before the retail sales
data were released. The market opened at its lowest level, with the
100-share index showing a gain of 3.9 points.
   Volume was meager, subdued in part because of quiet trading on
Wall Street before Tuesday's U.S. Independence Day holiday. The
London market saw 410.8 million shares change hands, down sharply
from 550.4 million on Friday.
   There was a small amount of buying interest at the outset of
trading on the first day of a new quarter and a new trading account,
analysts said. Activity then picked up as Boots Co., a
pharmaceutical retailer, launched an 800 million pound ($1.26
billion) hostile takeover bid for Ward White Group, a diversified
retailer and manufacturer.
   ``That helped sentiment. But the tone of the market was positive
even before the bid came out,'' said one dealer.
   Some of the market's robustness was dented, however, by the
retail sales report, which suggested that spending by British
consumers hasn't been curbed by high interest rates.
   The data showed that retail sales volume rose a revised 3.0
percent in May from April, the largest monthly rise in more than two
years. The government, which originally reported a 2.5 percent rise
for the month, said that recent retail sales figures have been
erratic and cautioned against reading too much into the data.
   The narrower Financial Times 30-share index was up 7.1 points at
1,791.6. The Financial Times 500 index was up 7.77 at 1,231.31.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
