<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   07-03 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corn, Soybeans Surge on Dry Outlook</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybeans futures prices closed sharply
higher Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid forecasts of an
extended spell of hot, dry weather in the Midwest.
   Oat futures also advanced while wheat futures prices fell
moderately in reaction to Friday's Argiculture Department
grain-stocks report, which indicated U.S. wheat stockpiles were
larger than traders had figured.
   Prices for most corn and soybean contracts rose at the opening
bell following a weekend of dry weather in the Corn Belt and were
bolstered by Monday's forecasts.
   ``Some forecasters don't see any rain at all for the next week or
so and that was the whole ballgame,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a
trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   The National Weather Service predicted mostly dry conditions in
the Midwest in a six-to-10-day forecast issued after the close of
trading, which could prompt further buying on Wednesday.
   The markets will be closed Tuesday, the Fourth of July.
   At the close, wheat settled 1 cent to 2} cents lower with July at
$3.94{ a bushel; corn was 4\ cents to 8} cents higher with July at
$2.72 a bushel; oats were 7{ cents to 8 cents higher with July at
$1.57 a bushel; soybeans were 5{ cents to 19 cents higher with July
at $7.40{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
