<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     07-03 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down; Gold Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished lower against all major
currencies in thin, pre-holiday trading Monday following a selloff
overseas.
   Gold prices were sharply higher in response. Republic National
Bank of New York quoted a troy ounce of gold bullion at $377, up
$3.50 from late Friday.
   Currency traders said the dollar started out lower after a big
decline in Europe and Asia that was attributed in part to
profit-taking and reported intervention by the Bank of Japan.
   Many overseas traders also unloaded dollars following losses
suffered by Japan's ruling Liberal Democratic Party in the Tokyo
municipal elections.
   ``We really inherited the weak dollar when we came in this
morning,'' explained Trevor Woodland, a trader with Harris Trust &
Co. in Chicago. ``This was not a North American market move.''
   Woodland said concerns that the Federal Reserve will move toward
an easier credit stance due to a slowdown in the U.S. economy also
depressed the dollar.
   Trading, though, was very quiet, with many dealers getting an
early start on the Independence Day holiday on Tuesday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 1.45 Japanese yen to a closing 142.50 yen. It was
quoted lower at 141.25 yen in London, and at 141.25 yen in New York,
down from 143.82 yen late Friday.
   The dollar fell against the British pound. It cost $1.5775 to buy
one pound in London, more expensive than $1.5535 late Friday.
Sterling fetched $1.5775 in New York, up from $1.5530.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday,
included: 1.9295 West German marks, down from 1.9515; 1.6550 Swiss
francs, down from 1.6757; 1.1953 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1966;
6.5545 French francs, down from 6.6290; and 1,397.50 Italian lire,
down from 1,412.5.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday, included
: 1.9285 West German marks, down from 1.9510; 1.6537 Swiss francs,
down from 1.6728; 6.5485 French francs, down from 6.6200; 2.1775
Dutch guilders, down from 2.2020; 1.1945 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1980; and 1,400.50 Italian lire, down from 1,410.50.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery jumped to $381.10 a troy ounce from $374.60 late Friday.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $375.05 an ounce, up
from late Friday's $371.75. In Zurich, Switzerland, gold rose to
$374.35 an ounce from $371.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.73 to close at a bid of
$375.93 an ounce.
   Silver prices also gained ground. On New York's Comex, silver
bullion for current delivery settled at $5.230 a troy ounce, up from
$5.155 Friday. Silver rose in London to $5.20 an ounce from $5.14.
</TEXT>
