<FIRST>r f AM-India-Strike     07-03 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Strike,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Right-Wing Strike Paralyses Bombay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOMBAY, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Factories closed and the stock exchange was
deserted Monday as a strike called by right-wing groups to protest
Sikh extremism paralyzed this commercial capital of India, officials
said.
   At least three people died, rioters smashed buses and a bomb was
detected at a railroad station during the 18-hour strike called
throughout the Maharashtra state, news reports and police in the
state capital of Bombay said.
   The deaths occurred in Chikli, 230 miles west of Bombay, when
police opened fire on a rioting mob of about 5,000 right-wing
activists, state Police Chief S.V. Bhave told reporters.
   The strike was called to protest the June 25 killing of 26 Hindus
by Sikh extremists in Moga, a town in the northern Punjab state.
   The victims belonged to a Hindu fundamentalist organization
called the Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh, or the National Volunteer
Force, and were shot to death in a park as they practiced martial
exercises.
   The force was one of the organizers of Monday's strike that began
at midnight and ended at 6 p.m. local time. The other organizers
were the opposition Bharatiya Janata Party, or the Indian People's
Party, and the Shiv Sena or Shiva's Army, named after the Hindu god
of destruction.
   The Shiv Sena along with the National Volunteer Force has a
strong following in this Hindu-dominated western state that is
governed by Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi's Congress (I) party.
</TEXT>
