<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru, Bjt,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market, adrift in the midst of a long
summer holiday weekend, posted a modest gain Monday in the slowest
trading in more than 2{ years.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, down 91.81 points last
week, recovered 12.71 to 2,452.77.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 9 to 7 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
733 up, 587 down and 562 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 68.87 million
shares, down from 170.49 million Friday and the lightest total since
48.86 million were traded Dec. 26, 1986.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 80.56 million shares.
   Wall Street had expected a slow session, given the absence of
many market participants taking a long July 4 weekend. The markets
will be closed on Tuesday.
   That helped make it difficult for stocks to mount a rally from
last week's decline, which was the steepest in more than 15 months.
   Analysts said traders' thoughts had begun to focus more intently
of late on the chances that the economy might in for something worse
than the much-ballyhooed ``soft landing'' bullish forecasters have
been predicting.
   New evidence of softening business activity emerged Monday
morning from a monthly survey of corporate purchasing executives,
who reported the first drop in new orders since May of 1986.
   Gainers among the blue chips included International Business
Machines, up ] at 112\; Pfizer, up ] at 57}; Philip Morris, up { at
139[, and General Electric, up { at 52[.
   Airline issues climbed on continuing speculation about possible
new takeover bids in the industry. UAL gained 5 to 144{; AMR 1~ to
63, and Delta Air Lines { to 68].
   Another pocket of strength showed up in Japanese issues. TDK rose
2{ to 83; Matsushita Electric 3{ to 165, and Kyocera 4| to 86\.
   Minnetonka, traded in the over-the-counter market, fell 2| to
22]. The company agreed to be acquired by Unilever N.V. for $22.86 a
share, a price well below what some traders had been hoping for.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $9.48 billion, or 0.30
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks gained
.61 to 178.51.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index rose 1.34 to 364.82, and S&amp;P's
500-stock composite index was up 1.25 at 319.23.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market added
.71 to 436.00. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 358.83, down .14.
</TEXT>
