<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 2034EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Mexico-SeaFood     07-03 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Sea Food,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexican Official Complains About Foreign Sea Food</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cheap, badly labeled and inferior tuna and
other canned sea foods mostly from Thailand and Peru are flooding
the market, providing ``disloyal competition'' for Mexico's
fishermen and canners, a spokesman for the industry said Monday.
   Andres Armenta Gonzalez, president of the Chamber of Fishing
Industries, also complained in an interview with the Excelsior news
agency that new seafood farming in several nations and and cheap
fish meal from Peru are giving Mexican fisheries a rough time.
   Gonzalez said this year's sea catches are very good, with about
65,000 tons harvested up to now, and an estimated 150,000 projected
for the entire year.
   But he complained that canned tuna from Thailand and Peru comes
in to Mexico without proper labeling and, in some cases, is
unhygienically packed.
   Gonzalez also said products from seafood farms in China and
Ecuador, produced at lower costs, are tending to edge Mexican
sea-harvested items out of traditional markets.
   ``In addition to that, fish meal from Peru is entering this
country without any kind of quality control,'' he added. Fish meal
is used principally as feed for the poultry industry.
   Mexican industrialists have been complaining about foreign
competition ever since Mexico joined the General Agreement on
Tariffs and trade in 1986-87 and opened its doors to foreign imports.
</TEXT>
