<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 1823EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     07-03 0725</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0748</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coffee Futures Sink To 8-Year-Low On Collapse Of Price Supports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Coffee futures prices collapsed to an 8-year low Monday as the
International Coffee Organization suspended export quotas and
traders positioned themselves for an expected surge in available
supplies.
   ``I think it's a bonanza for the American consumer,'' said Bert
Ruiz, a vice president with the New York brokerage firm Balfour
Maclaine Corp., who predicted that wholesale prices of canned,
roasted coffee would drop by 20 cents a pound.
   On other markets, pork futures plunged their permitted daily
limits; corn and soybean futures rallied strongly; and precious
metals advanced.
   Oil futures were not traded Monday because the New York
Mercantile Exchange was closed for the Independence Day holiday. All
of the nation's commodity exchanges were scheduled to be closed on
Tuesday.
   Green, unroasted coffee settled 6 cents to 16.07 cents lower on
New York's Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa Exchange with the contract for
delivery in July at 97.63 cents a pound and the most active
contract, for September delivery, at 93.84 cents a pound. It was the
lowest close since mid-1981, when coffee futures sank as low as
80.50 cents a pound.
   The collapse was triggered by the International Coffee
Organization's decision to suspend quotas on exports of coffee from
its producer members to its consumer members. The decision came
after representatives of the 74 nations that comprise the
organization, meeting in London, failed to muster majority support
for either of two proposals for a new agreement to succeed the
6-year pact that expires Sept. 30.
   Both failed proposals would have retained a quota system for
stabilizing coffee prices. Instead, the group approved a 2-year
extension of the current agreement, minus the quotas, which will
keep the organization alive as a record-keeping body.
   The largest coffee-consuming nations, including the United
States, had opposed any new agreement that did not increase the
availability of high-quality arabica coffees. Consumer nations also
wanted tighter restrictions on sales of coffee at cut-rate prices to
countries that are not members of the organization.
   Quotas have been suspended twice before, for a total of 8{ years,
since the ICO was established in 1963. The most recent suspension,
which ended in October 1987, lasted about 1{ years.
   Ruiz said the suspension of quotas will increase the availability
of high-quality coffees at lower prices, citing indications that
some of the major South American and Central American coffee
producers are sitting on large stockpiles.
   But other analysts said the world coffee surplus could be much
smaller than some believe and that there was no reason to assume the
coffee market will soon be flooded.
   ``The market had a very hysterical reaction and it was mostly
speculative,'' said an analyst for a large trade house who asked not
to be named. ``I don't think it necessarily means anything.''
   Pork futures tumbled their permitted daily limits on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange in reaction to Friday's quarterly Agriculture
Department hogs-and-pigs report, which showed more animals than the
market had expected.
   Live cattle were .22 cent to .55 cent lower with August at 69.82
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .35 cent to .65 cent lower with
August at 80.35 cents a pound; live hogs were 1.50 cents lower
across the board with July at 47.17 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were 2 cents lower across the board with July at 33.85 cents
a pound.
   Corn and soybean futures surged on the Chicago Board of Trade
amid forecasts for an extended spell of hot, dry weather in the
Midwest.
   ``Some forecasters don't see any rain at all for the next week or
so,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds
Inc. in Chicago.
   Wheat settled 1 cent to 2} cents lower with July at $3.94{ a
bushel; corn was 4\ cents to 8} cents higher with July at $2.72 a
bushel; oats were 7{ cents to 8 cents higher with July at $1.57 a
bushel; soybeans were 5{ cents to 19 cents higher with July at
$7.40{ a bushel.
   Gold and silver futures posted strong gains on New York's
Commodity Exchange, largely in reaction to the weaker dollar.
   Gold settled $3.70 to $3.80 higher with August at $381.10 a troy
ounce; silver was 7.1 cents to 7.5 cents higher with July at $5.23 a
troy ounce.
</TEXT>
