<FILEID>AP-NR-07-03-89 1847EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Scotus-Cable     07-03 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Cable,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Court Refuses to Let Officials Regulate Cable TV Rates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Monday refused to let
officials in Burlington, Vt., regulate the rates a cable television
company charges customers in that city.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that federal law
barred the local officials from setting cable TV rates.
   Burlington officials in June 1985 signed a contract with Mountain
Cable Co. to provide cable service to city residents.
   Mountain Cable took over the city cable franchise after acquiring
the company that had provided the service. Burlington has had cable
TV service since the 1950s.
   City officials said the agreement between the city and Mountain
Cable barred the company from raising customer rates until Dec. 29,
1987.
   The company raised its monthly rate from $10.50 to $12.50 on Jan.
1, 1987.
   The Vermont Supreme Court ruled last year that a federal law that
took effect Oct. 30, 1984, barred the city from regulating cable TV
rates.
   Burlington officials said the federal law limiting local rate
regulation was aimed only at ``franchising authorities.''
   The city officials argued that a Vermont state agency, the Public
Service Board, had the power to award franchises. Therefore, they
said, the city should be free to control rates charged by Mountain
Cable.
   The state court said, ``While the city may be correct in arguing
that the Public Service Board is a franchising authority here, the
city is also a franchising authority within the meaning of the
(federal) act.''
   The case is Burlington vs. Mountain Cable, 88-1816.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
