<FIRST>r f BC-GNCBuyout 1stLd-Writethru f0267 07-03 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-GNC Buyout, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0267,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>General Nutrition Corp. Approves Buyout</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 8th graf, `Neither Lee ...,' to ADD closing
stock price.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Nutrition Corp., the nation's largest
health food and health products retailer, has agreed to be purchased
by a Boston-based investment firm for nearly $330 million, officials
said Monday.
   GNC's board of directors unanimously agreed to sell the company
to Thomas H. Lee Co. and its affiliate, ML-Lee Acquisition Fund
L.P., which specialize in leveraged buyouts.
   Officials said the cash tender offer calls for payment of $11.50
a share to the holders of 28.7 million shares, or 91.3 percent of
GNC's outstanding common stock, on or before Monday.
   The tender offer is to be followed by a merger in which remaining
common stock will be exchanged for preferred stock.
   GNC Chairman Jerry D. Horn said the company's management was
``extremely pleased'' by the deal.
   ``Our commitment to enhance shareholder value while providing
General Nutrition with a new, more growth-oriented investor base has
been realized,'' Horn said.
   Horn said the $11.50 tender price represents a 48 percent premium
over the market price of GNC stock on March 23, the day before GNC
said it was considering selling the company.
   Neither Lee nor GNC officials said how the sale would affect the
company's management or its operations, which include 1,100 stores
nationwide.
   GNC's shares rose 37.5 cents Monday to close at $10.75 on the New
York Stock Exchange.
   Thomas H. Lee and ML-Lee own or partly own Playtex Family
Products Co., Stanley Interiors Corp., National Shoes and American
Health Cos.
   GNC said it wanted to sell the company as an amicable way to
resolve differences between management, which wanted to expand the
company, and the family of late founder David Shakarian, which
controls 57 percent of the company's stock.
   One shareholder filed suit Monday in Allegheny County Common
Pleas Court to block the sale.
   Peter Stuyvesant Ltd., a Philadelphia investment group, claims
that the Thomas H. Lee offer is ``grossly unfair and inadequate''
and does not reflect the instrinsic value and growth potential of
GNC. No date has been set for the hearing on Stuyvesant's claim.
</TEXT>
